<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Buffett     05-27 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Buffett,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investor Warren Buffett Has Bit Part On ABC Soap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warren Buffett, a corporate takeover
specialist whose company holds a major stake in ABC television,
says he doesn't expect an award for his appearance as a bartender
in an episode of an ABC-TV soap opera.
   Buffett is joined in the scene for ``Loving'', scheduled to air
today, by the show's creator, Agnes Nixon, and Thomas Murphy,
chairman of apital Cities-ABC.
   ``They were wise. They didn't trust us with any dialogue,''
Buffett said Thursday.
   He said he has seen a tape of the show and wasn't too impressed
with his performance.
   ``For a town that produced Henry Fonda, Marlon Brando and Fred
Astaire, I'm a sad commentary, I'll tell you,'' he said.
   Buffett's Omaha-based company, Berkshire Hathaway Inc., is the
largest shareholder of Capital Cities-ABC Inc., which owns the
television network.
   The scene is set in a restaurant where Murphy plays a waiter and
Miss Nixon portrays a customer.
   During the scene, Buffett's bartender character and waiter
Murphy are summoned by a headwaiter to eject an unruly young woman
from the bar, Buffett said. None of the three cameo performers
spoke in the scene, he said.
   Buffett said he was invited to appear on ``Loving'' by Miss
Nixon, whom he met at a dinner party at the Winter Olympics in
Calgary.
</TEXT>
