<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama-Repression     05-27 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Repression,0870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Regime Intimidates Opposition With Beatings, Threats</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The regime of Gen. Manuel Noriega has
used detentions, beatings, threats and sexual harassment to
intimidate Panamanians and quell what appeared only a month ago to
be a rising wave of protest.
   Noriega doesn't have to resort to slayings or to arranging for
people to ``disappear,'' as has happened in some Latin American
dictatorships.
   Panamanians themselves are the first to admit they are
unaccustomed to violent abuse and are easily cowed by it.
   ``I took part in demonstrations until they detained me,'' said a
27-year-old lawyer, who asked not to be named for fear of
reprisals. She was released after a half hour, but not before being
insulted, threatened and fondled by policemen.
   ``We are not Nicaragua or El Salvador or Afghanistan. We don't
have violence in our blood,'' said Ivan Romero, secretary-general
of the opposition Christian Democratic Party.
   Romero was detained, interrogated and beaten May 5 when he
returned from the United States, where he had gone to take part in
a conference. He was expelled to Miami the next day and allowed to
return on Monday.
   ``There is a triumph of terror,'' he told The Associated Press
in an interview. ``The regime is waging psychological war, and it's
winning.''
   The Defense Forces, which includes police and armed forces and
is under Noriega's command, did not return repeated telephone calls
Thursday asking for a response to these allegations.
   Only three people have been killed in political violence since
the U.S.-backed opposition campaign to oust Noriega began 11 months
ago. There are no ``disappeared,'' the enigmatic status that
military regimes in South and Central America conferred on tens of
thousands of opponents in past decades.
   But there is a secret police, G-2, whose members have
demonstrated ruthlessness. The corps is informed by street spies
called ``toads'' whose pervasive infiltration of everyday life is
taken for granted.
   ``We're not fighters, but a folkloric people; beach, sun and
sea,'' said a young professional jailed and mistreated for a week
last month. ``I myself am that way. It's in our genes.''
   The man said he was suspected of opposition activity and taken
from his home after midnight by several agents to G-2 headquarters.
He was stripped and his wrists handcuffed behind his back.
   Asthmatic and frail, he was forced to stand under a cold shower
for half an hour, punched in the face and abdomen and beaten on the
legs with a rubber hose, he reported. Then he was beaten on the
toes with a blackjack, a pain he describes as ``terrible.''
   Still nude and handcuffed, as he was to remain for 15 hours, he
was thrown into a cell where he was told he would be raped by an
inmate.
   Panamanian rights activists say a sexual element to physical or
psychological abuse of detainees is common. They report that
arrested people are frequently threatened with rape or sodomy.
   The young man was not sexually abused, he said. But when he was
taken from the cell several hours later, he was blindfolded, his
mustache was burned with a lighter and the barrel of a revolver was
placed at his temple.
   ``They told me the cemetery was just down the road,'' he said.
   ``My life is the university, work and my girlfried,'' said the
man, who fears reprisal if his name appears in print. ``Those seven
days were like a parenthesis, a long nightmare.''
   ``The day after I got out, there was a (anti-government) march.
I did not even think about going,'' he said.
   ``Our security forces are more clever than the Argentines (of
the 1970s),'' said Alvin Weeden, a lawyer who in the past year has
represented dozens of people arrested on political charges. ``Fear
is stronger than cadavers. People get used to cadavers, but they
don't get used to fear.''
   He said that since a failed coup attempt in March, the
prevailing paranoia has spread to the Defense Forces. He said the
18 officers and soldiers under arrest in connection with the
attempt have been subjected to treatment as least as humiliating as
that given civilians.
   ``The officers know that if they cast a funny glance at Noriega
or one of his inner circle, they will be under surveillance
themselves,'' said Weeden.
   ``There's even more fear inside the armed forces than outside,''
he said.
   Except for the coup plotters, political detainees are rarely
held more than a few days or a week. Most are required to pay
between $150 and $350 for their freedom, though payments of up to
$10,000 have been reported.
   Opposition leaders and human rights activists call the payments
``ransoms.''
   Weeden thinks the lull in protest and street demonstrations is
passing, a valley to be followed by a surge.
   Romero said he came back to Panama even though his wife pleaded
with him by telephone not to.
   ``I'm showing my face and going ahead to help smash the
terror,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
