<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SirenSong     05-27 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Siren Song,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Professor's Dream Girl Plans To Move To Illinois</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 61-year-old college professor who fell in
love with a Scottish bank teller's machine-recorded voice soon will
get a chance to hear that voice live when the woman of his dreams
moves to his hometown.
   ``It sort of means reducing a fairy tale come true to reality,''
Dick Ferry said Thursday night. ``It could be losing some of its
magic to see her grocery shopping.''
   But actually, Ferry said, both he and his wife Carol are
delighted that Sally Masterson, a British radio talk-show host, has
accepted a job with a radio station in this central Illinois city
of about 94,000 residents.
   It's all because of a newspaper column Ferry wrote after he
heard a teller-machine recording with her voice.
   ``I think I'm in love with a woman I've never seen,'' Ferry
wrote in his Feb. 4 column for the Decatur Herald & Review
newspaper.
   ``My infatuation is with the talking teller at the Money Network
station at First National Bank downtown,'' he said.
   Intrigued, the newspaper tracked down Ms. Masterson, 30, now a
talk-show host in London, and arranged for her to visit Decatur
last month. She and Ferry met _ with Mrs. Ferry, his wife of 25
years, looking on.
   Ms. Masterson, who is single, had made the teller-machine
recording three years ago in Scotland for NCR Corp. of Dayton,
Ohio, which makes automatic-teller products.
   ``I think he's smashing,'' she said, after meeting Ferry, an
education professor at Millikin University.
   For his part, Ferry said that what began as a romantic fling in
a newspaper column has become a friendship.
   ``I said I was in love with a voice _ and I was,'' Ferry said.
``But I'm in love with my wife. I would hope that Sally is a good
friend.
   ``I don't really expect her to stay in Decatur. I think her
voice is so impelling that she will get offers and offers.''
   Ms. Masterson told the Herald & Review earlier this week that
she has accepted a broadcast job with WDZ radio and will arrive
Sept. 5.
   David Webb, vice president and general manager of WDZ, said he
began talking with Ms. Masterson about the job soon after she made
a guest appearance during her April visit.
   He said Ms. Masterson will have a midday show Monday through
Friday, with the format still to be worked out.
</TEXT>
