<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MoscowPoll     05-27 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moscow Poll,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Finds Soviet Union Residents Unsure Of Effects Of Economic
Changes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Muscovites give Mikhail S. Gorbachev strong
support for his overall program of change in their country, but
only about half say they have seen tangible benefits of his program
of economic change, a poll has found.
   Only 40 percent of participants in a poll conducted for The New
York Times and CBS News said they expected their families' standard
of living to improve in the next five years, according to the poll
published in Friday's Times.
   And 18 percent of 939 adults in Moscow households with
telephones predicted their standard of living would worsen, the
poll said. An estimated 84 percent of Moscow households have phones.
   The margin of error for the poll was plus or minus 4 percentage
points.
   The poll found strong support for Gorbachev's overall program,
with 78 percent supporting his domestic policies completely and 19
percent less than completely. The Times said they especially liked
his calls for greater democracy and openness.
   The newspaper said one of the poll's most striking findings was
that a sizable minority seemed prepared to question the monopoly of
the Communist Party. While 51 percent agreed that the one-party
system in their country promotes development of democracy, 28
percent said they disagreed, the poll found.
   It also said many wanted the liberalization that had begun to be
expanded to include competitive elections, private publishing and
tolerance of public demonstrations.
   The interviews in Moscow were conducted by The Institute of
Sociological Research of the Soviet Academy of Sciences on May 7,
8, 14 and 15.
</TEXT>
