<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reapportionment     05-27 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reapportionment,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds Threaten Discrimination Suit Over LA County Supervisors'
Districts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials plan to sue Los Angeles
County for violating the voting rights of racial minorities by
diluting their influence when county supervisors redrew district
boundaries in 1981, a source said Thursday.
   Assistant Attorney General William Bradford Reynolds informed
the county by letter last week that he authorized the Justice
Department to sue the county for allegedly discriminating against
minorities in the 1981 reapportionment, said the source, who is
familiar with the case but asked not to be identified.
   The Board of Supervisors must remap its five districts every
decade and to divide the population evenly among them. But the 1981
plan allegedly diluted the influence of Hispanics and other
minorities, the source added.
   County Counsel DeWitt Clinton was called for comment Thursday,
but didn't immediately return the call.
   There has not been a Hispanic supervisor in Los Angeles County's
138-year history. The county's only black supervisor, Yvonne
Brathwaite Burke, was appointed to the board in the 1970s and
subsequently lost a bid for election.
   According to the 1980 federal census, there were more than 2
million Hispanics and 943,000 blacks among the county's 7.5 million
residents. By 1985 there were 2.4 million Hispanics and 964,000
blacks, according to projections by the county Department of Health
Services.
   Justice Department spokeswoman Deborah Burstion-Wade confirmed
Reynolds, who heads the Justice Department's civil rights division,
sent a letter to the county last week, but said she couldn't
comment on its contents.
   In voting rights cases, such letters are sent to allow the
target of a potential lawsuit to negotiate with the Justice
Department and ``avoid the cost and time of litigation, which
doesn't help anybody,'' she said by phone from Washington.
``However, if statutory violations cannot be resolved, then
certainly litigation is a real possibility.''
   Asked what kind of relief the government seeks in such cases,
Ms. Burstion-Wade replied: ``The relief would be to protect
minorities from disenfranchisement.''
   Raul Nunez, president of the Los Angeles County Chicano
Employees Association, said he understood the federal complaint
against the county would involve alleged discrimination against
Hispanics.
   ``We have always felt that the Latino community has been without
power in that they have been fragmented, and they have not been
able to exercise their voting ability,'' Nunez said.
   ``We are aware that county counsel has received a letter from
the Department of Justice,'' Deane Dana, chairman of the Board of
Supervisors, said in a statement. ``He is reviewing it and will be
advising the board. Until that process is complete, we will not
have any comment beyond that.''
   Bradford's letter first was revealed publicly in Thursday
editions of the Los Angeles Times, which cited anonymous sources.
   The Justice Department filed a similar lawsuit in 1985 that
forced the Los Angeles City Council to shift a district from the
San Fernando Valley to the city's largely Hispanic east side. The
suit led to the election to the City Council of former
Assemblywoman Gloria Molina.
   The Justice Department based its 1985 complaint on the 1965
Voting Rights Act, which prohibits redistricting that causes
minority residents to have ``less opportunity than other members
(of the community) to participate in the political process and to
elect representatives of their choice.''
   The lawsuit claimed that the city's 1982 plan splintered the
political influence of Hispanics by spreading them thinly over many
districts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
