<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--NavyCrash     05-27 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Navy Crash,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Instructors Safely Eject From Navy Jet That Crashed in Woods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GROVE HILL, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two flight instructors escaped serious
injury when they ejected and parachuted from a TA4J Skyhawk Navy
training jet that crashed and burned Thursday in a forest,
authorities said.
   Marine Capt. Thomas Henry Renken and Navy Lt. j.g. Timothy John
Roorda were picked up by a search helicopter and returned safely to
base, said Lt. j.g. Mary Chamberlin, spokeswoman for the Meridian
Naval Air Station in Mississippi.
   Roorda was being examined for a possible broken leg.
   Chamberlin said the jet, based at Meridian, Miss., was on a
routine training mission and crashed 11:45 a.m. Thursday in the
Scotch Wildlife Management area in southwest Alabama, 13 miles west
of Grove Hill.
   The crash sparked a wildfire near Alabama Highway 154 that was
fought by state forestry fire crews. Law-enforcement agencies
closed off the area pending an investigation of the crash by
military and federal authorities.
   There were no other injuries.
</TEXT>
