<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AcidRain     05-27 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Acid Rain,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Scientists Plan Acid Rain Study in Illinois</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government scientists are planning to spend a
month studying the skies over Illinois to learn how much effect
summer storms have on acid rain.
   The project, which will start on June 1 and continue for four
weeks, will use both radar and airborne measurements to see how
long and how far storms carry pollutants, said William J. Brennan
of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
   ``If you're going to get a handle on pollutants that are put
into the atmosphere and what their impact will be downwind, you
have to know what happens to them aloft,'' Brennan said Thursday.
   ``How much of the pollutants fall out within a 10- or 20- or
50-mile range of the source?'' he asked. ``How much of it gets
carried aloft and moved further along? What are the conditions that
cause it to either fall out early on or get carried along for some
distance? A scientist always has to know why.''
   Brennan said that the study being undertaken by his agency, the
Department of Energy, federal research laboratories, several
universities and the Illinois Water Survey will provide ``a body of
knowledge from which the policymakers can reach decisions on acid
rain.''
   During the four-week study based at Willard Field in Champaign,
Ill., one team of scientists will use flying laboratories to see
how storms redistribute pollutants, while another team will use a
new radar technique to observe the movement of pollution in the
troposphere, seven to 10 miles above the ground, Brennan said.
   He said a team from the oceanic and atmospheric administration's
Aeronomy Laboratory in Boulder, Colo., will be conducting a related
study to test two kinds of Doppler radars, one for monitoring
upper-level winds and the other for winds near the surface.
   At the same time, the Illinois Water Survey will use its
rainfall-collection network to determine how much pollution is
contained in rainfall from local storms.
</TEXT>
