<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HousingVouchers     05-27 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Housing Vouchers,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rent Voucher Program to Be Extended to Rural Families</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some rural families will soon be able to take
advantage of a federal program that is helping 110,000 urban
residents pay their rent, sometimes with cash left over for the
renter.
   Housing and Urban Development Secretary Samuel R. Pierce
announced Thursday that HUD's housing voucher program was being
extended into 50 public housing districts in 13 states.
   Initially, the program will aid only 2,178 rural families, but
officials say they hope it can be expanded to other housing
districts and states. HUD has asked for funding to issue an
additional 100,000 vouchers in fiscal 1989.
   The largest numbers of rural vouchers will be available in
Kentucky, Mississippi, Missouri and Michigan, according to Pierce's
announcement.
   James Schoenberger, deputy federal housing commissioner, said
areas in those states and in nine others were chosen because they
had public housing authorities that appear most ready to set up the
rural programs in cooperation with the Farmers Home Administration.
   The voucher program, which began as an experimental alternative
to public housing in 1984, became permanent under a law signed by
President Reagan earlier this year.
   Qualified low-income families may be given housing vouchers
worth the difference between 30 percent of their family income and
the local ``payment standard'' for adequate housing in the area
where they live. Officials said that HUD expects to be funding more
single-family dwellings in rural communities than it does in
cities, where most recipients live in apartments.
   The program contains what HUD officials call a ``shopping
incentive,'' allowing renters to rent whatever kind of housing they
want, rather than limiting them to public housing projects.
   ``We think it's a program with a great amount of sensitivity to
it,'' Schoenberger said.
   He said that the vouchers allow people to receive aid without
subjecting themselves to the social problems that often plague
public housing projects.
   In a typical situation under either the rural or urban programs:
   A family might be earning $10,000 a year, meaning that it would
be expected to pay 30 percent of its income or $3,000 in rent. If
HUD determines the ``payment standard'' for an adequate unit for
the family to be $5,000, the family would receive vouchers worth
$2,000 a year.
   Recipients then can decide whether they want to pay $5,000 and
use all of the voucher, stay in a $3,000 unit and use the
additional funds for other needs, or pay more than $5,000 to
further improve their lifestyle.
   In public housing, renters don't see any of the assistance given
by the government. Under the voucher program, an arrangement can be
made to return money to the renters if they can find a unit that
rents for less than the subsidy.
   Schoenberger said that there already may be a line of applicants
for the rural vouchers in some housing authorites, but in others,
there could be an ``opportunity to pretty much walk into the door
and take advantage of it.''
   Under the program, select Mississippi housing authorities will
assist 441 famlies; Kentucky, 422 families; Missouri, 380;
Michigan, 225; and Georgia, 130. New Hampshire, Vermont, Oklahoma
and Washington will each be allowed 100 vouchers, while Montana,
North Dakota and Idaho will each serve 50 rural families, and
Louisiana will help 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0039 </DOCNO>
