<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hastings-Impeach     05-27 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hastings-Impeach,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Asserts That Impeachment Hearings Raise No New Points</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge Alcee L. Hastings said he
remains confident that a House subcommittee will refuse to
recommend that he be impeached on charges of conspiring to solicit
a bribe.
   On Thursday, at the end of five days of hearings before the
House Judiciary subcommittee on criminal justice, Hastings said:
``I haven't heard anything new so far. These are old charges. They
all came up in my trial.''
   Asked how he would assess the hearings to date, Hastings
replied: ``Hastings five, Congress nothing.''
   The subcommittee hearings will continue next Wednesday.
   Hastings, who still sits on the federal bench in Miami, has been
accused by an investigative panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Atlanta of taking part in a bribery scheme with his
close friend, Washington lawyer William A. Borders.
   Borders was convicted in 1982 of arranging a $150,000 bribe for
Hastings from two Miami racketeers, Frank and Tom Romano, in
exchange for a promise of lenient sentences. One year later, a
separate trial jury acquitted Hastings of conspiring with Borders
to solicit a bribe from the Romano brothers.
   Hastings is also charged with compromising an FBI investigation
into zoning code corruption in the Miami area in 1985.
   Earlier, FBI agent William J. Murphy Jr., who directed the
Hastings-Borders investigation, testified at Thursday's
subcommittee hearing
   that Hastings was a target from the beginning of the probe.
   Murphy also said that Hastings and Borders weren't illegally
lured into taking the bribe even though an undercover FBI agent
gave $120,000 to Borders before he was arrested on Oct. 9, 1981.
   Murphy said the FBI began the investigation after an informant,
William Dredge, had bragged that he controlled several judges,
including Hastings and another federal jurist who was not
identified.
   He said the undercover operation took place because ``we were
only trying to prove or disprove what (Dredge) said.''
   In answer to a question, Murphy said Hastings ``was a target
from the outset. His name was mentioned by Borders. We tried to
prove or disprove the allegation and it turned out to be true.''
   Rep. Patrick L. Swindall, R-Ga., said that the FBI's undercover
operation appeared to him to be ``a classic, textbook entrapment.''
   Saying he was not an attorney, Murphy replied that he did not
believe it was entrapment. He said the operation ``was a tool to
respond to (Dredge's) allegations. If Borders didn't show up at the
meeting and didn't say the things he did, the case would have
stopped.
   ``The information we were trying to prove or disprove was that
Borders and Judge Hastings were going to do a crime,'' Murphy said.
``We didn't decide one day in the office to get Judge Hastings.''
</TEXT>
