<DOCNO> AP880527-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ZeroTolerance     05-27 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zero Tolerance,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Members Lash Out at `Zero Tolerance' Drug Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the U.S. Customs Service blames
the public outcry over the new federal ``zero tolerance'' anti-drug
policy on wealthy Americans whose boats are being seized by the
government.
   Customs Commissioner William von Raab, in his first appearance
before Congress since the policy began, said Thursday that seizures
of vessels at sea after discoveries of miniscule amounts of illegal
drugs were affecting ``arrogant stock brokers and smooth lawyers
who think they're above the law.''
   Von Raab told members of the House Coast Guard and navigation
subcommittee that complaints were coming from ``rich people who
have a lot of pull with the media, who have a lot of pull with
Congress.''
   The policy, he said, ``is supported by the American people.''
   Joining von Raab was Admiral Paul A. Yost Jr., commandant of the
Coast Guard, who disputed lawmakers' complaints that his service
was squandering money from its already tight budget.
   Yost told the legislators that the arrests and seizures were
occurring only during routine patrols and inspections, saying, ``I
am not wasting resources in this policy.''
   Most members of the subcommittee, however, rejected the
officials' claims and insisted that zero tolerance was a case of an
overzealous government going too far.
   ``In the minds of the public, this is a government policy gone
awry,'' said Rep. Robert W. Davis of Michigan, the panel's ranking
Republican. ``It symbolizes unfairness.''
   The subcommittee's chairman, Rep. Earl Hutto, D-Fla., was one of
several lawmakers who complained that the seizure of fishing boats
after crewmen were found to have tiny amounts of drugs was
depriving innocent owners of a means to earn a living.
   ``Innocent persons are being hurt more than users,'' he said.
   Some members of the panel engaged von Raab in heated exchanges.
   Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, complained to the Customs official
about a small boat seized in Alaska after paraphernalia such as
rolling paper and rolling machines were discovered.
   Young said that such implements could be perfectly innocent and
told von Raab, ``You're not helping the cause here at all. In fact,
you're hurting it.''
   Under the policy, Customs and Coast Guard officers finding small
amounts of illegal drugs during searches conducted at sea have
begun arresting people and seizing boats.
   The new procedures have resulted in the temporary seizure of
such boats as the Atlantis II, owned by the Woods Hole
Oceanographic Institution of Massachusetts, after a crewman was
found to have a tiny amount of marijuana.
   In addition, the $2.5 million yacht Ark Royal and the Monkey
Business _ the pleasure boat that former presidential candidate
Gary Hart sailed on with model Donna Rice _ were seized after small
quantities of drugs were discovered.
   Under new guidelines issued late last week, authorities finding
small amounts of drugs on board vessels beyond the 12-mile limit
now are seizing boats only if they appear to be involved in
transporting drugs into the country.
   Some lawmakers defended the policy.
   Rep. Wally Herger, R-Calif., conceded that zero tolerance needs
adjustments but said he believed the policy is sound.
   Rep. Bob Clement, D-Tenn., said, ``My constituents want a tough
policy, and that policy is that no amount of drugs is OK.''
   Von Raab said that the Customs Service has made 1,500 seizures _
mostly of automobiles crossing into the United States _ since zero
tolerance took effect. Yost said 44 boats have so far been seized,
13 of which have already been released.
   The Customs Service implemented the policy on March 21, and the
Coast Guard followed suit on April 11.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
