<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ContraAid     05-27 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Aid,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House GOP Rebuffed in Effort to Renew Military Aid to Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republicans staged a legislative ambush
in an attempt to renew military aid to Nicaragua's Contra rebels,
but were rebuffed amid fears that such a move would upset delicate
negotiations in Managua.
   In a surprise move, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., sought Thursday to
amend an intelligence bill to permit President Reagan to dip into
the CIA's contingency fund to finance future covert military aid to
the rebels. The measure was defeated, 214-190.
   Since 1983, the law authorizing intelligence operations has
contained a prohibition on use of the spy agency's contingency fund
to buy weapons and other supplies for the Contras. The ban was
imposed after lawmakers became angered at the CIA's role in aiding
the Nicaraguan war.
   Hyde's amendment would have dropped the prohibition from the
law. At present, the rebels can receive only humanitarian aid _
food, clothing and medicine _ from the United States under a $17.7
million program approved by Congress earlier this year.
   Proponents of the move argued that things have gone badly for
the rebels since Congress voted earlier this year to end military
aid. The two sides are nearing the end of a two-month truce agreed
to during talks at Sapoa, Nicaragua.
   The Contra supporters said that the Nicaraguan government has
taken advantage of the cease-fire to weaken the rebels and has
failed to live up to promises made in a regional peace accord
reached last year. Instead, they argued, the Sandinistas have
harassed peaceful anti-government demonstrators, arrested labor
leaders and denied press freedom.
   Giving Reagan the power to resume covert military aid any time
after Oct. 1 would add pressure for the Managua regime to release
political prisoners, restore civil liberties and hold free
elections, supporters of the amendment argued.
   Opponents of the move noted that a new round of negotiations
between the two warring sides was taking place in Managua and said
that there was still hope that a lasting peace could be achieved.
   ``I cannot think of a more pernicious, ill-timed amendment,''
said Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich. ``At the very minute that the
Contras, who have struggled for three weeks to put their own act
together, ... meet with the government of Nicaragua, an amendment
is offered to put the CIA back into this war.''
   In another attempt to pressure the Sandinistas, a group of
conservative lawmakers announced plans to seek new military aid for
the rebels if the Managua government fails to meet its obligations
under the peace accord by the time the formal truce ends on May 31.
   Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., while declining to give precise figures,
said the package would include substantial military and
humanitarian aid, sufficient to last the Contras a year to 18
months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Gore-Veep     05-27 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gore-Veep,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Would Bring Southern Strength To Democratic Ticket</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One in a series of occasional profiles of vice presidential
prospects.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. remains on the
list of possible Democratic candidates for the vice presidency
despite calling the job a ``political dead end'' when he was
seeking the No. 1 spot on the ticket.
   Gore's prospects of joining the ticket declined in the
estimation of some Democrats as a result of his attacks on both
Jesse Jackson and Michael Dukakis in the final weeks of his
presidential campaign.
   He would bring to the ticket, however, credentials as a
Southerner with proven popularity in the region.
   Gore ended his 1988 presidential hopes after the New York
primary in April, his campaign a failure outside of the region-wide
victories in the Super Tuesday primaries.
   At 40 the youngest of the potential vice presidential nominees,
Gore remains in the speculation in part because of those Southern
successes.
   Some observers contend that Dukakis, the likely Democratic
presidential nominee, needs a Southerner on the ticket if he is to
carry any states in the region that is often crucial to Democratic
electoral strategy. Other Southerners getting frequent mention are
Sens. Sam Nunn of Georgia, Bob Graham of Florida and Lloyd Bentsen
of Texas.
   Gore insisted throughout his campaign that he had no interest in
the No. 2 job. He did not flatly rule it out, however.
   ``I have no interest in it _ might very well turn it down,
indeed, and probably would,'' he said once.
   ``I think Vice President Bush will demonstrate again this year
that it is a political dead end,'' Gore said.
   Gore met privately with Dukakis recently. Dukakis insists he is
not considering the selection of a running mate until he has
collected a majority of convention delegates.
   Gore has nearly 400 Democratic National Convention delegates. He
has asked them to remain committed to him, but he has been losing
delegates nearly daily to Dukakis.
   When his presidential hopes reached a stage of desperation, Gore
turned up his attacks on Dukakis and accused him of foreign-policy
blunders born of inexperience and lack of knowledge.
   He turned attacks on Jackson, too, on foreign policy _ and
blasted Dukakis as ``afraid to say a single word about Jesse
Jackson.''
   New York Mayor Edward Koch backed Gore and picked up the
criticism of Jackson with a vengeance. Gore aides were dismayed by
Koch's attacks. Even Gore seemed to cringe, although he did not
take public issue with his newfound supporter.
   Gore is the son of a veteran Tennessee politician, Albert Gore
Sr., who spent 32 years in the House and Senate before losing his
seat in 1970, with his opposition to the Vietnam War an issue. Gore
Jr. enlisted in the Army and served in Vietnam.
   He was born and educated in Washington, D.C., attending the
elite St. Albans prep school and then Harvard. His wife, Tipper,
was a high school sweetheart, and she has become well-known in her
own right for leading public crusades against violent and sexually
explicit lyrics in music aimed at young people.
   Gore worked as a newspaper reporter in Nashville, Tenn., and
entered both divinity school and law school, not completing either.
He quit law school after two years when the House seat his father
once held came open, and won election in 1976.
   He won election to the Senate in 1984, when Republican Howard
Baker declined to run again.
   Although he has a congressional voting record decidedly more
liberal than some of Tennessee's other members of Congress, Gore
positioned himself in the presidential race to the right of most
other Democratic contenders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
