<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-Cooper     05-27 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Cooper,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Justice Official Reportedly Leaving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Another adviser to Attorney General Edwin
Meese III is about to leave his Justice Department post, according
to a published report. Meanwhile, a majority of people surveyed in
a new poll say they have a negative impression of the attorney
general.
   Assistant Attorney General Charles J. Cooper is talking with
private law firms and is expected to announce his resignation
before independent counsel James C. McKay issues a report on his
yearlong criminal investigation of Meese's financial dealings, The
Washington Post reported in Friday's editions. McKay is expected to
release his report within the next few weeks.
   Cooper played a leading role in the unsuccessful efforts to win
confirmation of Robert H. Bork to the U.S. Supreme Court and was
among a small group of trusted aides who helped Meese investigate
the Iran-Contra affair in November 1986.
   Two other top department officials, Deputy Attorney General
Arnold Burns and criminal division chief William Weld, quit
recently out of concern that Meese's continued tenure was hurting
the department's operations, morale and public image.
   The Post, which quoted unidentified sources, said that Cooper
did not return repeated telephone calls on Thursday seeking
comment. But the newspaper quoted Justice Department spokesman
Patrick Korten as saying that if Cooper were leaving, ``it would
scarcely be unusual at this point in the administration.''
   ``Take a look around at a dozen Cabinet agencies around town,
and you will find a number of presidential appointees have already
departed for the private sector,'' Korten said, adding that he had
``no knowledge of what Chuck's plans are.''
   Meese told a gathering of conservative congressmen on Wednesday
that McKay's report ``will clear him completely,'' said Rep. Cass
Ballenger, R-N.C., who attended the meeting.
   The report is expected to raise questions about Meese's ethical
behavior.
   Meanwhile, a Washington Post-ABC News Poll released Thursday
found that 51 percent of those surveyed had an unfavorable
impression of Meese and only 9 percent had a favorable impression,
with 40 percent expressing no opinion.
   In addition, 38 percent said that he should resign, while 9
percent said he should not and 54 percent expressed no opinion on
the matter.
   The poll was based on telephone interviews conducted May 19 to
26 with 1,508 randomly selected adults. The margin of error was
plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</TEXT>
