<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Sikhs     05-27 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Dead In Blast, Indian Government Bans Use Of Shrines By
Extremists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Indian laborers died today of
injuries suffered when a bomb went off in a crowded market in
Punjab, a northern Indian state racked by Sikh separatist violence.
   In another development, the federal government issued an
ordinance banning the use of temples and shrines for political
activity or the harboring of wanted criminals.
   President Ramaswami Venkataraman issued the ordinance on
Thursday, aimed at ending Sikh extremists' use of the Golden Temple
in Amritsar as a base for their separatist activities.
   The bomb, apparently hidden in a rickshaw, went off Thursday
night in the town of Phagwara in Karpurthala District, east of
Amritsar.
   The Press Trust of India news agency said 30 people were
injured, most of them laborers from nearby work camps. The news
agency said three of the victims were in serious condition at local
hospitals.
   It quoted police as saying the bombing was the work of the
Barbar Khalsa gang, one of a dozen Sikh extremist groups operating
in Punjab state. The news agency quoted District Police Chief
Swaran Singh as saying police raided a number of the radicals'
hideouts in a search for the bombers.
   Sikh radicals, who have been waging a guerrilla war for an
independent homeland in Punjab since 1982, recently stepped up
attacks on Hindu migrant workers in Punjab.
   Government officials say that one-third of the estimated 700,000
Hindu migrants have fled to their homes in eastern India,
threatening to undermine Punjab's agricultural economy.
   The new ordinance was described by the Times of India newspaper
as ``the first step toward separation of religion from politics.''
   Legislation to make the rule permanent will be introduced in the
next session of Parliament, government officials said. Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi's governing Congress Party has a majority in
both houses of Parliament, and the legislation is expected to be
enacted quickly.
   Violations will be punishable by imprisonment of up to five
years or a $770 fine.
   The ordinance was announced after the Sikh committee of elders
that governs the Golden Temple and other Sikh shrines said it could
not cooperate with police in keeping the sites free of extremists.
   Police and paramilitary troops have maintained a cordon around
the Golden Temple since May 9, when Sikh radicals inside the shrine
fired on police inspectors outside its walls.
   A siege ended May 18 with the surrender of the last of about 200
Sikh extremists and sympathizers from the shrine. Forty-six deaths
were reported during the confrontation, most of them Sikh militants.
   The Indian Express newspaper reported today that the government
has decided to go ahead with a plan to tear down scores of shops
and homes close to the shrine. The creation of a ``security
corridor'' would improve the ability of police to patrol around the
complex and prevent extremists from entering through numerous
alleys around it.
   Sikh militants have killed more than 1,170 people in Punjab this
year in hit-and-run attacks. Last year, 1,030 people died.
   Sikhs, whose religion was formed 500 years ago as an alternative
to Hinduism and Islam, claim they are discriminated against by
India's majority Hindus. Sikhs make up less than 2 percent of
India's 800 million population but are a majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
