<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NorthernIreland     05-27 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Plans Talks On Northern Ireland; Protestant Given Life
Terms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
indicated it wants to talk with Northern Ireland's main political
parties about returning some local control to the province.
   Strife-torn Northern Ireland has been administered directly from
London since Britain suspended the provincial parliament there in
March 1972 because of sharp differences between the majority
Protestant and minority Roman Catholic communities.
   In Belfast, meanwhile, a deputy commander of an outlawed
Protestant paramilitary group was sentenced Thursday to three life
terms in prison after confessing to three murders and 41 other
terrorist crimes.
   Lord Justice MacDermott sentenced Denis McClean, 40, and said
the defendant had pleaded guilty to terrorist crimes that could
never have been proved if he had not confessed to police.
   In London, the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, Tom
King, said in a statement Thursday night that he would consider
further how progress might be made towards giving some power back
to Northern Ireland's provincial authorities.
   The announcement by King, the Cabinet member responsible for the
province, followed a series of separate talks in recent months
involving him and political leaders from Northern Ireland.
   Earlier Thursday, King met with the province's two main
Protestant politicians, James Molyneaux and the Rev. Ian Paisley.
   Molyneaux is leader of the Official Unionist Party. Paisley is
leader of the Democratic Unionist Party.
   The liberal British newspaper The Guardian said Molyneaux and
Paisley had agreed to talks with Northern Ireland's moderate
Catholic Social Democratic and Labor Party.
   The Guardian said however that it has yet to be seen whether the
Social Democratic and Labor Party wants to talk with the
Protestants.
   In Belfast Crown Court, Judge MacDermott said he believed
McClean, a leader of the outlawed Ulster Volunteer Force, had
confessed because he wanted to clear his conscience.
   In addition to the murders, the charges for which McClean was
convicted included manslaughter of a policewoman, six attempted
murders, bomb making, causing explosions and illegal possession of
guns.
   The prosecution said McClean's first victim was a 62-year-old
Protestant, William Wallace, who died during a gun and bomb attack
on a Belfast bar in 1973.
   McClean had admitted in a written confession to police that he
and two other men attacked the bar because it was owned by a Roman
Catholic.
   McClean's two other murder victims, killed in random attacks
against Catholic targets, were a 45-year-old taxi driver in 1984,
and a 30-year-old hospital chef last year. Both were Catholics.
   The policewoman died while on patrol in 1975 in a bomb attack at
a bar at the east coast resort of Bangor.
</TEXT>
