<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Leadership Ties Foreign Policy Position To Black Vote In
November</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of black leaders is warning
Democratic presidential front-runner Michael Dukakis that the
``price'' for him to win black votes in the November general
election is his backing of ``stringent and comprehensive''
sanctions against South Africa.
   A 28-page report released by the coalition called for Dukakis to
support the sanctions as well as recognize the Marxist government
in Angola and to end aid to the South African-supported rebel group
UNITA in Angola.
   ``The Democratic Party can lose with our support, (but) they
cannot win without it,'' said Randall Robinson, head of the
anti-apartheid group TransAfrica, in making the announcement
Thursday. ``So all those who turned out in the black community for
the primary must turn out for Michael Dukakis if he has any chance
of the White House. There is a price for that turnout.''
   The report was authored and supported by the Congressional Black
Caucus, the Martin Luther King Jr. Center for Nonviolent Social
Change, the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People, the National Council of Negro Women and the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference.
</TEXT>
