<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BullRampage     05-27 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bull Rampage,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bull Killed After Terrorizing Residents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOXAHATCHEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 1,500-pound bull terrorized residents
for over two hours, flipping a dog, charging cars and an air
conditioner and scattering backyard items before being shot and
killed, witnesses and police said.
   ``The animal was highly agitated. It was intense negotiations
from behind the car, I'll tell you that,'' said sheriff's Sgt. Greg
Wyble.
   The black-and-white Holstein, who jumped a fence for the second
time after it gored a cow to death about a week ago, went on a
rampage Wednesday.
   Susan Shelley said the bull chased her inside and then came
right up to her front door.
   ``He was pawing the ground and snorting. I was waiting for it to
plow through at any time,'' she said. ``I had six kids in the house
who were crying.''
   Ms. Shelley said the bull flipped a neighbor's dog through the
air but didn't hurt it.
   ``It scared the life out of everybody. There were people in
their houses with loaded guns. They didn't know what it would do
next,'' she said.
   The bull ripped through hedges, dented a car and a truck, tore
down clotheslines and scattered boats, barbecue grills and lawn
furniture, witnesses said.
   ``One of the neighbors told me the bull was looking at its
reflection in a sliding glass door. And when a nearby
air-conditioner compressor came on, he got startled and rammed the
air conditioner with his head,'' Wyble said.
   The bull also attacked a sheriff's patrol car, although no
damage was reported, Wyble said.
   Deputies used food to try to entice the animal into a nearby
pasture, and county animal control officers tried to corral the
bull for more than two hours to no avail, Wyble said.
   With the approval of Animal Control Division Director Dennis
Moore, a deputy fired four 12-gauge shotgun slugs into the animal's
head, killing it, Wyble said.
   Moore said the bull had earlier caused problems but had been
lured back into a fenced-in pasture. It jumped the fence again
before entering the residential area here west of Palm Beach and
was shot in the backyard of a home.
   ``We tried everything we could, but in the end it came down to a
matter of public safety,'' Moore said.
   The animal was owned by Jose Castillo, who neighbors said is out
of the country.
</TEXT>
