<1ST_LINE>r w BC-Summit-Schedule     05-27 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Summit-Schedule,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President's Summit Schedule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the schedule for President Reagan's
trip to Finland and Moscow and his fourth summit with Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Finland is seven hours ahead of Eastern Daylight Time, and
Moscow is eight hours ahead.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 27 _ Arrival ceremony with President and Mrs. Mauno
Koivisto, followed by luncheon at the palace. Speech at Finlandia
Hall, dealing with the summit agenda and human rights.
   May 28 _ Release of pre-taped weekly radio address, dealing with
the summit.
   May 29 _ Departure for Moscow, arriving around 2 p.m. local time
at Vnukova airport. Reagan holds first meeting with Gorbachev at
the Kremlin, followed by private evening at the Spaso House, the
U.S. ambassadorial residence where the president will stay.
   May 30 _ Second official summit meeting at Kremlin. Early
afternoon, Reagan will visit the Danilov Monastery on the outskirts
of Moscow ``to symbolize our concern for religious freedom,''
according to Fitzwater.
   Late afternoon meeting at Spaso House with Soviet dissidents and
refuseniks, discussing freedom of speech, press and emigration.
   Gorbachev will host an official state dinner in the Hall of
Facets at the Kremlin.
   May 31 _ Third meeting with Gorbachev, followed by Reagan trip
to the House of Writers for talks with poets, artists, film makers
and intellectuals to discuss artistic freedom.
   Afternoon, Reagan delivers speech at Moscow University on
U.S.-Soviet relations, followed by question-and-answer session.
   Separately, the president's wife, Nancy, will fly to Leningrad
for the day on her own schedule.
   Evening, Reagan gives reciprocal dinner for Gorbachev, beginning
at 8 p.m.
   June 1 _ Fourth meeting with Gorbachev at the Kremlin, after
which time has been allotted for a signing ceremony.
   Reagan news conference at Spaso House at 4 p.m.
   Evening, the Reagans will accompany Gorbachev and his wife,
Raisa, to a special ballet presentation by the Bolshoi Theater.
Afterward, the Reagans will join the Gorbachevs at a private dinner
at a dacha outside Moscow.
   June 2 _ Reagan meets with embassy personnel at Spaso House in
the morning, and then has farewell meeting with Gorbachev at the
Kremlin.
   Official departure ceremony at the airport at 10:45 a.m., with
Air Force One taking off about 11:30 a.m.
   Arrival in London, followed by afternoon tea with Queen
Elizabeth at Buckingham Palace. Afterward, private meeting with
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and dinner with Mrs. Thatcher at
No. 10 Downing Street.
   June 3 _ Morning meeting with Japanese Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita.
   At noon, Reagan delivers a speech at Guild Hall summarizing the
summit and talking about the future of East-West relationship.
Later, he meets with U.S. Embassy personnel.
   Departure for Washington at 1:50 p.m. London time, arriving
Andrews Air Force Base in suburban Maryland about 4:30 p.m. EDT.
Arrival ceremony and remarks at Andrews.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
