<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     05-27 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,580</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner Michael
Dukakis is increasingly shifting the focus of his campaign to the
general election this fall, even though he's keeping up the
pretense that the party's nominating strugggle isn't over yet.
   ``We have not carried California in years,'' he told an
enthusiastic rally Thursday night as he wrapped up a quick, trip in
advance of the state's June 7 primary. ``But this is the year.
We're going to carry it.''
   Dukakis made his prediction of victory in the Republican bastion
of Orange County near Los Angeles _ going so far as to predict a
victory over Georeg Bush there as well as statewide. His aides said
they thought that was doubtful but said Dukakis decided to stop in
Orange County several weeks before the formal start of the fall
campaign in hopes of minimizing Bush's expected local victory and
thus make California easier to win.
   The Massachusetts governor was wrapping up a Western swing today
with stops in Albuquerque and Texas. The New Mexico visit was in
advance of the state's June 7 primary.
   But the decision to attend a barbeque in Austin, Texas, which
held its primary March 8, was made with the fall campaign in mind.
Dukakis was expected to receive the endorsements of several locally
prominent officials as he continues the process of unifying the
party for the general election campaign.
   Dukakis' manuevering comes as fresh public opinion polls
indcated he holds a substantial lead over the Republican vice
president.
   A Washington Post-ABC survery published in Friday's editions
reported the Massachusetts governor gaining the support of 53
percent of those polled to 40 percent for Bush.
   Dukakis dismissed the importance of the poll as he campaigned
through California on Thursday insisting, for the record, that he
still is concentrating on his final four primaries against
Democratic rival Jackson.
   ``It's not over yet,'' he said of his nominating struggle with
his sole remaining opponent, even though he is expected to wrap up
enough delegates on the final day of the primary season to clinch
the nomination.
   Dukakis used his time Thursday to depct himself as a
progressive, future oriented candidate.
   He stopped at a company-sponsored day care center in Palo Alto,
and issued a statement calling for expanded day care programs
nationally. He told employees of a high-tech medical firm that he
favors devoting a greater share of federal research and development
funds to civilian work.
   He also made a brief tour of a facility in Irvine where lasers
are developed for use in treatment of cancer and other disease, and
he and his wife Kitty used a laser beam to burn their names into a
honeydew melon.
   In between, at a news conference, he renewed his demand for a
``full explanation'' of links between the CIA and Panama's military
leader Manuel Antonio Noriega, who is under indictment on drug
charges in the United States.
   ``The vice president was asked a few weeks ago whether or not we
were paying Noriega, he said `I can't confirm or deny that.'''
   ``He's not running for press spokesman of the CIA,'' said
Dukakis. ``He's suppose to be running for president of the United
States.''
   He said Bush or President Reagan should explain any links betwen
the CIA and Noriega. ``Who are the people that were involved in
drug running and profit skimming and who was it in this
administration who thought that made sense.''
</TEXT>
