<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Exercise-Fetuses     05-27 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Exercise-Fetuses,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fetal Heart Rates Slow After Very Vigorous Maternal Exercise,
Study Finds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exercise is good for pregnant women, but
one-third of the 45 expectant mothers who pushed themselves to the
limit in brief workouts slowed the heart rates of their unborn
babies, researchers say.
   Whether diminished heart rates hurt fetuses is unclear, but it
could deprive them of needed oxygen, researchers said in a study in
today's Journal of the American Medical Association.
   Milder exercise doesn't have the same effect, and the findings
suggest that higher exercise levels than currently recommended are
safe for pregnant women, said lead researcher Dr. Marshall W.
Carpenter.
   ``The study is encouraging that women can continue exercising
during pregnancy at levels reminiscent of that before pregnancy,''
he said in a telephone interview Thursday.
   ``On the other hand, I would caution women against exceeding 145
to 150 heartbeats a minute (for their own heart rate) because we
don't know what effect it has on the fetus.''
   The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists
recommends that an expectant mother not exercise beyond a level
that raises her heart rate to 140 beats per minute, Carpenter said.
   But that recommendation was largely precautionary, and ``we can
give women a little more latitude than before,'' he said.
   The 45 women in the study were 4{ months to 7{ months pregnant,
and had an average age of 29.
   Fetal heart rates were measured at moderate and maximum exercise
levels by Carpenter, physiologist Stanley P. Sady, and other
researchers at Brown University.
   They found that maximum exercise _ when women peddled stationary
bicycles against increasing resistance until they were unwilling or
unable to continue _ produced brief episodes of slowed heart rates
in 15 fetuses.
   Two other fetuses experienced slowed heart rates linked to
moderate exercise, they said.
   The researchers believe any oxygen shortage was mild because
tests given the unborn babies 30 minutes after the initial
measurements were normal.
   The slowed heart rates did not appear to give rise to later
problems, the researchers said. Three of the 45 infants studied as
fetuses died within five weeks of birth, but of apparently
unrelated causes.
   Some of the study's subjects had exercised vigorously on a
regular basis before becoming pregnant and some had not, but that
did not appear to affect fetal heartbeats, the researchers said.
   Dr. Robert L. Jones, a researcher at Pennsylvania State
University College of Medicine in Hershey, said in a telephone
interview that the most important consideration is tailoring the
level of exercise to the individual.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugTesting     05-27 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Testing,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prison Test Ban Extended</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration's plans for
random drug testing of all federal prison employees have been put
on hold for three weeks more by a judge.
   U.S. District Judge Stanley Weigel on Thursday extended the
restraining order to June 16. The order had been sought in a
lawsuit by the American Federation of Government Employees, the
country's largest federal workers union.
   The testing was to have started last Monday. Weigel issued a
temporary restraining order May 20, saying constitutional problems
were raised by testing law-abiding employees not suspected of
wrongdoing.
   The delay has triggered a hiring freeze by the Bureau of
Prisons, said Justice Department lawyer Richard Lepley. Lepley,
noting that the agency has tested job applicants since 1984, asked
Weigel to exempt applicants from his order.
   The judge did not make an immediate decision.
   The program stems from President Reagan's 1986 order that
federal employees in sensitive jobs receive drug testing. The
prisons agency was one of the first agencies scheduled to begin
testing and the first to order random tests for all employees on
the theory that all hold sensitive jobs.
   The union, which claims 9,400 prison employees among its 750,000
members, contends in its suit that testing without suspicion of
drug use by an individual violates constitional standards for
unreasonable search.
   The suit also claims violations of federal laws forbidding
discrimination against the handicapped and requiring that employee
discipline be related to job performance.
   Union attorney Joe Goldberg said Thursday that the government's
safety justifications were a smokescreen. ``This program was not
designed for safety,'' Goldberg said.
   ``Testing was developed as a political reaction'' to
administration frustration at its inability to curb drug
importation, he said. ``Federal employees were an available
scapegoat.''
   Lepley acknowledged that testing does not directly measure
inability to do a job, but said it could reveal the potential for
abusing drugs, would discourage employees from using them and would
help keep drugs out of prisons.
   Prison employees have a reduced expectation of privacy, he said.
   In a separate suit, the union has challenged the entire drug
testing program, which would cover 345,000 employees in 40 agencies.
   Another suit was filed in the same court Thursday by an employee
group, the Overseas Education Association, challenging plans for
random drug testing of more than 9,600 teachers in schools run by
the Defense Department for U.S. military dependents in 20 countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0455EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador     05-27 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislature Inaugurated Nearly A Month Late</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers have agreed to put
aside a lengthy dispute over congressional election results and
allow the nation's single-chamber legislature to convene _ nearly a
month late.
   Legislators from the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance
and the governing Christian Democratic Party reached consensus
Thursday after three hours of negotiations in the National Assembly.
   The Alliance, known by its Spanish acronym Arena, contends it
won 31 seats in the 60-seat assembly in March 20 elections. The
Central Elections Council said Arena won 30 delegates, prompting
Arena party leaders to charge that the Christian Democrats stole
one through fraud.
   Arena's claim is pending before the Supreme Court.
   The council gave the Christian Democrats 23 seats and the small
National Conciliation Party seven seats.
   The National Assembly was to have been installed May 1.
   By Thursday night, only one legislator of the National
Conciliation Party supported the Arena-Christian Democrat
agreement. He indicated he would vote with Arena on most bills, in
effect giving the rightists a majority.
</TEXT>
