<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Tibet     05-27 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Tibet,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government To Renovate Ancient Tibetan Palace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government plans to renovate the ancient
palace of the Dalai Lama that overlooks the Tibetan capital of
Lhasa _ at an estimated cost of $8 million, an official newspaper
reported today.
   The China Daily said portions of the Potala Palace have been
cracked or damaged by worms over the centuries. It said more than
$1 million was spent on repairs in 1981, but that this was ``far
from enough.''
   The planned renovation will include repairs to 720 square feet
of frescoes, the report said.
   The vast Potala Palace, which now includes hundreds of rooms
stacked 13 stories high, was begun in the 7th century as a
pavilion. It was greatly enlarged in the 17th century.
   It includes living quarters for the Dalai Lama, Tibet's
traditional god-king, mausoleums of seven previous Dalai Lamas,
ceremonial halls, treasure store rooms, government offices, a
prison and a monastery.
   Since 1959, however, when the current Dalai Lama fled to India,
only a few monks have been allowed to remain in the Potala, and it
serves mainly as a museum for tourists.
   The Dalai Lama fled China during a failed uprising by thousands
of Tibetans against communist Chinese rule, imposed nine years
earlier.
   Most of the temples and religious sites in Tibet were destroyed
or badly damaged by radical bands of Red Guards during China's
Cultural Revolution from 1966-76.
   Tibetan activists claim Beijing is renovating the temples now to
lure more foreigners to Lhasa and profit from their tourist dollars.
   The activists have staged two large demonstrations over the past
year in Lhasa calling for an independent Tibet. Both were crushed
by Chinese authorities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0510EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AZTStudy     05-27 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AZT Study,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AZT Might Reduce Spread Of AIDS To Sexual Partners, Study Finds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AZT could make AIDS patients less infectious
to their sexual partners, according to researchers who found high
levels of the virus-fighting drug in the semen of patients treated
with it.
   However, the University of Minnesota researchers caution in
today's Journal of the American Medical Association that larger and
more detailed studies are needed to determine if AZT can reduce the
risk of spreading the virus.
   ``Our worst scenario is that some patients taking AZT will
decide that they no longer need to follow existing (safer-sex)
recommendations,'' said Dr. Henry Balfour, a University of
Minnesota virologist and a member of the research team.
   Researchers are trying to learn whether the drug even lowers the
amount of AIDS virus in the semen, said study author Dr. Keith
Henry, who is with the St. Paul Health Department. If so, said
Henry, it raises the possibility that AZT could lower the risk of
virus transmission to sexual partners.
   Health experts strongly urge people who even suspect that they
may have the AIDS virus to forgo sexual intercourse, or at least to
use a condom to reduce the risk of the virus spreading.
   At best, AZT probably would reduce, rather than eliminate, the
risk of the virus spreading, and no one yet knows by how much,
Henry explained. The abstinence-or-condom recommendations are
expected to continue as the first line of defense regardless of
what further studies find, he added.
   Semen has been the primary means by which the AIDS virus has
been transmitted since the epidemic began in 1981. Infected blood
is the other major transmission route.
   AZT is not a cure for AIDS, but it's the only drug so far that
has shown a clear-cut ability to extend some AIDS patients' lives.
It is being taken by at least 25,000 people who have the AIDS
virus, Balfour said.
   The Minnesota study found that the level of AZT in six patients
was typically several times higher in their semen than in their
blood. These AZT levels would be enough to keep the virus from
multiplying in a test tube, but Balfour said the results might be
different in the body.
   In addition, the drug isn't designed to get rid of all the
virus, only to keep it from growing, he said.
   Three of the patients in the study have AIDS, and three others
were ill with less severe symptoms called ARC, or AIDS-related
complex.
   The study was the first major look at how AZT concentrates in
body fluids other than blood, the researchers said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
