<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Floods     05-27 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Floods,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Rises To 131 With New Flooding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from flooding in southeast China
rose to 131, including five people who died after a new rainstorm
in Guangdong province, official reports said today.
   The China News Service reported that 91 people were dead and
more than 650 injured in coastal Fujian province, up from the
previous toll of 82 dead and 436 injured.
   Fujian, Jiangxi and Hunan provinces were hit with heavy rains
May 19-21. Three people died in Jiangxi and 32 in Hunan. The China
News Service, in a report on Fujian, said floodwaters were
receeding.
   The Xinhua News Service said heavy rains fell Tuesday and
Wednesday in northern areas of Guangdong province, killing five
people, injuring more than 370 and leaving three missing.
   Government officials rushed to the region to help relocate 8,000
people from heavily flooded areas, Xinhua said.
   It said 12 inches of rain fell on one Guangdong county, Fugang,
during the two-day storm, causing 2,150 houses to collapse and
flooding 6,422 acres of farmland.
   The English-language China Daily said the rains damaged part of
the Beijing-Canton railway line in northern Guangdong. Rail service
was halted for about six hours early Wednesday until repairs were
made, it said.
   The China News Service described damage in Fujian as much more
devastating than previously estimated.
   It said nearly 100,000 homes collapsed and 823,745 acres of
farmland were flooded, wiping out the crops in more than half the
area.
   The news agency estimated direct economic losses in Fujian at
$53.8 million.
   The heavy rains that have hit China's east coast have not helped
drought-stricken inland provinces, especially those in
north-central China such as Gansu, where a drought has lasted
nearly two years.
</TEXT>
