<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0518EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iraq-Battlefront     05-27 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iraq-Battlefront,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranians Fortify After Defeat, Bodies Scattered on Battlefield</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUT SWADI, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian troops were busy building new
fortifications east of this tiny frontier post after Iraq drove
them back into their own territory in a lightning attack east of
the port city of Basra.
   Reporters on a government-organized tour of the war front
Thursday saw the bodies of dozens of Iranian soldiers scattered on
this dusty plain along with their light weapons, rocket-propelled
grenade launchers and hand grenades.
   A field hospital built in a trench and well protected with
concrete walls was abandoned. Its equipment was scattered on the
floor along with more bodies of Iranian soldiers.
   Reporters were shown a small number of Iranian prisoners of war,
some in their mid-teens, others in their 60s. Iraqi officers would
not let reporters speak to them.
   From this border post 10 miles east of Basra, Iranian troops
were visible in the distance, hastily building new fortifications.
   The Iraqi officers said their forces, led by elite Presidential
Guards, routed the Iranians in a five-pronged offensive launched
Wednesday morning that lasted 10 hours.
   A senior officer, speaking on condition his name and rank not be
divulged, said Iraqi troops backed by tanks, artillery, jet
fighters and helicopter gunships retook 50 square miles of Iraqi
territory.
   The attack was spearheaded by tanks, part of Iraq's heavily
mechanized armed forces, and faced more lightly armed but sometimes
fanatical Iranian Revolutionary Guards and volunteers.
   The officer said those Iranian troops that weren't killed or
wounded ``fled to the other side of the border.''
   This observation post is where the Iranians pushed their troops
into Iraq in a January 1987 offensive that eventually petered out
just six miles from Basra. The southern city, Iraq's second
largest, is also its only sea port.
   Iranian army jeeps, trucks and ammunition stocks, some in good
shape, were abandoned by the Iranians along tracks they had built
to approach their main defense points.
   Western military analysts estimated that between 35,000 and
40,000 Iraqi troops took part in this week's offensive, but
reliable casualty estimates were not yet available.
   Reporters counted 400 Iranian prisoners of war being held here.
   The analysts say about 25,000 Iranians were believed killed in
the 1987 offensive and perhaps 10,000 Iraqis.
   Iraq has gone on the offensive recently after more than two
years of defensive tactics in the war, which began in September
1980. On April 18, Iraqi forces retook the Faw Peninsula, which had
been in Iranian hands since February 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
