<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-BurtandLoni     05-27 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Burt and Loni,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reynolds Misplaces Marriage License</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burt Reynolds built a special
chapel for his wedding last month to Loni Anderson and hired a
special caterer and a motorized stagecoach. But then he forgot
where he put the marriage license.
   ``He called us the day before the wedding and said he couldn't
seem to find it,'' said John Dunkle, Palm Beach County clerk of
courts. ``He wanted to know what to do.''
   Dunkle had personally delivered the marriage license application
to Reynolds at his Jupiter ranch March 2.
   The application is good for 60 days. Burt and Loni were married
on the 57th day. All Reynolds had to do was get the minister and
two witnesses to sign the license after the ceremony.
   That is, if he could find it.
   Dunkle told him a duplicate could be supplied. Marriage License
Supervisor Lynda Brown stayed in the office all day April 29, the
day of the wedding, waiting for Burt to call.
   ``I wanted to take the duplicate up there. I wanted to go to the
wedding,'' she said. ``My phone didn't ring the whole day.''
   Someone in Dunkle's office later sent Reynolds a duplicate. One
of Reynolds' assistants, Elaine Hall, is mailing it around so the
best man and another witness can sign it.
   Reynolds and Anderson are officially married, Dunkle said. They
just can't prove it.
</TEXT>
