<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0651EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Marcos     05-27 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Immigration Official Says Marcos Should Be Allowed To Attend
Mother's Funeral</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. immigration official says Ferdinand
Marcos should be allowed to return to the Philippines for his
mother's funeral, a remark that drew a rebuke from a Philippine
official.
   The deposed Philippine president reiterated his desire to return
to his homeland as he ended a two-day stay Thursday at St. Francis
Medical Center for treatment of chest pains.
   Harold Ezell, regional commissioner for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, met with Marcos' chief spokesman, Arturo
Aruiza, shortly afterward and said he thought Marcos should be
allowed to attend his mother's burial.
   ``Whether or not you agree with everything that's happened,
there is still a factor that Ferdinand Marcos is a human being who
had a mother who has passed away,'' Ezell said after accepting a
letter from Aruiza requesting approval for the return.
   ``The politics _ the government decisions _ sometimes have to be
weighed separately from that,'' he said.
   But, Ezell said, the final decision rests with Philippine
President Corazon Aquino. Mrs. Aquino has refused to allow Marcos
back, calling him a national security risk.
   The Philippine consul general in Hawaii criticized Ezell.
   ``I thought his behavior was rather irregular,'' said Tomas
Gomez. ``He is a public official who is supposed to react to a
bureaucratic process; he didn't have to editorialize.''
   Ezell said he sympathized with Marcos' situation because Ezell's
father died about a year ago.
   Before his release from the hospital, Marcos told reporters that
Mrs. Aquino should back down from her claim that he poses a threat.
   ``I've told them I will not bother them ... but will hold back
the people from starting violence,'' Marcos said while seated in a
wheelchair.
   Marcos, 70, was accompanied by his wife, Imelda, several aides,
a nurse and his physician, Dr. Azucena Ignacio, who said Marcos was
fit to travel.
   Ignacio said arthritis or inflammation in the area of the left
sixth rib caused Marcos' chest pains. Marcos improved dramatically
with rest and was being treated with a painkiller, she said.
   Aruiza's letter contained a list of 71 people for whom Marcos
wants officials to grant permission to go to the Philippines for
the funeral of Josefa Edralin-Marcos, who died May 4 at age 95.
   William Craig, the INS district director, said the 71 also
requested permission to re-enter the United States if allowed to
travel to the Philippines.
   Marcos is under ``a prevent departure notice,'' which means he
needs permission to leave the United States, Craig said.
   Ezell and Craig said the letter would be forwarded to Washington
for consideration. Included in the list were Marcos, his wife, son
Ferdinand Marcos Jr. and daughter Irene Araneta.
   A State Department official in Washington, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said the United States would not consider any Marcos
trip without the approval of the Aquino government.
   According to the Philippine Department of Immigration and
Deportation, 16 of the 71 on the list are covered by a ``hold
order'' that prevents them from leaving the Philippines should they
return. They include Marcos, his wife and two children.
</TEXT>
