<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolShootings     05-27 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Shootings,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Friend of Dann's Committed to Psychiatric Ward After Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINNETKA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A female friend of Laurie Dann, who killed
one child and wounded six people during a shooting rampage, has
been charged with making harassing telephone calls similar to the
ones Dann was accused of, police said.
   Sheri L. Taylor, 34, of suburban Highwood was arrested at the
local convenience store where she worked and later surrendered a
.357 Magnum handgun she kept in the hotel room where she lived,
Winnetka Police Chief Herbert Timm said Thursday.
   Taylor was charged with threatening her former husband over the
telephone, Timm said. Before her death Friday, Dann had also been
accused of threatening her ex-husband.
   Taylor was arrested late Wednesday by a local-county task force
investigating Dann's background, Timm said. She was involuntarily
committed to a psychiatric unit at Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's
Medical Center in Chicago for treatment.
   ``We should let the psychiatrists examine her and then decide
what should be done,'' said Lisa Howard, a spokeswoman for Cook
County state's attorney's office.
   Last Friday, Dann started a small fire in a home, shot six
children at Hubbard Woods Elementary School, killing one, and then
shot and wounded a 20-year-old man at a nearby home. She then shot
and killed herself.
   At a news conference, Timm identified Taylor ``as a very close
friend of Laurie Dann.'' He said Taylor's ex-husband had warned
that ``she might be a threat to him, to herself and this
community.''
   ``It was extremely obvious that this was a serious situation. We
are concerned with the safety of the Taylor family. ... We wanted
to prevent another tragedy,'' Timm said.
   Dann and Taylor had been roommates about a year ago and also had
a distant family connection, said Assistant State's Attorney Randy
Stewart.
   Timm said there is no evidence that Taylor had any connection
with Dann's violent rampage or helped her make threatening calls.
   ``We are in the process of determining the extent of Ms.
Taylor's involvement with Laurie Dann,'' Timm said.
   In another development Thursday, an FBI official in Madison,
Wis., said Dann apparently acted alone in obtaining the poison she
used to lace about two dozen packages of snacks and juice that she
sent or delivered to acquaintances before going on her Winnetka
shooting spree.
   ``Nobody else has surfaced as an accomplice based on the
investigation we did here,'' said Charles Steinmetz, supervisor of
the FBI's Madison office.
   Authorities are investigating whether Dann sent her former
husband, Russell Dann, an envelope containing fruit juice that was
found Wednesday at a Highland Park post office.
   Also Thursday, one of the children shot by Dann was released
from Evanston Hospital, and the most seriously injured victim,
8-year-old Lindsay Fisher, was upgraded to fair condition. Two
other children were in good condition at the hospital. Two other
shooting victims were in fair condition at Highland Park Hospital.
   Taylor was arrested on two outstanding warrants _ on a new
charge of threatening the life of her ex-husband, Scott Taylor, and
their children, who live with their father, and an old charge of
failing to appear on a drunken driving charge in Evanston, Timm
said.
   Taylor's ex-husband signed the complaint against her because he
was concerned about his family's safety and feared that Taylor
might harm herself, Winnetka Police Sgt. Gene Kalvaitis said.
</TEXT>
