<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Party     05-27 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Party,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Program Criticizes Militarism, Calls For Purge Of Bureaucrats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party's policy-making Central
Committee says the Kremlin has in the past wrongly stressed
military over diplomatic solutions to world problems and that its
foreign policy is no longer dogmatic.
   A position paper approved by the 300-plus member body also
sharply criticizes the role the party has come to occupy in Soviet
society, saying bureaucrats are too often impeding the
effectiveness of government bodies.
   It proposes limiting party officials to two five-year terms,
with exceptions that could include Mikhail S. Gorbachev, and says
elections for party jobs should be by secret ballot with more than
one candidate.
   The report will serve as the foundation for an extraordinary
party conference that begins June 28, the first such gathering
since 1941. Its details were distributed Thursday by the official
Tass news agency.
   Approved Monday, it sets the agenda for a possible showdown
between reformers led by Gorbachev and conservatives resisting
change.
   The report says foreign policy before Gorbachev came to power
``trailed behind fundamental changes that occurred in the world and
missed chances to reduce tensions and enhance understanding among
nations.''
   Praising changes made by the Soviet leader, it said Kremlin
foreign policy now addresses problems of a world faced with nuclear
destruction while ``not imposing any conditions or dogmas on
anyone.''
   The new Soviet approach has led to a ``definite improvement'' in
relations with the United States, and a ``fresh discovery'' of the
Soviet Union in other countries, the Central Committee report says.
   ``In our bid for military-strategic parity we occassionally
failed to use opportunities available to attain security for our
nation by political means, and, as a result, allowed ourselves to
be lured into an arms race which could not but affect this
country's social and economic progress and its standing on the
international scene,'' the report says.
   On domestic policy, the program strongly reflects Gorbachev's
priorities for increasing citizen involvement in public affairs and
making individuals more accountable. Its passage shows that the man
who rose to party chief in March 1985 was able to muster the vital
support of the Central Committee.
   Gorbachev was named to present the party program at the meeting
next month at which 5,000 delegates will pass judgment on his
reforms.
   The program indicates the Communists still lay claim to being
the most important force in Soviet society and the only legal
political party. But it says Communist authorities have seriously
weakened local governing bodies and the party itself by seeking to
dominate nearly all aspects of life.
   ``The rights and powers of the representative bodies have been
curtailed and they remain under unwarranted tutelage from party
committees,'' the report says, with governing councils often left
to rubber-stamp decisions already made at higher levels.
   The result has ``sharpened many social development problems,''
the report said. ``It is vital to change this situation radically.''
   The report says changes must extend to the Supreme Soviet, the
nominal parliament which finished a three-day session in the
Kremlin on Thursday.
   Party documents call for an increase in the number of days the
governing councils work, urge that members be relieved of work
obligations to attend such sessions and that the meetings be open
to the public and the media.
   The report indicates that those who do not support Gorbachev's
reforms will be purged from the 19 million-member party.
   Gorbachev in January 1987 called on the party to implement
procedures to ensure that new blood is brought into the leadership,
but he ran into resistance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0704EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bernardin-Euthanasia     05-27 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bernardin-Euthanasia,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal Renews Opposition To Euthanasia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Joseph Bernardin urged Roman Catholics
and non-Catholics to oppose efforts to legalize euthanasia, but
said opponents must work for alternatives for the incurably ill
such as hospices.
   ``As individuals and as a society, we have the positive
obligation to protect life,'' Bernardin said in a speech Thursday
to the Center for Clinical Medical Ethics at the University of
Chicago Hospitals and Clinics.
   ``We have the negative obligation not to destroy or injure human
life directly, especially the life of the innocent and vulnerable.''
   Bernardin suggested that funding for hospice programs in
hospitals or patients' homes could come from insurance or public
sources.
   ``In this way we can eliminate many of the legitimate concerns
that may motivate people to consider euthanasia, which otherwise
would be unacceptable to them and society,'' he said.
   The cardinal said his position against mercy killing does not
include keeping alive by extraordinary medical procedures or
machines ``those who should be allowed a natural death.''
   He said he was ``convinced that we are not morally obliged to do
everything that is technically possible'' to keep terminally ill
patients alive. ``In other words, there are cases where we would
not be obliged to provide nutrition and hydration.
   He said the challenge was to develop a public policy ``to
protect against an attitude that could erode respect for the
inviolable dignity of human life.''
   But such a policy should not create categories or priorities of
people ``whose lives no longer need be protected,'' he said.
   The cardinal said his remarks were prompted by the increased
public discussion of euthanasia following advances in medical
technology that can artificially prolong a patient's life.
   The issue has been widely debated since the Chicago-based
Journal of the American Medical Association published a letter in
January by an anonymous doctor describing the mercy killing of a
terminally ill cancer patient.
   ``The fear, then, of the pain and discomfort of a life prolonged
inappropriately has led to an erosion of the natural instinct to
preserve one's life,'' the cardinal said.
   ``In certain critical decisions involving living and dying, many
perceive that the focus of concern many no longer be the good of
the patient'' but what will best protect the doctor and hospital
from legal action, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
