<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DiGilio     05-27 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-DiGilio,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Body Found In River Identified As That Of Reputed Mobster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of a reputed mobster was found in a
body bag floating in the Hackensack River, with two bullet holes
behind his ear and a credit card left behind to signal his
identity, authorities said.
   The body of John DiGilio, a flamboyant ex-boxer who was a friend
of heavyweight champions Muhammad Ali and Joe Frazier, was found in
the river by the New York suburb of Carlstadt on Thursday, said
Bergen County Prosecutor Larry McClure.
   ``Sometimes when you live by the sword, you die by the sword,''
said Jeff Bronster, a Justice Department attorney who prosecuted
DiGilio in a recent waterfront racketeering case.
   The corpse was decomposed beyond recognition, but DiGilio was
wearing the same clothes he had on when his wife reported him
missing May 7 and authorities were able to confirm his identity
through fingerprints, McClure said.
   After the 55-year-old Bayonne man was reported missing,
authorities said their sources indicated the reputed Genovese crime
family soldier had been the victim of gangland violence.
   The former longshoreman was a colorful figure who frequently
spoke with reporters, successfully acted as his own attorney in the
racketeering case, often invited his boxing friends to the
courtroom and filed a harassment suit against federal officials.
   Authorities believe that flamboyance may have prompted mob
colleagues unhappy with the attention to seek DiGilio's elimination.
   DiGilio was also to be sentenced on a state loan-sharking
conviction May 19.
   His body was found inside a zipped mortician's bag, with two
bullet holes behind the ear, state police said. A Visa card was
found between DiGilio's legs so that whoever recovered the body
would be able to identify it, said McClure.
   Mob experts have said it was likely DiGilio's death would be
made known to serve as a warning to others.
   Authorities alleged the former middleweight boxer controlled
loan sharking and labor rackets on the Hudson River waterfront, and
had extended his influence into Bergen County to the north.
   Last April, a jury acquitted him of extorting money from a
stevedore company on the Bayonne waterfront in exchange for labor
peace.
   DiGilio was convicted of loan sharking last October after
remaining free for 10 years through a series of delays, most of
them connected to claims of ill health and mental instability.
   He was cleared in 1986 of violating a probationary sentence for
his 1975 conviction for arranging the theft of his FBI file, his
only other conviction. He served nine months in jail for the file
theft.
</TEXT>
