<DOCNO> AP880527-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0738EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MiracleBaby     05-27 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Miracle Baby,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baby Who Weighed 15{ Ounces At Birth To Go Home Soon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``little miracle'' who barely filled an
adult's hand when she was born 17 weeks premature last January
should be able to leave the hospital in about two weeks, doctors
say.
   Ashley Lynn Cunningham seems to have escaped the problems that
often plague premature babies, doctors said Thursday.
   Ashley, who weighed just 15{ ounces at birth, now weighs 3
pounds 15{ ounces and measures 16\ inches. She has color in her
cheeks, can hold her head up and cries frequently, although very
softly.
   When she was born, doctors were uncertain whether she would
survive more than a few days. Had things gone according to plan,
Ashley would have been born today.
   ``She's really a little miracle,'' said Deborah Blair, a nurse
in the neonatal intensive care unit at Children's Medical Center,
Ashley's home since birth.
   Ashley should go home in about two weeks, said Dr. Ronald E.
Hoekstra, a specialist on newborns at the hospital.
   The smallest premature infant to survive in the United States
weighed 15 ounces, according to Hoekstra.
   Although Ashley's eyes are not fully developed, doctors don't
believe she will have any problems with sight.
   She has not experienced any hemorrhaging in her brain, another
common problem with premature babies, and doesn't appear to have
any serious breathing difficulties, though she lived on a
respirator for 77 days. Her skin, thin at birth, has developed and
will protect her from infection, Hoekstra said.
   It appears she will live a normal, healthy life, although her
progress will be monitored by doctors periodically until she is 7,
Hoekstra said.
   Five years ago, Ashley probably would not have lived long enough
to go home, Hoekstra said. He said technological advances and
better-trained doctors have made it possible to treat infants such
as Ashley.
   Ashley's grandmother, Joan Cunningham, said she can't count the
prayers she and family members have said for Ashley in the past
four anxiety-filled months. Ashley's medical bills stand at about
$224,000, and will be covered by insurance, hospital officials said.
</TEXT>
