<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0477 05-27 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0477,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Laserphoto WX8</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Sees Central America in Mediating Role in Panama</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 5 grafs following 6th graf pvs, bgng, A unilateral
... etc., to UPDATE with Reagan comments in Helsinki, Finland.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Following the collapse of its negotiating
effort, the Reagan administration is promoting a more active role
for the Central American democracies in encouraging Panamanian
leader Manuel Antonio Noriega to surrender power.
   ``I think it's an excellent idea,'' said Undersecretary of State
Michael Armacost, noting that several Central American countries
``have a tremendous storehouse of experience in the transition to
civilian democratic rule.''
   Armacost, the State Department's third-ranking official, spoke
Thursday evening on the ``MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour'' after a day
marked by high-level consultations in Washington and in a number of
Latin American capitals.
   Assistant Secretary of State Elliott Abrams said earlier that
U.S. ambassadors from around the hemisphere were instructed to
sound out host governments on their ideas for negotiating a
solution in Panama.
   Panama was the subject of a senior level meeting Thursday at the
White House as well.
   A unilateral U.S. effort to negotiate Noriega out of power
failed on Wednesday when the Defense Forces commander and de facto
ruler backed out of a deal his representatives had negotiated with
State Department envoy Michael Kozak.
   During a photo session in Helsinki today with Finnish President
Mauno Henrik Koivisto, President Reagan indicated that he and his
advisers have reached no decisions about how to proceed on the
Panamanian problem.
   ``We have had no opportunity to consider where we go,'' he said
in response to reporters' questions.
   Reagan also side-stepped a question as to whether he would use
military force in Panama.
   ``I can't answer as to what might be the possibilities,'' Reagan
said, saying it would be wrong to talk about options.
   Pressed to respond to Abrams' refusal to rule out the use of
military force, Reagan said again, ``I won't comment on the
possibilities.''
   As part of a U.S. plan to restore democratic rule in Panama next
year, Noriega was to step down this August and go into temporary
exile. In return, federal drug smuggling indictments against him
were to be dismissed.
   Noriega's rejection of the plan ended the negotiations and
appeared to breathe new life into a Central American initiative in
which Guatemalan President Vinicio Cerezo apparently would play the
key role.
   Panamanian Ambassador Juan Sosa, who is allied with the
anti-Noriega forces, told reporters after a meeting with State
Department officials that diplomatic contacts had been made with
Cerezo after the collapse of the U.S. effort.
   Cerezo assumed power two years ago as the first elected civilian
president after more than 30 years of military or
military-dominated governments in Guatemala.
   His Washington ambassador, Oscar Padilla, told the ``NewsHour''
program that the ``Central American family'' should initiate an
effort to resolve the Panamanian crisis.
   Joining with Guatemala in any such effort would be the
governments of Costa Rica, Honduras and El Salvador, all
democracies with close links to the United States.
   The administration has resisted significant involvement by other
hemispheric governments in the Panama issue, but has now shifted
its strategy somewhat after calling a halt to its own initiative.
   While Armacost indicated there would be a reduced U.S. role in
the future, he noted that the federal indictments against Noriega
imply continued American participation in any effort to reach a
settlement in Panama.
   Although Noriega has little overt support in Latin America,
hemispheric nations have indicated deep reservations about the
administration's approach to the problem.
   One example of this was a meeting of 26 Latin American countries
two months ago at which a resolution was passed criticizing the
U.S. economic sanctions against Panama.
</TEXT>
