<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-Bomb     05-27 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Bomb,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Destroys Summer Home Of Galician Conservative Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERBES, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded today outside the
unoccupied summer home of a leading Spanish conservative,
destroying the chalet but causing no injuries, police said.
   The explosion occurred at 4:40 a.m. at the two-story house
belonging to Manuel Fraga, a European Parliament deputy.
   The building is on the outskirts of this seaside town in La
Coruna province in the northwestern region of Galicia.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility, police said.
Fraga's wife and family were in Madrid, where the politician has
lived for decades. Fraga's whereabouts were not immediately known.
   In 1977, Fraga, a native of the Galician town of Villalba,
founded the conservative Popular Alliance party, the largest
opposition party in the national Parliament. He resigned as
president 18 months ago.
   On May 21, the Galician branch of the party elected him as its
leader and named him its candidate for president of the region's
autonomous government in elections set for late next year.
   In June 1987 elections, Fraga won election to the European
Parliament in Strasbourg, France.
   Fraga served as tourism and information minister in the 1960s
and Spanish ambassador to Britain in the early 1970s during the
rule of Gen. Francisco Franco. He was also a minister in the first
government appointed by King Juan Carlos after the death of Gen.
Franco in 1975.
</TEXT>
