<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Carlucci-Summit     05-27 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carlucci-Summit,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviet Defense Chiefs To Discuss Military Doctrine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci said today he planned to meet with his Soviet counterpart
during the Moscow summit to discuss the superpowers' military
doctrines.
   Carlucci and Soviet Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov first met
on the topic in March in Bern, Switzerland, following indications
from Moscow that it was putting less emphasis on offensive military
firepower.
   Carlucci indicated that he had taken the initiative to arrange a
second meeting.
   ``He has agreed to such a meeting, and we will have further
discussions on this subject because we obviously want to learn as
much as we can about the Soviet doctrine,'' Carlucci told a news
conference after a two-day meeting of North Atlantic Treaty
Organization defense ministers.
   The NATO ministers said in a joint declaration that despite
Soviet statements indicating the East bloc wanted a less
confrontational relationship with the West, there was not yet
concrete evidence that Moscow had made changes in its military
structure.
   Carlucci was flying to The Hague, the Netherlands today for
talks with Dutch government officials before going to Moscow on
Sunday.
</TEXT>
