<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OmakFires     05-27 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Omak Fires,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guilty Plea in $6.5 Million Fires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKANOGAN, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former firefighter has been sentenced
to 9{ years in prison for setting a string of fires that caused
$6.5 million damage at a school and two churches in Omak.
   Adrian Julius Howe, 23, had reported one of the fires, helped
set up barricades at another and was seen at three others, said
Okanogan County prosecutor Jack Burchard.
   Howe pleaded guilty to five counts of arson Thursday and
received the maximum sentence, nine years and eight months, from
Superior Court Judge James R. Thomas.
   He pleaded guilty to setting two fires in December at Omak North
Elementary School, which he had attended, and three blazes at two
churches in February.
   An arson charge stemming from a fire that caused $5,000 damage
to a church parsonage was dismissed.
   Burchard and Sheriff Jim Weed said there was no apparent motive
for the fires.
   The fires depleted the rural county's coffers, and county
commissioners have requested state help. A new school is expected
to be ready by fall 1989.
   Howe, a lumber mill employee on the Colville Indian Reservation
and former firefighter for the Bureau of Indian Affairs, was
arrested Feb. 25.
</TEXT>
