<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PhonesAtLast     05-27 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Phones At Last,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Switching Hour Finally Comes For Phone-Troubled Suburbanites</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Midnight was the switching hour for thousands of
suburban Illinois Bell customers whose telephone service went up in
flames on Mother's Day.
   At 11:59 p.m. Thursday, a technician punched a computer button
at the fire-damaged Hinsdale switching station, hooking up half of
Illinois Bell's 35,000 Hinsdale-area customers to a new digital
switching system.
   With that action, these customers should have normal service
again, 2{ weeks after the May 8 fire at the switching station, a
key part of the phone network for northern Illinois, Bell spokesman
Tim Bannon said Thursday.
   ``There might be some shakeout wrinkles, but these people should
have state-of-the-art telephone service,'' including clearer lines
and such options as call waiting and call forwarding previously
unavailable through the 20-year-old equipment at the station,
Bannon said.
   The new equipment, which normally takes 50 weeks to put into
service, was installed in just two weeks by about 250 Illinois Bell
employees working day and night, Bannon said.
   The rest of Illinois Bell's Hinsdale-area customers will
continue to have problems calling outside the area and getting
long-distance service until they can be connected to the new
equipment in early June, Bannon said.
   They remain hooked to the old equipment, which sustained smoke
and fire damage but has been kept operational as a stopgap measure.
   ``The system is getting better, but it is upsetting,'' said Ruth
Collins, of Burr Ridge, whose phone line was one of those on the
old equipment. ``You reach a point after a while where you are
grateful for anything.''
   The fire disrupted service for hundreds of thousands of
residents in Chicago's western suburbs and totally cut off the
35,000 customers for at least a week.
   Bannon said virtually all of the long-distance circuits and
special business lines transmitting computer data that had been
routed through the Hinsdale station had been restored, although it
would still take a few more days to correct some scattered problems.
</TEXT>
