<1ST_LINE>r i PM-FerryFire 2ndLd-Writethru a0541 05-27 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ferry Fire, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0541,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Engine Room Fire On Ferry In English Channel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with ferry under tow. Pick up
3rd pvs, `It was...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire broke out early today in the engine
room of a British passenger ferry in the English Channel, but it
was quickly put out and no one was hurt, officials said.
   The 3,335-ton European Trader, carrying 85 passengers and crew,
was being towed to the French coast, according to its owners, P and
O European Ferries Ltd. It maintained power, however, with an
emergency generator.
   It was the second blaze this week aboard a British ferry plying
the channel between England and the Continent, the world's busiest
waterway.
   On Monday, one crewman died and another was seriously burned
when a fire started in the engine room of the 5,917-ton Seafreight
Freeway, owned by Sealink U.K. Ltd. The fire on the freight ferry
was blamed on a fractured fuel pipe.
   Both fires occurred as the ferries sailed between this southeast
England port and the Belgian port of Zeebrugge. It was outside
Zeebrugge that the British ferry Herald of Free Enterprise capsized
in March 1987, killing 193 people.
   P and O said the blaze in the engine room of the European Trader
started before dawn today, 20 miles northwest of Dunkirk, France.
Crewmen evacuated the engine room as it filled with smoke.
   Helicopters flew out carrying firefighters and rescue workers,
and tugs and a lifeboat were sent to the area. But the ship's
captain reported that the fire was smothered by an on-board
firefighting system activated when the crew evacuated the engine
room.
   There was no immediate indication what caused the blaze.
   The European Trader was the first vessel to break a continuing
strike on P and O's lucrative Dover-Calais route when it sailed to
the French port on May 14, the first such voyage for 15 weeks.
   Today, the ferry was carrying 44 passengers, 41 crewmen and 50
freight trucks from Zeebrugge to Dover, P and O said.
</TEXT>
