<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-RedArmy 1stLd-Writethru   05-27 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Red Army, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0507,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Question Man Suspected Of Being Red Army Terrorist</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs with questioning on hijacking, new
terrorist activity, details on charges; pickup 6th graf, `Two of
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today questioned a suspected Japanese Red
Army terrorist about the 1970 hijacking of a Japanese airliner to
North Korea, a police spokesman said.
   Yasuhiro Shibata, 34, also will be questioned about whether the
leftist terrorist group was planning any new terrorist action, the
spokesman said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Shibata, 16 years old in 1970, was one of nine suspected Red
Army members who hijacked a Japan Air Lines Boeing 727 to the North
Korean capital of Pyongyang. He was arrested in Tokyo on May 6.
   Authorities said they brought Shibata to Tokyo today in an
unusual helicopter airlift from his hometown in western Japan to
ensure his safety. He was taken to Tokyo's Metropolitan Police
Department, where questioning began.
   The Kobe Prosecutor's Office so far has charged him only with
using someone else's passport.
   The police spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
prosecutors will determine whether to charge him in the hijacking.
The investigation also is looking into current Red Army activity,
he said.
   Two of the remaining seven hijackers declared in Pyongyang on
Tuesday that they were ready to return to Japan.
   ``We can't leave him (Shibata) alone in his present situation,''
declared Moriaki Wakabayashi, 41, in his first interview with
Japanese television.
   Police believe Shibata returned to Japan in April 1985 by an
unknown route from North Korea, and that another member of the
hijacking team died in Pyongyang of illness.
   Police have said Shibata worked part time in Tokyo and obtained
the phony passport in Yokohama in July 1986 using the name of a
Kobe man with Japanese and North Korean citizenship. The man
returned to North Korea in 1972 without disclaiming his Japanese
citizenship, they said.
   According to the Kobe Prosecutor's Office, Shibata would face up
to three years in prison if convicted of using a false passport. A
convicted hijacker not charged with murder in Japan is subject to a
maximum term of life in prison.
   Authorities said Shibata has refused to cooperate with police,
but that travel records show he went several times to Europe using
the other man's passport.
   The police spokesman said today that it was too early to say
whether Europe was being used as a Red Army base or whether North
Korea had aided the group in any way. Other police officials have
said Shibata could not have left North Korea without official
government permission.
   Osamu Maruoka, the Red Army's reputed No. 2 man who was arrested
in Japan last November, and Yu Kikumura, a suspected Red Army
member arrested in the United States in April for possessing
explosives, are both believed to have traveled in Europe before
their arrests.
   Following Maruoka's arrest, investigations showed he had
reserved a one-way ticket to travel last Decemer to Seoul, the site
of the 1988 Summer Olympics.
   Two more suspected Red Army members, Junzo Okudaira and Fusako
Shigenobu, the Red Army's alleged leader, are being sought by
police in Italy for suspected involvement in a car bomb attack in
Naples in April.
   The arrests and bombing have sparked speculation that the
long-dormant terrorist group is planning a comeback.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
