<2ND_LINE>PM-Grade Selling,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Faculty Members Accused of Grade Selling Threatened With Firing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two faculty members accused of offering A's
to students at California State University's Northridge campus in
exchange for selling $100 in raffle tickets have been notified they
will be fired, their attorney said.
   University officials declined comment Thursday on the case
against Pan-African studies Professor Eleazu S. Obinna and
instructor Willie J. Bellamy.
   Obinna, a 17-year member of the department, and Bellamy, a
first-year instructor, were accused by students of offering A's in
three African history and culture classes in exchange for selling
raffle tickets, the university said last month.
   The raffle money went to Obinna's nonprofit United Crusade
Foundation, which he founded in 1982, the university said.
   The university April 28 canceled the three independent studies
courses, with an enrollment of more than 180. Students had reported
that the courses required no classroom attendance and assigned no
course work.
   Francis E. Smith, the faculty members' lawyer, said Thursday the
letters alerted Obinna and Bellamy of the university's intent to
fire them.
   ``We intend to vigorously oppose any effort on the part of the
university to dismiss either Dr. Obinna or Professor Bellamy,''
Smith said.
   The Nigerian-born Obinna, 54, denied any wrongdoing last month
and said the charges were ``concocted by he administration.'' He
said he required 45 hours of course work and graded students on
participation in minority community affairs.
   Bellamy has declined comment.
   The Los Angeles County District Attorney's office announced
Tuesday it was conducting a separate investigation. Raffles are
illegal under state law.
   In addition, the state attorney general's office is
investigating whether donations to Obinna's foundation were
improperly diverted. City records show the foundation has spent
$120 for the needy since its inception.
   Obinna and Bellamy have seven days to request a hearing with an
examiner. It then would be up to the university president to decide
whether to uphold, modify or reject any discipline recommended by
the examiner.
   The Northridge campus is 25 miles northwest of downtown Los
Angeles.
</TEXT>
