<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0543,0791</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Syrian Troops Move Into Shiite Slums</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UDPATE with more troops moving in.
ADDS details and color. Pick up 9th graf pvs: `Kenaan said...'
Edits thereafter to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Syrian troops moved into
Beirut's southern slums today to end a three-week bloodbath between
rival Shiite Moslem militias.
   The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, and the
Syrian-armed Amal militia stopped shooting as the deployment began.
   Syria's move was expected to increase pressure for the release
of 18 foreign hostages, including nine Americans, who are believed
to be held in the slums by Shiite factions linked to Hezbollah.
   Hours after Syria announced Thursday that its troops would move
in, gunmen ambushed a car carrying four Syrian generals. All four
escaped injury.
   About 900 soldiers wearing bulletproof vests over their combat
fatigues advanced on foot from Beirut's airport highway into the
Ghobeiri and Shiyah districts.
   A half-hour earlier, shell blasts and staccato bursts of gunfire
in the embattled slums resounded across Beirut. Police had no word
on what touched off the flareup, which occurred despite pledges by
both factions to observe a cease-fire.
   The Syrians advanced in three groups, each made up of 300
infantrymen carrying machine guns and shoulder-fired grenade
launchers. The first group was followed by 50 Lebanese policemen
carrying automatic rifles.
   The Syrians set up four or five checkpoints along a
disengagement line between the Amal-held Shiyah neighborhood and
Hezbollah-controlled Ghobeiri.
   Wailing women greeted the Syrians as they moved in by showering
them with rice in a traditional gesture of welcome.
   ``Animals, they're all animals, animals killing animals,'' a man
standing in front of his bomb-shattered house shouted in English
when he saw Western correspondents covering the Syrian advance.
   His house was seized by Hezbollah fighters during the final
phase of the savage street fighting that erupted May 6. Police say
296 people have been killed and 1,000 wounded in the turf war.
   There was no immediate word when the Syrians planned to send
tanks and other armor into the devastated districts to enforce the
cease-fire.
   Syria's military intelligence chief in Lebanon, Brig. Gen. Ghazi
Kenaan, said Syria would deploy 7,500 soldiers in the
16-square-mile slums, about 90 percent of which are controlled by
Hezbollah.
   Kenaan was one of four generals riding in a Mercedes 500 that
was hit by dozens of bullets as it traveled through Ghobeiri on
Thursday. Neither the generals nor their bodyguards were hurt, the
Syrians reported.
   The attack came just hours after Kenaan announced Syrian forces
would enter the slums today.
   Police said Hezbollah militiamen raked Kenaan's bulletproof dark
blue Mercedes with machine gun fire as it drove through Ghobieri.
   According to police, Hezbollah forces claimed they were not
notified that Kenaan's motorcade would be going through Ghobeiri,
although police said notification was made.
   Also in the car were Maj. Gen. Saeed Bairakdar, commander of
Syria's forces in Lebanon; Brig. Gen. Ali Hammoud, chief of
military intelligence for the Beirut area; and Brig Gen. Zuheir
Musattat.
   President Hafez Assad's Syrian government announced on Thursday
that a truce agreement has been reached with all parties concerned,
including Iran and Hezbollah, to end the carnage.
   ``Ending the fighting will create new hope for the hostages and
Syria will spare no effort to secure their release, regardless of
their nationality,'' a Syrian official told The Associated Press in
Damascus.
   A source at the Syrian command, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the deployment operation would be carried out in
two stages today and Saturday.
   The first involves the establishment of buffer zones in key
positions along the confrontation lines in the neighborhoods of
Shiyah, Ghobeiri, Mesharrafieh and Haret Hreik today, he said.
   The deployment in the rest of the slums would be completed on
Saturday, including Hezbollah's main strongholds of Bir el-Abed and
Hay Madi, the source added.
   The hostages are believed to be imprisoned in Hezbollah's Hay
Madi barracks.
   Both Amal and Hezbollah have said they would withdraw their
fighters once the Syrians move in and keep only political and
information offices.
   It was not clear whether the hostages were part of the truce
deal. But the Iranian assistant foreign minister, Ali Mohammed
Besharati, predicted last week that the hostage problem would be
solved after peace was restored in south Beirut.
   Syria is the main power broker in Lebanon, embroiled in civil
war for 13 years. Although an ally of Iran, it appears anxious that
Iran's brand of Islamic fundamentalism may be getting too much of a
foothold in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
