<HEAD>Fire Near Air And Space Museum Causes Minor Damage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 1st graf of 3rd item to delete word ``notorious''.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire caused minor damage in a restaurant
being built adjacent to the most popular tourist attraction in the
nation's capital.
   The two-alarm fire began Thursday afternoon near the Air and
Space Museum sending heavy smoke into the air but it did not spread
to the popular museum where countless irreplaceable exhibits of
aviation and space history are on display.
   ``Seeing all that smoke coming out of it, it was a frightening
sight,'' said Madeleine Jacobs, a spokeswoman for the museum.
   She said, however, the fire wasn't as serious as it appeared and
visitors to the museum were not disturbed.
   ``Apparently a spark from a welder's torch ignited some paper
that was being used to line the windows,'' said Leo Givs of the
District of Columbia Fire Department. No injuries were reported.
