<HEAD>Iran Attacks Merchant Ship; Claims 10,000 Iraqi Casualties In Land
War</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-9 pvs, `Associated Press ...' to DELETE
extraneous words and CLARIFY. Pick up 10th pvs, `On May...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Iranian speedboats raided a Maltese
freighter today and left it burning in the Strait of Hormuz, then
fired at a press helicopter when it approached the site of the
attack, shipping executives said.
   Iran earlier claimed it killed or wounded 10,000 Iraqi troops in
land battles east of Basra.
   The press helicopter chartered by the American television
network CBS was not hit.
   Shipping executives had said a second ship was hit but later
retracted that report.
   The executives said the 18-member crew of the 18,000-ton Don
Miguel abandoned ship after the 8 a.m. attack. An Omani warship
sailing nearby rescued them.
   The executives, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
crew, all South Koreans, were transferred to a salvage tugboat of
the Dutch company Smit and appeared to have been unharmed.
   Associated Press photographer Greg English, who was aboard a
helicopter in the area, said a second Smit salvage tugboat was
battling the flames as they ravaged the freighter's stern.
   The executives said the Iranians fired at the helicopter
chartered by CBS when it tried to get close to the site of the
attack. But they said the four volleys of gunfire only hit the
water and did not damage the aircraft.
   It was the second Iranian raid in 12 hours and the fourth in 10
days.
   On May 3 Washington broadened the duties of the U.S. Navy in the
gulf, allowing American warships to intervene in attacks on
commercial ships, even if they are not sailing under the Stars and
Stripes.
   The executives said no American warships were believed to have
been in the vicinity of the Don Miguel when it was raided.
   All the recent Iranian attacks took place near the Iranian
offshore Larak oil terminal and all the ships were sailing to or
from Saudi Arabian ports.
   Iraqi jets raided Larak on May 14, hitting five tankers,
including the world's largest, the Seawise Giant.
   Iraq strikes Iran's oil facilities to pressure Tehran into
ending its 7{-year-old war with Iraq. Iran retaliates by attacking
neutral commercial shipping.
   In the land battle, Tehran radio late Thursday quoted a
statement by Iran's Revolutionary Guards saying that in the
fighting east of Basra, ``severe casualties were inflicted on the
enemy and more than 10,000 of them were killed or wounded.''
   It was the first time either side has reported any casualty
figures in this week's fighting, centered in the area between
Basra, a southern Iraqi city, and the Iranian border town of
Shalamcheh.
   Western military analysts say an estimated 35,000 to 40,000
Iraqi troops took part in the operation, retaking chunks of Iraqi
territory in the third military defeat for Iran since mid-May.
   Tehran radio, monitored by the British Broadcasting Corp., said
Iranian forces were continuing to resist the Iraqis from new
positions.
   Earlier the official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Cyprus, admitted that Iranian forces ``had to retreat from parts of
the area they had captured earlier.''
   It said the Iranians were now in ``new positions'' but gave no
details, in one of Tehran's rare acknowledgements that it had
suffered a military setback.
   The radio also reported ``large numbers'' of volunteers were
dispatched to the front from 19 cities across Iran in the 24 hours
following the Iraqi offensive.
   On April 18, Iraq recaptured its Faw Peninsula, which had been
occupied by Iranian forces since early 1986. On the same day, U.S.
forces destroyed two Iranian oil platforms and sank or damaged six
Iranian warships in the gulf.
   The U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, Vernon Walters,
arrived in Bahrain early today as part of a trip to the Middle East
for consultations on the Iraq-Iran war and the Palestinian problem.
   Walters already has visited Egypt, Israel, Jordan, Syria, Iraq,
Kuwait, Oman, the United Arab Emirates and Qatar.
</TEXT>
