<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChurchFlap     05-27 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Church Flap,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Faculty of 14 Resigns When Told Jewish Teachers Must Be Faithful
to Christ</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All 13 teachers at a church-run nursery
school have resigned after its governing board announced that all
faculty members, Christians and Jews alike, must profess faith in
Jesus Christ or quit.
   Five teachers and about half of the 82 toddlers at the First
Presbyterian Church of Sherman Oaks are Jewish, school director
Wendy Cummings said. A 23-year school employee, Ms. Cummings also
turned in her resignation Thursday.
   ``I am a Presbyterian, but I cannot conduct a school where I
have to explain to children that their teacher has been fired
because she is Jewish,'' she said. ``I do not believe in what they
are doing.''
   The governing board of the church voted Tuesday to change the
school from a non-religious nursery school to a ministry of the
church that teaches Christian principles, said Joe Kelly, clerk of
the church's 21-member board.
   As part of that plan, all teachers working by September 1989
must ``profess the Christian faith as a condition of employment,''
he said.
   ``Those who teach Christian teaching should subscribe to those
teachings themselves,'' the Revs. John and Pamela Powell, pastors
of the church, said in a statement. ``Christian teaching is not
simply an academic matter but a matter of an entire world view.''
   Some of the Jewish teachers accused the church of anti-Semitism.
   ``We were devastated,'' said Marilyn Freitag, who has taught at
the school for 14 years. ``I take it as a personal assault. They're
saying they don't want the Jewish influence.''
   The Powells denied the church was being anti-Semitic.
   ``The school will continue to be open to children of all races.
We are only trying to reorganize the teachings of the school,''
Powell said. Jewish teachers could remain if they are ``confessing
Christians,'' he said.
   Officials of the federal Equal Opportunity Employment Commission
and the Anti-Defamation League of the B'nai B'rith, a Jewish civil
rights organization, said the policy appeared to be legal.
   Attorney Robert Olmos of the employment commission said hiring
practices by religious institutions were exempted from the 1964
Civil Rights Act.
   The resignations are effective June 15, the end of the academic
year.
   Actress Pat Klous of television's ``Love Boat,'' singer Debbie
Boone and former astronaut Gordon Cooper are among parents whose
children either attend or attended the school.
   Ms. Klous, who is not Jewish, said she would withdraw her child.
``I'm heartbroken,'' she said.
   ``I can't see supporting a school where I don't believe in what
they do,'' said Cooper, whose wife is a volunteer substitute.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
