<2ND_LINE>PM-Western Sahara,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Referendum Reported Likely in War-torn Western Sahara</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar expects that a referendum can be held soon in the
disputed Western Sahara after 15 years of war, an aide said today.
   Perez de Cuellar made the assessment after meeting there today
with Mohamed Abdelaziz, president of what anti-Moroccan fighters
call the Saharawi Republic, said the aide, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   The aide spoke in Addis Ababa, where African leaders attending
an Organization of African Unity summit went into a closed session
to discuss the issue.
   He said the U.N. chief ``expects to be able to hold a referendum
in Western Sahara within the next few months.'' Aides also said de
Cuellar was confident of resolving the war between Abdelaziz's
Polisario Front fighters and Morocco.
   The peace process accelerated with this month's resumption of
diplomatic relations between Morocco and Algeria, the Polisario
Front's main backer.
   ``Our contacts with the parties encourage us to believe that,
given their continued cooperation and political will, a peaceful
solution to the problem can be found,'' the aide said.
   Morocco annexed the mineral-rich Western Sahara, previously a
Spanish province, in 1979. Morocco broke with the Organization of
African Unity in 1984 when the 50-member body recognized the
rebels' Saharawi Republic as a full member state.
</TEXT>
