<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Protest 1stLd-Writethru   05-27 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0556,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Protesting Employees At Luxury Hotel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, `Police, who ...' to UPDATE with fines
paid and workers released; CORRECTS spelling of Carlton throughout;
SUBS 9th pvs, `Larry MacArtney ...' to CORRECT spelling to
Macartney and UPDATE with hotel seeking meeting with workers</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baton-wielding riot police
today arrested 245 black employees of a luxury hotel as they
demonstrated against a U.S. company that is canceling its contract
to manage the hotel.
   The Westin Hotels Co. of Seattle had managed the Carlton Hotel
for 15 years. It reportedly decided to pull out of South Africa
because of pressure from the anti-apartheid movement.
   Hotel guests, including a contingent of travel agents from North
America and Europe, looked on in amazement as police ordered the
chanting protesters to disperse, then moved in with batons to begin
the arrests.
   Police, who have authority to declare virtually any outdoor
gathering illegal, said 142 men and 103 women were arrested. The
workers were released several hours later after the hotel
management paid $50 fines for each worker. Payment of the fines
acknowledges guilt for the gathering.
   During the first arrests, some protesters were beaten and flung
into police vans. Other employees _ including cooks in chef's hats
and a doorman in top hat and tails _ voluntarily moved toward the
vehicles to be taken to police headquarters.
   Westin announced last month that it would withdraw on June 6 as
manager of the Carlton.
   Workers carried signs accusing Westin of exploitation and told
reporters that the firm should pay them severance bonuses as part
of its disinvestment.
   The Carlton, one of the two luxury hotels in central
Johannesburg, is owned by the property division of Anglo American
Corp., South Africa's largest conglomerate.
   Larry Macartney, the hotel's marketing director, He said the
workers' contracts were with the hotel owners, not with Westin, and
were not affected by the disinvestment. He said the management
wanted to meet with the workers to explain the situation and hear
complaints.
   Before the confrontation with police, the protesters _ including
maids, bellhops and waiters _ trotted around the block on which the
Carlton and an adjoining high-rise office building stand.
   Inside the hotel, white employees served breakfast in the
restaurant and made beds, while departing guests carried their own
luggage.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
