<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Jarvik-Teen     05-27 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jarvik-Teen,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-Ager Dies After Receiving Jarvik Heart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 13-year-old who doctors said was the youngest
recipient of a Jarvik-7 artificial heart died eight hours after it
was implanted as a stopgap measure until a donor heart could be
found.
   Eric Rutkowski died Thursday night after developing pulmonary
edema, or fluid in the lungs, said St. Luke's Hospital spokeswoman
Diane De La Santos.
   The seventh-grader had suffered since February from viral
myocarditis, which destroys the heart, De La Santos said. He was
admitted to the hospital May 17 for evaluation for a transplant,
but his condition deteriorated rapidly. The decision to implant the
Jarvik-7 came Wednesday after an urgent request to the national
network for a donor heart came up empty, De La Santos said.
   Rutkowsky was the youngest ever recipient of the artificial
heart, used initially as a permanent heart replacement but now
employed as a bridge to a transplant.
   Christopher Larson, 15, of Esdaile, Wis., received a Jarvik-7 in
1987 at Abbott Northwestern Hospital in Minneapolis. He received a
donor heart a month later.
   St. Luke's is one of only 15 medical centers nationwide
permitted by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration to use the
Jarvik-7.
</TEXT>
