<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Duncan Retirement,0129</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rep. Duncan, Ranking Republican On Ways and Means, Announces
Retirement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. John Duncan, the ranking Republican
on the House Ways and Means Committee, announced today that he will
not seek a 13th term in Congress because he is suffering from
cancer.
   ``My heart says yes, but my doctors say no,'' the 69-year-old
congressman said in a statement.
   Duncan, the former mayor of Knoxville, was first elected to
Congress from Tennessee's 2nd District in 1964. He said he learned
he had prostate cancer in 1980.
   There had been speculation that Duncan's son Jimmy, a Knox
County Criminal Court judge, would run for the seat. The younger
Duncan's office said this morning that he would discuss his plans
later today.
</TEXT>
