<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru   05-27 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0599,0750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Palestinians Die After Woundings By Israeli Troops</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with 3-year-old reported killed
by tear gas. Pick up 8th graf pvs: `A 14-year-old...' Edits
thereafter to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers fired tear gas grenades at
Palestinian protesters in the Gaza Strip today, and a 3-year-old
girl who inhaled the gas died, Arab reports and Israel radio said.
   The army command confirmed the child's death but said the cause
could not exactly be determined.
   Also today, two Palestinian teen-agers shot by Israeli soldiers
during clashes in the occupied West Bank died, hospital officials
and Israel radio said.
   The deaths bring to 198 the number of Palestinians killed since
the Arab uprising in the occupied territories began last Dec. 8.
Two Israelis also have died.
   In Gaza City, hundreds o Moslem worshipers waving outlawed
Palestinian flags and black flags of mourning marched from a mosque
to the home of Ahmad Wazir, the cousin of the slain PLO military
chief Khalil Wazir, an Arab reporter said.
   The PLO leader, better known as Abu Jihad, was assassinated last
month in Tunis, reportedly by Israeli commandos. Israeli soldiers
blocked Palestinians from attending a ceremony at the cousin's home
Wednesday.
   Israel radio reported demonstrations in the Jabaliya refugee
camp and the towns of Khan Yunis and Rafah in Gaza.
   On Thursday, an Arab assailant stabbed a Jewish teen-ager in the
back as he walked through the Moslem quarter of Jerusalem's Old
City.
   Mayor Teddy Kollek called the attack on the seminary student an
isolated incident, but he said the nearly 6-month-long Palestinian
uprising has raised tensions between the city's Arabs and Jews.
   In the Old City, thousands of Moslem worshipers dispersed
peacefully after Sabbath prayers today.
   Officials at Gaza City's Ahli Arab hospital said relatives
brought Dina Sawafiri, claiming she died of tear gas fired by
Israeli troops in the Zaytoona neighborhood. Hospital officials
said the girl's 24-year-old aunt, Sabbah Sawafiri, also was treated
for tear gas effects.
   A relative who spoke on condition of anonymity said a tear gas
grenade landed in front of the family's house.
   A doctor at the hospital said the causes of Dina's death could
not be determined because the family took the girl's body and
buried it. The army command confirmed the report.
   A 14-year-old youth died at Jerusalem's Hadassah Hospital of a
wound to his head suffered Wednesday during a protest in the West
Bank refugee camp of Jalazone, Israel radio and Arab reports said.
   The radio said the boy apparently was shot accidentally when he
peeked out of his house. Arab reports identified him as Amin Rajab
Abu Radaha.
   Iyad Ibrahim Zaid, 16, died at east Jerusalem's Makassed
Hospital of bullet wounds to his chest and back. He was wounded
early in February during a demonstration in the West Bank town of
Qalqiliya, hospital officials said.
   Chanoch Albeck, 16, suffered a punctured lung when he was
attacked Thursday as he walked through the city's perfume market.
Police said the assailant shouted ``God is great'' before plunging
a kitchen knife into Albeck's back.
   Albeck was in stable condition today. Police rounded up 27
suspects.
   It was the second attack on a Jewish civilian in Jerusalem since
Dec. 8.
   On Dec. 28, a resident of Kiryat Arba was slightly wounded when
he was stabbed in the Old City.
   Hours after Thursday's stabbing, a firebomb was hurled at a
paramilitary border police patrol in Arab east Jerusalem's A-Tur
neighborhood, Israel radio said. There were no injuries or damage.
   Police spokesman Rafi Levy said police strength in Jerusalem
would remain at 1,200 because ``it's impossible to have police on
every corner ... We are assuring everyone that the city is safe.
This could have happened anywhere.''
   Israel seized the West Bank and east Jerusalem from Jordan and
the Gaza Strip from Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war. Israel
annexed east Jerusalem but maintains military governments in the
territories.
   Kollek called the stabbing an isolated incident.
   ``This is a very sad case, but for the last six months, not one
Jew or Arab has been killed in the city,'' he told The Associated
Press.
   The mayor said the uprising has strained relations between
Jerusalem's 340,000 Jews and 130,000 Arabs.
   ``We are living in an atmosphere of tension,'' Kollek said.
</TEXT>
