<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Tyson     05-27 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Tyson,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two PA Cops Who Accepted Gift Of Bentley Suspended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two police officers who accepted a $183,000
Bentley convertible from heavyweight boxing champion Mike Tyson _
then were forced to return it when their bosses found out _ have
been suspended for 10 days.
   Port Authority Officers Dana Bratton, 34, and Steven Barnes, 37,
were suspended without pay Thursday after a departmental hearing.
   The pair were in their squad car May 8 when they saw a
fender-bender involving Tyson's silver Bentley Convertible near the
entrance to the Holland Tunnel.
   ``I've had nothing but bad luck and accidents with this car. You
guys take this car and keep it,'' the New York Post quoted Tyson as
telling the officers.
   The two took the car to a garage in Jersey City, N.J., where it
stayed until Monday when rumors reached a police commander,
authorities said. The car was returned.
   The officers pleaded guilty to accepting a gratuity, conduct
unbecoming an officer, being off their posts and failure to file a
report, according to Lynn Tierney, a PA spokesman.
</TEXT>
