<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VoterCredit     05-27 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Voter Credit,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Income Tax Credit Proposed To Improve Voter Turnout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Idaho income tax credit is being proposed
to spur more people to go to the polls in the wake of the worst
voter turnout for any statewide election.
   ``I think it's in the best interest of government,'' said Ada
County Clerk John Bastida, who came up with the idea for a $5 voter
tax credit.
   Unofficial turnout in Tuesday's primary was less than 25 percent
of Idaho's 520,000 registered voters. Initial checks showed turnout
running about 22 percent in the larger counties and 15 percent in
Ada, the state's largest.
   ``When 15 percent of the people are dictating to the other 85
percent who their leaders are going to be, I think that's bad,''
Bastida said. ``There ought to be something gained from the people
going to the polls instead of saying, `I don't care. They're all
crooks anyway.'''
   He said voters could be given a stamp when they cast their
ballots and then place it on their state tax returns to show they
qualified for the break.
   ``I think the Legislature ought to turn around and take a look
at it,'' Bastida said.
</TEXT>
