<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AbandonedGirl     05-27 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abandoned Girl,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Whose Daughter Lost Legs To Frostbite Is Sentenced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CROWN POINT, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of a 9-year-old girl who
lost her lower legs to frostbite last winter after being locked in
an unheated apartment was sentenced today to 14 years in prison for
felony child neglect.
   Lake County Superior Court Judge Richard W. Maroc also said he
will recommend treatment for Darlwin J. Britt's cocaine habit while
the 29-year-old woman is in prison.
   The sentence had been specified in the plea bargain that spared
the daughter, Darlwin Carlisle, from testifying against her mother
and dropped two charges against the woman, but Maroc had the option
of a shorter prison term.
   The offense carries a maximum sentence of 20 years in prison.
   Construction workers boarding up an abandoned Gary house Jan. 17
discovered the child alone an unheated apartment. Investigators
said the girl had been in the apartment nearly 10 days during a
spell of near-zero temperatures.
   Surgeons later amputated her gangrenous legs below the knee.
   On May 6, Britt pleaded guilty to felony neglect, but defense
attorney Daniel Toomey said today he wanted to take the case to
trial. He did not explain his reasons.
   However, Maroc told Britt: ``I think you are locked into the
plea. I think it's a good plea, a valid one under the law.'' Toomey
asked the woman if she still accepted the plea, and she said, ``I
don't want to go to trial.''
   Child welfare authorities placed Darlwin with her paternal
grandmother after her release from the hospital. She has been
fitted with artificial legs.
   ``She still holds affection for her mother even though she
doesn't want to live with her,'' said Lake County Prosecutor Jack
F. Crawford.
</TEXT>
