<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru   05-27 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0470,0682</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Peace Talks Off To Shaky Start</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with rebels accusing
government of breaking promise to allow meeting with opposition.
Pick up 2nd pvs, `The Contras...' Edits thereafter to conform and
trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rebel delegation to peace talks
today accused the Sandinista government of breaking a promise to
allow them to meet with domestic opposition groups in the capital.
   ``We came to Managua because the Sandinista government had
offered us free movement and that we would meet with the opposition
parties, but that didn't occur last night,'' said Bosco Matamoros,
spokesman for the Nicaraguan Resistance.
   He said the rebel leaders had planned to meet Thursday night
with the Nicaraguan Democratic Coordinate, which groups political
parties and other groups that oppose the Sandinistas.
   ``The Sandinista government told us that they would come here,
and they told them that we would go there,'' Matamoros said. ``So,
they were waiting for us there and we for them here, and there
wasn't a meeting. We're going to see if they (the Sandinistas)
fulfill that promise today.''
   Despite the shaky start to the peace talks, the two sides
resumed talking this morning for the third round of top-level
discussions in Managua to seek an end to the 6{-year war. This
round began on Thursday.
   The Sandinistas on Thursday rejected the Contras' offer to
disarm if Nicaragua embraces democracy.
   The Contras, as the rebels are known, demanded that the
government guarantee complete press freedom within five days and
abolish the military draft within 60.
   They also demanded that the Sandinistas ease their control over
the army and government and allow the rebels to resupply their
forces in the field.
   Manuel Espinoza, the presidential spokesman, on Thursday
described the plan as ``preposterous.''
   ``The Contra proposal is unrealistic and casts aside all that
has been done and agreed upon until now and makes new proposals,''
Espinoza said.
   ``With this proposal, they're acting as if they had won the war
and the Sandinistas had surrendered,'' said Deputy Foreign Minister
Victor Hugo Tinoco.
   Tinoco said the government offered to discuss ``guarantees in
the electoral process, dates for municipal elections, reforms in
the electoral law, pluralistic representation in the electoral
council and guarantees and norms for the functioning of a mixed
economy.''
   Alfredo Cesar, chief of the rebel delegation, said the Contra
offer contained ``democratic changes the country should make at the
end of the war.''
   Cesar said the rebels were prepared to make a ``special effort
to achieve a definitive cease-fire.'' But he said the Contra
delegates were not optimistic about the outcome of the meeting and
said the government has not complied with a preliminary peace plan
agreed upon March 23 in Sapoa.
   At Sapoa, a Nicaraguan town near the border with Costa Rica, the
two sides agreed to a 60-day cease-fire and on the basis for
further talks to arrange a permanent truce.
   The cease-fire expires May 30, but President Daniel Ortega said
this week he would extend it for an additional 30 days.
   Rebel leaders have said they want a permanent truce but will not
break Ortega's unilateral extension of the cease-fire.
   Under what the rebels called a flexible timetable, they
indicated they would lay down their arms sometime before Christmas.
   ``It seems they are trying to bypass the Sapoa agreement,'' said
Bayardo Arce, vice coordinator of the political commitee of the
governing Sandinista National Liberation Front.
   In an interview, Arce said that Defense Minister Gen. Humberto
Ortega, head of the Nicaraguan delegation, told the Contra
delegates ``that the logical thing was to continue the discussions
under the Sapoa agreement.''
   The delegations are meeting under tight security at the Camino
Real Hotel. Contra representatives were permitted Thursday to leave
the hotel to visit relatives and political leaders.
   Roman Catholic Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo and Joao Baena
Soares, secretary-general of the Organization of American States,
attended as witnesses.
</TEXT>
