<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MilitaryLove     05-27 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Military Love,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marines Drop Charges Against Navy Officer Who Married Enlisted Man</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy officer and the Marine enlisted man
she married show that ``an officer and a gentleman can be a
couple,'' their attorney said after a general dismissed
fraternization charges.
   Lt. Kathleen A. Mazure, 29, was cleared after a 4{-hour hearing
Tuesday before Maj. Gen. Gene Deegan, commander of the Marine Air
Ground Combat Center at Twentynine Palms.
   ``The case ... was about whether the love of country by a member
of the military could somehow automatically and in all
circumstances preclude the love of another, also a member of the
military,'' said Mark Rosenbaum, an attorney for the American Civil
Liberties Union Foundation of Southern California.
   Ms. Mazure and her husband, Scott Price, 24, who resigned from
the Marines, showed that ``an officer and a gentleman could be a
couple and that there was something sick and cockeyed about
declaring for all members of the military _ even for members of
different branches _ that love at first sight or anytime thereafter
was always to be a crime,'' Rosenbaum said Thursday.
   Price, of Eden, Texas, married Ms. Mazure on Nov. 28.
   Charges were brought Nov. 25, marking ``the first time in the
history of the United States ... that charges of fraternization
have been brought against an officer for conduct with a member of
another branch of the service,'' Rosenbaum said, emphasizing that
the couple were not in the same chain of command.
   The charges had been recommended for court-martial. But on
Tuesday, Deegan held a hearing that resulted in dismissal of the
allegation, the attorney said.
   ``I love my husband. I love the Navy, and I don't see why the
two are not compatible,'' said Ms. Mazure, a dentist assigned to
Twentynine Palms. ``I hope that from out of this the fraternization
policy will become more defined.''
   Ms. Mazure said that she was stationed in Jacksonville, Fla.,
when she met Price during an evening of dancing in 1986 and that
neither knew the other was in the service until after several dates.
   They kept in touch by mail when Price was transferred to the
California desert base in 1987.
</TEXT>
