<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShootingVictim     05-27 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shooting Victim,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Innocent Victim In Drug Gang Shoot-out Can't Testify</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has decided a 67-year-old man
paralyzed in the crossfire of a crack cocaine shoot-out can't
testify in the case because his appearance could prejudice the jury.
   ``His speech therapist ... says he wants to testify, and I've
been over and talked to him, and he indicated to me he wants to
testify. I can't believe we can't put the victim on the stand,''
said Deputy District Attorney Michael Gaffey.
   Alameda County Superior Court Judge David Lee ruled Wednesday
after a hearing at the hospital bedside of Terry Brown, who is
paralyzed from the neck down and breathes with the help of a
respirator.
   Brown's appearance could jeopardize the defendants' right to a
fair trial, Lee said.
   ``The man was an innocent victim who stepped out of his house
and was shot _ he doesn't remember anything,'' said Ray Plumhoff,
an assistant public defender in the assault trial of Nate Porter,
20, and Johnny Lee Smith, 19.
   Porter and Smith are charged with assault in the June 30, 1987,
gunfight in which at least five men battled in the street outside
Brown's home.
   ``The only reason (te prosecutor) wanted to bring Mr. Brown in
was to prejudice the jury by showing how badly injured he was.''
   Brown was shot in the neck with an Uzi carbine as Porter's gang
shot it out with a rival gang led by Art Coleman, 21, who is
believed to have fired the shot that struck Brown, the prosecutor
said.
   Coleman was killed by three men who broke into his bedroom in
August 1987.
   Porter and Smith have been charged with the attack on Brown,
under the ``vicarious liability'' legal theory that says all
participants of a crime are equally responsible.
</TEXT>
