<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0482 05-27 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0482,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Not Worried About Polls, Likes ``Fighting Back''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush on polls, Noriega in top 18 grafs, picking
up in 9th graf pvs, ``It's largely; deletes last 4 grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, claiming the bracing
Maine air had invigorated him to step up his battle against
Democrat Michael Dukakis, declared today, ``I'm the underdog and I
like it.''
   ``He is the front-runner. He's been decreed that by poll after
poll,'' Bush told reporters in a news conference on the lawn of his
oceanside retreat.
   ``Do I worry about it? I don't worry about it. I like fighting
back,'' Bush said, brushing off recent polls suggesting Dukakis'
lead has been widening.
   He called for a resumption of collpased negotiations to remove
Panamanian Gen. Manuel Noriega from power, though he had previously
expressed reservations about the talks. He said the talks should
also include other nations if possible.
   Bush branded as ``an outrageous lie'' what he said was a
reported suggestion by Noriega that the negotiations were meant to
help Bush's campaign.
   ``When you read these outrageous charges by a drug-related,
indicted dictator, discount them. They are total lies,'' he said.
   Bush, with the pounding surf of the Atlantic to his back, also
said if elected he would personnally countermand any effort by the
Secret Service to close off the nearby waters to lobstermen as a
security precaution.
   ``That is absolutely absurd,'' he said. ``They will continue to
fish here and they will continue to be welcome.''
   As a sole lobster boat worked its pots in a cove several hundred
yards away, Bush said he would give up coming to his Maine retreat
rather than see the waters closed.
   Bush is here for a week of talks with advisers and prominent
Republicans. Among today's visitors were Govs. John McKernan of
Maine, John Sununu of New Hampshire and James Thompson of Illinois
as well as former Housing Secretary Carla Hills and former deputy
Treasury Secretary Richard Darman.
   Of the recent polls, Bush said, ``things aren't in focus yet. It
is May. The election is in November.''
   A Washington Post-ABC poll today reported that Dukakis had a
13-point lead over Bush _ and that among female voters, the
Massachusetts governor was ahead by a 60-30 margin.
   Bush conceded that the ``gender gap'' was a major concern. He
said it was at the top of today's discussion list, in fact.
   ``What I've got to do is more clearly define what I feel on
certain women's issues. One of them will be day care.''
   Bush promised to come out of his one-week break swinging.
   ``When I get up here I feel _ it's not feistiness _ but I feel
very relaxed about it. I don't feel troubled by somebody pointing
out I'm behind in the polls. ... I'm coming out of 10 points down
in these polls and I've got five months to fight back.''
   ``There's a little bit of a cholesterol rise, the frustration
level going up, in terms of sitting around and listening to (Jesse)
Jackson and Michael Dukakis dump all over me and the the
administration. So I'm beginning to get a little more combative,''
Bush said.
   One day earlier, Bush pollster Robert Teeter conceded that
Bush's ``gender gap'' seemed to be far worse than that ever faced
by President Reagan, who also had more support among men than women
voters.
   ``It's largely for institutional reasons. It's got more to do
with party than it does with candidates. But it did close in 1984
as we got close to the election, although it never closed
completely. There is an institutional and a party gender gap and
we're going to make a very strong effort to close it,'' Teeter said.
   Bush staff chief Craig Fuller said that the vice president would
focus on domestic affairs in sessions on Friday and Saturday and
would meet with economic advisers next Tuesday and Wednesday to
flesh out his fall campaign positions.
   Fuller said that Bush was not overly concerned about recent
polls that showed him falling behind Dukakis.
   ``There are some advantages to being the underdog and fighting
back,'' Fuller said.
   Campaigning in New Jersey on Thursday, Bush focused on the war
against drugs, calling for a requirement that government contracts
be awarded only to companies that have ``drug free'' programs for
their employes.
   Aides said that the proposal could involve some form of
mandatory drug testing for all companies doing busines with the
government, although details had not been worked out.
   Bush also called for an international drug ``strike force'' that
would seek out and destroy drug crops wherever they were found.
   And he said he would put ``a single military figure'' in charge
of coordinating U.S. participation in such an effort. Bush has said
that the overall anti-drug effort in his administration would be
headed by the vice president.
  
</TEXT>
