<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mormons-AIDS     05-27 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mormons-AIDS,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Urge Members To Join In AIDS Prevention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mormon Church members should join in legal
and political efforts to stop the spread of AIDS, but the best
defense is obedience to the doctrine of chastity before marriage
and fidelity after, the faith's First Presidency said Friday.
   In a two-page statement, the three-member presidency praised
efforts to find a medical solution to AIDS, but reiterated church
teaching on sexual relations:
   ``The Lord has not left mankind without clear guidance on
matters that affect our happiness. That guidance is chastity before
marriage, total fidelity in marriage, abstinence from all
homosexual relations, avoidance of illegal drugs and reverence and
care for the body.''
   The First Presidency governs the 6.5 million-member Church of
Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints. Its members are President Ezra
Taft Benson and counselors Gordon B. Hinckley and Thomas S. Monson.
   The statement quoted from an earlier sermon in which Hinckley
urged people to disdain ``carnal attractions that often result in
the tragedies that follow moral transgression.''
   The statement urged compassion for victims of the deadly disease
and said members should work through legal and political channels
to help combat it.
