<DOCNO> AP880527-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MoscowAtItsBest Bjt   05-27 0875</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moscow At Its Best, Bjt,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lilacs Blooming, Stores Stocked _ It's Moscow At Its Best</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, in his first visit to the Soviet
capital, will see an enormous city of 12-lane boulevards dominated
in part by seven massive Stalin-era Baroque buildings. He will see
the city at its best: the lilacs are blooming, the weather is mild
and downtown stores are stocked with meat and tomatoes.
   Arriving for the first time in the Soviet capital is at times
like taking a trip back in time. The electrical appliances seem
old-fashioned and traffic jams are rare, though smog has taken hold.
   Nearly 9 million people live here, yet the only time it seems
crowded is when people are queuing to buy food, perfume, and other
scarce consumer goods. Humans are dwarfed by immense buildings,
both the charmless, modern structures from the 1960s _ said to be
modeled on buildings Nikita Khrushchev saw and liked in New York
City _ and a variety of monuments to mother Russia's war heroes.
   Few of the cars are new, almost all are Soviet-made, and
taxicabs seem scarce, at least to the legion of visitors who
arrived this week to prepare for the Reagan-Gorbachev summit.
   Most Muscovites do not own cars, and so while Central Committee
and Politburo members are whisked into the Kremlin during the
morning rush hour and out again at dusk, millions of commuters use
the city's excellent subway or local bus and trolley systems.
   The Kremlin is not one big building, like the Pentagon for
example. Instead, it is a walled citadel of government buildings,
cathedrals, towers and arsenals dating back to the 14th Century.
``Alcatraz on the outside, Versailles on the inside,'' in the words
of one American.
   Some of the city's best known sites _ the red-and-white and
yellow-and-blue onion domes of St. Basil's Cathedral, cobblestoned
Red Square and the Bolshoi Theater _ sit just outside the Kremlin`s
red-brick wall.
   The words ``grim,'' ``drab,'' ``dreary,' and ``unkempt'' are
often used to describe Moscow, but the sunny skies _ the first in
10 months _ the sweet-smelling purple lilacs and the pre-summit
spruce-up helps overcome the feeling of grayness brought on in
large part by decades of listless architecture.
   ``It's not Paris, but it's a lot prettier that it was two months
ago,'' said Richard Gilbert, an American Embassy spokesman.
   Soldiers, in their gray tunics and green hats, are shining the
huge swinging metal doors on government buildings.
   Women on hands and knees are planting begonias in front of the
Kremlin wall, workers are mowing the grass sprinkled with yellow
dandelions and plasterers are touching up the Union of Writers'
Club, where Reagan will visit. A three-man team is painting the
flagpoles of the Pushkin Museum.
   Residents seem excited about the upcoming Reagan visit.
   At the Hotel Rossiya, home to many of the American journalists
and officials working at the summit, the local employees _ not
widely known for wasting pleasantries _ are going out of their way
to be helpful.
   The dezhurni, Russian ``key ladies'' who are posted day and
night on each hotel floor _ smile when you turn in the key after
leaving the room. Service may be slow, but this week at least it is
service with a smile.
   ``Service is impossible here,'' said George Black, a businessman
from Basking Ridge, N.J., who has dealt with the Soviets in his
advertising business. ``There's no motivation, that's the
problem,'' he said.
   Black and his wife, Ruth, say they have deep affection for the
Soviet people. ``When you get to know them, they are very nice,''
he said. For Americans, the language barrier is a real problem, he
said, because the Soviets may seem rude when they are really just
embarrassed at not being able to communicate.
   While Soviet bureaucrats and law enforcement officials generally
wear a dour expression, young people were smiling as they strolled
in the May sunshine along the broad sidewalks of Kalinin Prospekt,
Moscow's ``Fifth Avenue,'' where behind the glass shop windows are
a paltry number of fashions and consumer products.
   Moscow has little street crime, no doubt partly a result of the
omnipresence of police. There are so many uniformed officers that
they sometimes seem to be watching one another.
   The Moscow militia says none of Moscow's 60 banks has been
robbed in 20 years.
   The hotels have plenty of food on hand for the summit,
attracting large numbers of Soviets who filled their bellies, and
in some cases their pockets, with such rarities as tomatoes,
sausages and cheese _ items that the locals say have not been seen
for weeks in most stores.
   The beriozkas, special hotel shops which accept only Western
currency, are freshly stocked for the summit, and foreign residents
of the city have been seen carting cases of wine to their waiting
cars _ a basic precaution in a society where such commodities may
not reappear for months.
   Renee Fisher, a teacher from Tampa, Fla., said her biggest
disappointment on her trip to the Soviet Union is that the
facilities are ``dirty and unhygienic.'' But that hardly affected
her trip, she said.
   ``The people are so nice and they love Americans,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
