<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BoneProbe     05-27 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bone Probe,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medical Examiner Target of Investigation Over Bone Extractions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A medical examiner under investigation
for supplementing his income selling bones from the dead for up to
$425 a body had the approval of his superiors, the county's chief
administrator says.
   ``Unless we are given some new information that it legally
should not continue, then it will,'' said Tom Vickers, head of the
Bexar County commission.
   County Chief Medical Examiner Dr. Vincent DiMaio said Thursday
he earned about $50,000 since 1983 removing bones for the
non-profit Bone Bank Foundation of San Antonio, which used them in
transplants.
   Prosecutors are examining whether he violated the law in
removing the bones in county facilities or on county time, said
Assistant District Attorney Nelson ``Skip'' Atwell.
   ``We will talk to him and the county auditor and then we'll sit
down and evaluate the thing and see if it's a commissioner's court
issue, or something we should be involved in or something nobody
should be involved in,'' Atwell said.
   DiMaio, who was among several pathologists who exhumed Lee
Harvey Oswald's body in Dallas for reexamination in 1981, said he
has charged between $175 and $425 per body for removing bones from
corpses sent to the Medical Examiner's Office.
   A gunshot wound expert who also supplements his $92,000-a-year
salary by testifying at civil and criminal trials, DiMaio said that
he had county approval and that consent forms were obtained from
survivors.
   ``I charged for my time, on my own time, not on the county's
time,'' he said. ``They may be able to change their minds, but they
can't ever say they weren't informed.''
   Vickers said that the county commissioners in 1983 agreed to let
DiMaio do work for the Bone Bank Foundation and decided the county
would bill the foundation $25 per case for use of the facilities,
Vickers said.
   ``It was all above board,'' Vickers said. ``As far as I can
tell, he didn't try to hide anything. His statement was given in
open court, in front of attorneys and auditors.''
   DiMaio likened his role to a physician removing a heart from an
accident victim for use in another transplant. ``Everyone is paid
for their services,'' he said.
   At the foundation, the bones are cleaned and chopped into pieces
and freeze-dried for use in transplants, mostly for back, dental or
reconstructive surgery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
