<HEAD>Japanese Police Seize Heroin, Arrest Five</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities seized 9.4 pounds of heroin and
arrested five men from Hong Kong in the second-largest heroin bust
in Japan, police said Friday.
   The heroin, with an estimated street value of $3 million, was
discovered in two suitcases when four of the men arrived at Tokyo's
Narita airport, a National Police Agency drug enforcement officer
said.
   The officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said four of
the men were arrested Sunday. A fifth man, believed to be the
leader of the group, arrived at the airport Monday and was arrested.
   All five had entered Japan several times since July and were
targeted by customs agents as possible drug smugglers, he said.
   Japan's largest heroin-smuggling case was broken in December
1985, when 10.1 pounds were confiscated, the officer said. Last
year, a total of 10.6 pounds of the drug was seized, he said.
