<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0590,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Calls for Indian Summit, Noriega-Dealings Probe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Jackson speaking to Indians in top 9 grafs,
picking up in 7th graf, ``Half our</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANNE BUCKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Jesse
Jackson told Indian leaders today that Indians have been ignored by
the government and ``it's not too much to ask for a summit with the
American Indian leadership.''
   Jackson spoke to the Indian group at the All Indian Pueblo
Council today, one day after telling a separate audience that the
American public deserves a full-scale congressional investigation
of U.S. dealings with Panamanian Gen. Manuel Noriega.
   The U.S. government should ``not negotiate with drug dealers,''
Jackson said Thursday.
   Vice President George Bush and President Reagan have been plea
bargaining with Noriega, Jackson said.
   ``We need and deserve a full-scale congressional
investigation,'' he said. ``So far, we've heard one side of the
story ... they've been trying to smoke him out, buy him out, the
deal being (Noriega's) silence.''
   He told the Indians today that they should not surrender their
values.
   Jackson hearkened back to the beginning of his Rainbow Coalition
and called for people to work together.
   ``Hispanics in the barrios, blacks in the ghettos, ranchers on
ranches, Indians on reservations. ... There's a tendency of these
people to be abandoned by law,'' he said. ``The real challenge is
to begin to pull together our various backgrounds and find common
ground ... to turn to each other and not on each other.''
   On Thursday, Jackson spoke to the National Federation of
Democratic Women as the group opened its annual convention here,
and he lamented what he said were inequities women face in society.
   ``Half our nation is female. Half of our poor children live in a
house run by poor women where there is no man,'' he said. ``Women
make 65 cents on a dollar to what a man makes. ...
   ``Your self-respect is not negotiable,'' he said. ``You've
earned the right to expect ERA (the Equal Rights Amendment) to be
in the (Democratic Party) platform.''
   Dukakis was to speak to the women's group later today.
   Jackson also talked of the government's need to stop the flow of
drugs into the United States.
   ``Drugs affect our family. Drugs affect our children in schools.
Drugs affect the safety of our streets,'' he said. ``Drugs are the
No. 1 threat to our national security.''
   Jackson, in the final weeks of campaigning for his party's
nomination, made several campaign appearances in California earlier
in the day.
   The obviously tired and hoarse candidate also criticized a small
movement in the United States that wants to make English the
official language of the country in a reference to the upcoming
summit between Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``Reagan is going to meet with Gorbachev this week in Moscow,''
he said. ``It's the right thing to do. It's a step in the right
direction. ... I hope our translator does not speak English only.''
   Jackson's visit to New Mexico was the second this month.
   Polls indicate Jackson is running far behind Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis for the June 7 primary.
   Dukakis has 1,700 delegates for the nomination, while Jackson
has 983 according to the Associated Press. Another 443 delegates
still are uncommitted, and a candidate needs at least 2,081 to win
the nomination.
   New Mexico will have 28 delegates to the Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta this summer.
</TEXT>
