<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Academy Award winners Shirley MacLaine, Sally
Field and Olympia Dukakis will come to terms with life, death and
marriage in a small Southern town in the movie version of ``Steel
Magnolias.''
   The film, based on the acclaimed off-Broadway play about six
women in a small Louisiana town, also will star Dolly Parton and
Daryl Hannah, the movie's producer, Ray Stark, said. One of the six
major female roles is yet to be cast.
   Shooting is to begin July 12 in Natchitoches, La., and should be
completed by early September, said Stark.
   ``Herb Ross (who will direct) and I have put together what I
think is the most exciting ensemble cast since George Cukor did
`The Women''' in 1939, Stark said.
   That cast included Joan Crawford, Norma Shearer, Rosalind
Russell, Paulette Goddard, Joan Fontaine, Marjorie Main and Hedda
Hopper.
   ``Steel Magnolias''' focuses on life at a small-town beauty shop
owned by Ms. Parton's character.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If this is New York, it could be Baltimore to
Tom Selleck.
   His new movie, ``Her Alibi,'' is to begin shooting June 27 in
Baltimore, though it's set in New York and Connecticut.
   Location crews won't reveal much about the Marty Elfand movie,
but Selleck, 43, is expected to be here for much of the eight to 10
weeks of shooting, said Drew Friedman, international account
executive for the film commission.
   Except for a few establishing shots in New York, much of the
movie will be filmed in Maryland, he said.
   ``If we just waited for every Baltimore script to come down the
pike, we'd be sitting here, collecting dust, I think,'' said
Friedman.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burt Reynolds and Loni Anderson are
officially married. They just can't prove it.
   Reynolds built a special chapel for the April 29 wedding, and
hired a special caterer and a motorized stagecoach. But he forgot
where he put the marriage license.
   ``He called us the day before the wedding and said he couldn't
seem to find it,'' said John Dunkle, Palm Beach County clerk of
courts. ``He wanted to know what to do.''
   Dunkle had delivered the license application to Reynolds at his
Jupiter ranch March 2.
   The application is good for 60 days. Burt and Loni were married
on the 57th day. All Reynolds had to do was get the minister and
two witnesses to sign the license after the ceremony.
   Someone in Dunkle's office later sent Reynolds a duplicate. One
of Reynolds' assistants, Elaine Hall, is mailing it around so the
witnesses can sign it.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A visitor who regularly waddles into the garden at
No. 10 Downing St. won't leave without a swim and a drink in the
future if Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher has her way.
   Mrs. Thatcher said Friday she plans to build a pond for a duck
from a nearby park that has turned up at the back door of her
official residence and laid some eggs.
   Mrs. Thatcher, whose cat-in-residence died last week after 14
years as the No. 10 mouser, told patients at Papworth Hospital in
Cambridgeshire, northeast of London, of her plans.
   ``We are going to have a little bit of water put in, because we
have a duck that comes across from St. James's Park and lays her
eggs,'' said the prime minister.
   Mrs. Thatcher said the visitor never met up with Wilberforce,
the cat who served four prime ministers after straying into Downing
Street in 1973. Wilberforce, who retired to the countryside a year
ago, died at the age of 15.
   A Downing Street spokeswoman, who was not identified in keeping
with British custom, said she didn't have any further details about
a duck, but said, ``they do fly in from time to time.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT PAYNE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randy Owen, lead singer of Alabama, is
tired of hearing people say the group's seventh annual charity
bash, June Jam, will be its last.
   ``I don't know how all of that got started. But none of its
true,'' he said.
   Owen said the concerts ``will continue as long as the people of
the state of Alabama _ from the governor's office on down to the
people in Fort Payne who volunteer to work with us every year _
want it to go on.''
   June Jam VII is scheduled June 11 on a field behind Fort Payne
High School in the band's hometown. Artists scheduled to appear
with Alabama include K.T. Oslin, Sweethearts of the Rodeo, Carl
Perkins, Mel McDaniel, Ricky Van Shelton, Gary Morris, Exile,
Restless Heart, Dan Seals, Charlie Daniels Band, Eddy Raven and the
Shooters.
   The June Jam festivities begin June 9, when Owen and band member
Teddy Gentry will play in a charity softball game with former
Atlanta Braves pitchers Phil Niekro and Rick Camp. The next day
there will be a benefit golf tournament with former New Orleans
quarterback Kenny Stabler, Auburn University football Coach Pat
Dye, and University of Alabama at Birmingham basketball Coach Gene
Bartow.
   The first five June Jams raised huge sums for charities, with
attendance peaking at 60,000 in 1986. Last year, the concert was
hit with heavy rains, attendance fell to 20,000, and there was
nothing left after expenses to give to charity.
</TEXT>
