<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Out-Of-BodyLivers     05-27 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Out-Of-Body Livers,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surgeon Repairs Livers Outside Body</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hoping to buy time for victims of one of the
bleakest forms of cancer, a West German surgeon is repairing livers
outside the body, a procedure believed to be the first of its kind.
   ``I think it may help some patients for whom we couldn't do
anything else,'' said Dr. Rudolf Pichlmayr of the University of
Hannover Medical School.
   Pichlmayr said that he has removed, repaired and replaced livers
three times, including twice this month. Malignant liver tumors
left no choice, he said. The repairs took four to five hours.
   The patients, two women and a man, were doing well, Pichlmayr
said Thursday by telephone from West Germany.
   ``They are improved dramatically,'' he said. ``I'm afraid those
patients might get a reoccurrence of the disease. But I feel the
justification to do it because it's the best possible retaliation''
against cancer.
   He said that because of the nature of liver cancer, the patients
would probably eventually develop new tumors, either in the liver
or elsewhere, but the operation at least will prolong their lives.
   Previously, such bench surgery was limited to the
well-established repair of blood vessels or the removal of cysts
and tumors in kidneys, which are less delicate and less vital to
sustaining life than the liver.
   ``It's a very intriguing development,'' said liver transplant
pioneer Dr. Thomas Starzl of the University of Pittsburgh.
   ``I can see how it might be a significant advance, although we
really must wait and see,'' he said.
   ``My hat's off to him. It's a monumental effort,'' said liver
transplant surgeon Dr. John S. Najarian of the University of
Minnesota. He has tried liver transplants on four liver cancer
patients, only one of whom is still alive.
   Liver cancer is among the deadlier forms of the disease, said
National Cancer Institute spokesman Frank Mahaney. Early detection
gives patients a 10 percent to 30 percent chance of surviving for
five years. Late detection leaves a mere 3 percent chance.
   Pichlmayr performed the first operation Feb. 5 to remove cancer
that more than doubled the weight of a 40-year-old woman's liver.
   The woman has since returned home.
   He said a transplant might have wasted a valuable donor organ
because the cancer had spread beyond her liver, and he avoided
traditional in-body repairs because of the tumor's size and central
location.
   As he removed the organ, Pichlmayr installed a pump that kept
blood flowing through the two main explosed blood vessels. Outside
the body, the liver was cooled with ice water and flushed
periodically with a special fluid to keep it fresh.
   Pichlmayr described the procedure in a West German medical
journal in April.
   ``She's gained weight again, and at this moment she's very
healthy,'' he said. ``She was suffering extremely, and I think she
would not be alive now.''
   Pichlmayr performed liver bench surgery again May 6 on a
48-year-old woman and May 11 on a 58-year-old man.
   ``The lady is at home, quite well,'' he said. ``The man is still
in the hospital, but is good.''
   Also this year, Pichlmayr did the world's first split-liver
transplant, dividing one liver and implanting the halves into two
patients.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
