<2ND_LINE>PM-Alias Scam,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three-Time Burglar Slipped Through Courts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A burglar used three aliases to stay out of jail
and one step ahead of the law, police said.
   Three times, using different names, Anthony Dearill Eiland
pleaded guilty to burglary, and each time was placed on probation.
   Investigators said they caught up with Eiland, as he's now known
by police, after eight months when they jailed a man named Joe
Smith last week and matched his fingerprints with three other sets
on file.
   Police said Eiland may have taken advantage of a backlog of
paperwork.
   Incomplete computer records used to research Eiland's burglary
cases at the district attorney's office alternately omitted Social
Security numbers and fingerprint ID numbers, said Norman Kinne,
first assistant district attorney.
   ``Unless you knew the names,'' he said, ``you wouldn't hit on
it.''
   The suspect was being held on more than $50,000 bail on charges
including burglary, violating probation, an evading arrest and an
investigative charge of failure to identify himself.
</TEXT>
