<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     05-27 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Najib Chooses New Prime Minister As Soviets Withdraw</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One word for Najib cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib chose a new prime
minister from outside his governing party in an effort to widen his
support base as Soviet troops withdraw, leaving the government to
face Moslem guerrillas alone.
   However, the president's choice, 62-year-old Mohammad Hasan
Sharq, has been closely associated with the party. He has been a
deputy prime minister in Najib's government for the past 11 months.
   His promotion, announced late Thursday by official Kabul radio,
must be approved by the National Assembly, which is expected to
convene in a few days. Confirmation is virtually certain because
the body is controlled by Najib's People's Democratic Party and
allied groups.
   Sharq was entrusted with primary responsibility for repatriating
an estimated 5 million refugees _ one-third of the country's
population _ who have fled since Soviet troops entered Afghanistan
in 1979 to help the government in its war with the guerrillas.
   He would replace Prime Minister Sultan Ali Keshtmand, a ranking
member of the governing party since its founding in 1965.
Keshtmand, 52, was appointed to the post in 1981 by Najib's
predecessor, Babrak Karmal. Keshtmand was named secretary of the
central committee of the governing party.
   Najib has repeatedly professed a desire to bring more non-party
men into his government as Moscow withdraws its troop.
   However, the test of whether such a declaration will have real
basis or be primarily cosmetic may come when Sharq's Cabinet is
named.
   ``If they simply move to reshuffle the furniture, it's not going
to be significant,'' a Western diplomat said Friday.
   Most of the current 34 Cabinet members are either members of the
party or closely tied to it. The exact breakdown is unknown because
of the shadowy nature of Afghan politics.
   Najib's declarations of plans to broaden his government has not
ended guerrilla attacks.
   From their bases in Pakistan, the guerrillas have announced they
captured at least a dozen Afghan army border posts since April 15,
when the Soviet Union agreed to start pulling out its troops.
   Under the withdrawal agreement, the more than 10,000 Kremlin
soldiers in Afghanistan are to leave by next February. Moscow says
9,000 already have crossed the Amu Darya River into the Soviet
Union since the withdrawal began May 15.
   Najib's choice of Sharq as prime minister also appeared to
lessen the chances of former King Zahir Shah returning to Kabul to
preside over any transition from the present Soviet-style socialist
government to a more broadly-based government.
   The restoration of the king, in a role ranging from figurehead
to active player, has been a topic of speculation in both Eastern
and Western diplomatic circles since the Kremlin decided to end its
military intervention.
   Sharq was Cabinet chief of staff when Mohammad Daoud, a cousin
of the former king, served as prime minister from 1953 to 1963.
However, during that decade, the king exercised little power.
   Daoud resigned in 1963 at Zahir Shah's behest and then overthrew
him in 1973.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
