<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ConvictLawyer     05-27 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Convict Lawyer,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Prisoner Poses As Lawyer Then Disappears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ex-convict tricked a lawyer into sending
him a resume then assumed the attorney's identity, collecting
thousands of dollars in legal fees and defending a man in court
before disappearing, authorities said.
   James Klaver was out of prison awaiting retrial in a rape case
when he began impersonating Richard Keffler, a real-life lawyer in
Texas who also practices in Florida, Seminole County authorities
said.
   Klaver had all the credentials of a lawyer, including an ID card
from the Florida Bar and numerous law books.
   He collected more than $3,000 in retainer fees from clients and
appeared before Orange County Circuit Judge Ted Coleman on April
18, representing a drug user.
   Coleman said Wednesday he had been suspicious about Klaver but
didn't say anything at the time.
   ``I thought he was the defendant,'' said the judge. ``I guess to
judges, lawyers are like pornography _ we don't know what it is,
but we know it when we see it.''
   The case eventually was reassigned to a real lawyer, with the
client pleading guilty to cocaine possession.
   Investigators said Klaver, who was released from prison in
December when his conviction and 60-year rape sentence were
overturned, had called Keffler in March.
   Keffler said Klaver claimed to be a business owner planning to
expand into Texas. He said the man wanted him to handle the firm's
legal matters. Keffler sent Klaver his resume.
   Within weeks, Klaver was pretending to be Keffler, police said.
   Seminole County sheriff's Sgt. Jerry Human and Deputy Robin
Yolton said Klaver moved into an office also used by attorney
Angela Blakeley after telling her he was being placed on a list of
lawyers available for court-appointed work.
   Klaver began taking cases and accepting fees.
   ``He appeared legitimate,'' said Ms. Blakeley. ``All his
references checked out.''
   Officials discovered the ruse after a man charged with writing
bad checks complained that his lawyer had abandoned him after
collecting a $200 retainer.
   Investigators have asked the state attorney's office to file
charges of forgery, obtaining property by false impersonation and
theft against Klaver.
   A spokesman for the Florida Bar, Jerry Butterfield, said the bar
may have to tighten controls on its ID cards, possibly adding
photographs.
   Ms. Blakeley said that when Klaver disappeared, he took more
than $10,000 in law books and computer equipment, including all her
business records, and collected about $10,000 from her own clients.
   He fled in a car he bought under the name and credit rating of
Keffler, authorities said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
