<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ConvoytoNicaragua     05-27 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convoy to Nicaragua,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convoy Takes Humanitarian Goods to Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five old trucks and buses, driven by U.S.
veterans, left the capital Friday as part of the nationwide
``Veterans Peace Convoy'' bearing food, medical supplies, clothing
and toys for the children of Nicaragua.
   The contingent will merge June 5 in Austin, Texas, with several
other conveys that originated in northern cities a week ago. Then
the entire group, involving 50 vehicles and 100 drivers, will begin
the drive through Mexico, Guatemala and Honduras to Nicaragua.
   Robert Livesay, a Dorchester, Mass., veteran who hatched the
project and heads the group that started in Boston, said a total of
about 40 tons of humanitarian aid will be delivered by the convoy
to private relief agencies in Nicaragua.
   ``This is a people-to-people project to feed children, not a
government one to feed war,'' Livesay said.
   The veterans' drive also is designed to promote the larger ``Let
Nicaragua Live'' program, under which various peace groups plan to
send 4,200 tons of oats to Nicaragua via container ships this year.
   The various legs of the convoy will pass through 40 states, with
stops in 90 cities, Livesay said. Other groups started in Seattle;,
Missoula, Mont.; Minneapolis; Dayton, Cleveland and Cincinnati,
Ohio, and Portland, Ore.
   Among the donated supplies driven by the veterans are hospital
equipment, powdered milk, and oral rehydration salts to help battle
diarrhea, the No. 1 cause of death among Nicaraguan infants. The
trucks also will carry stuffed animals and baseball equipment for
the children.
   Livesay said he got the idea for the drive during a trip to
northern Nicaragua last fall on behalf of the Veterans for Peace.
   When another veteran mentioned the possibility of a U.S.
invasion aimed at Nicaragua's leftist government, he said,
``Something clicked. I said he ought to invade this place ourselves
with a convoy of real humanitarian aid.''
   Livesay said, ``The kids were saw were malnourished, with
discolored hair and distended stomachs, without clothes. The war
had really begun to destroy the ability of the people in the
countryside to produce.''
   ``I saw the situation developing the same way it did in
Vietnam,'' said Livesay, who worked for the Air Force security
branch in Vietnam and Thailand in the 1960s. ``I couldn't believe
that after 20 years, we just hadn't learned our lesson.''
   He said the relief materials will be handed over to
non-governmental social service agencies in Nicaragua, including
the Institute of John XXIII and the Red Cross.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
