<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Eastern-Pentagon     05-27 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern-Pentagon,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Decides Against Suspending Eastern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force announced today it would
continue to allow Eastern Airlines the right to carry military
passengers but said it would closely watch the carrier after
inspectors reported ``performance deficiences.''
   The Military Airlift Command said Eastern was the subject of a
``commercial carrier survey'' in March. Air Force inspectors said
they found ``performance deficiencies which, if not corrected,
could affect the safety of the half-million DOD (Department of
Defense) personnel who annually fly on Eastern aircraft.''
   The airline handled about $87 million worth of military travel
business in fiscal 1987.
   The decision to extend Eastern's right to handle military
business was made by the Commercial Airlift Review Board, a panel
created in the aftermath of the December 1985 crash of a chartered
Arrow Air DC-8 that left 248 soldiers dead.
   Eastern was told April 11 that suspension proceedings were being
started.
   Officials of the airline met with the Air Force on April 25 and
convinced the service they were addressing the problems, Lt. Col.
Nick Lacey, chief of the Air Carrier Survey Office, said today.
   ``They went out of their way to address these as serious
concerns,'' Lacey told a reporter. The Air Force ended up extending
Eastern's right to carry military passengers but also decided to
continue in-flight survey observations, he said.
   ``The book is still open,'' Lacey added.
   Lacey said the Air Force survey team expressed concern about
pilot turnover, poor morale among both air crew and maintenance
personnel, antagonism between management and employees and the
level of manning for certain operations. The military inspectors
also questioned whether Eastern was doing enough to audit and
oversee contractors providing maintenance service, Lacey said.
   Eastern is a unit of Texas Air Corp. that is locked in bitter
dispute with employee unions. Last month, the airline was the focus
of an unusally broad safety investigation by the Federal Aviation
Administration that involved inspections of all of its airplanes.
   Corporate officers of Eastern maintain most of the complaints
about airline operation can be traced to disaffected union workers
and that the carrier is not scrimping when it comes to safety.
   ``They (the Air Force) did have some questions concerning
airline safety and maintenance,'' said Paula Musto, an Eastern
spokeswoman in Miami. ``But we reviewed everything with them and we
think we satisfied their questions. We welcome any inspections,
observations or whatever.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
