<HEAD>Energy Board Now Will Have Two Vacancies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Another member of the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission has resigned, leaving the five-member board
with two vacancies and only one sitting member with a regular
appointment.
   Commissioner Anthony Sousa, 60, whose second four-year term
would have expired in October, will leave the commission July 31 to
become U.S. bankruptcy trustee for northern and eastern California
and Nevada, based in San Francisco, the commission announced Friday.
   Two of the three remaining members, Chairman Martha Hesse and
Charles Stalon, are holdovers. Their terms expired last October,
and unless successors are confirmed earlier, they must leave this
coming October. President Reagan has renominated Ms. Hesse as
chairman, but the Senate Energy Committee has not acted on the
nomination.
   The term of Charles Trabandt also expires in October. The fifth
member, Charles Naeve, resigned last month.
   Sousa is a former vice president and general counsel of the
Hawaiian Telephone Co. and a former counsel and administrative law
judge at the California Public Utilities Commission.
   Bankruptcy trustees work under the supervision of bankruptcy
judges in administering bankruptcy cases.
</TEXT>
