<HEAD>LaserPhoto HX2</HEAD>
<HEAD>Two Waive Hearings In Lottery Scam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two city men charged with using a bogus
lottery ticket to claim a $15.2 million jackpot waived preliminary
hearings Friday and were scheduled to appear for arraignment in
July.
   Henry Arthur Rich, 33, a computer troubleshooter for a company
that helps run the lottery, is charged with using his expertise to
identify an unclaimed jackpot and forge a winning ticket.
   Officials allege Rich provided Mark S. Herbst, also 33, with the
bogus ticket and the two planned to split the winnings. Charges
were leveled against the men May 3, less than a week after Herbst
traded in the ticket for the first installment of the July 15,
1987, jackpot, $469,989.
   The two men appeared briefly in the chambers of District Justice
Bob Yanich. After the men waived the hearings, Yanich scheduled
arraignments in Dauphin County Court for July 7.
   Rich remains free on a $50,000 bond. Herbst was returned to
Dauphin County jail, although his bond has been reduced from
$50,000 to $25,000, Yanich said.
   Authorities have charged Rich with two counts of theft, one
count of conspiracy, one count of tampering with records, one count
of forgery and one count of unlawful use of a computer. Herbst is
charged with two theft counts, one conspiracy count and one forgery
count.
   If convicted, Herbst would face up to 31 years in prison and
$70,000 in fines. Rich would face 40 years in prison and up to
$90,000 in fines.
   Herbst told lottery officials he had been using the ticket as a
bookmark.
</TEXT>
