<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FlabbyGeneration     05-27 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Flabby Generation,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Physical Education Professionals Say Kids Need to Shape Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schools should revamp physical education programs
to help the nation's out-of-shape young people become fitter and
learn to exercise regularly, a fitness expert said Friday.
   ``We've got an alarming problem with the deteriorating state of
fitness in American kids,'' said Donald F. Haydon, executive
director of the American Health and Fitness Foundation. ``There's
no question that our kids are far more sedentary than 20 years
ago.''
   The Austin-based foundation _ which recently completed a fitness
survey of 20,000 schoolchildren, primarily in Texas _ presented its
study at the American College of Sports Medicine annual convention.
   Haydon, former director of the Texas Governor's Commission on
Fitness, said his group has developed a pilot program, called Fit
Youth Today, to encourage young people to improve cardiovascular
fitness through regular exercise.
   The program was tested last fall in 17 Texas school districts.
This spring, it is being used by a number of districts throughout
the country, he said.
   Previous fitness programs simply tested students once annually
through programs such as the one sponsored by the President's
Physical Fitness Council. But the FYT program includes an
eight-week training program of running and calisthenics, followed
by a four-part test.
   Haydon said that of the 20,000 students participating in last
fall's study, 29 percent reached the program's fitness standards
after the eight-week regimen.
   Part of the problem is that schools emphasize prowess at the
expense of general fitness, said William G. Squires, an associate
professor of biology and physcial education at Texas Lutheran
College in Seguin.
   The researchers also said parents should take an active role in
encouraging their children to pursue physical fitness.
   ``Parents check their kids' math homework, but how many parents
actually pay attention to the fitness levels of their kids?''
Squires asked.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
