<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthKorea Bjt   05-27 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea, Bjt,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Riot Police Roughly Break Up Anti-Government Protests
^LaserPhoto SEL3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police kicked and clubbed
anti-government protesters Friday and fired tear gas grenades after
President Roh Tae-woo ordered that all measures be taken to crush
violent demonstrations.
   Roh, presiding over a meeting of the National Security Council,
said the dissident protests threaten the safety of the Olympic
Games, which begin Sept. 17 in Seoul.
   As part of tightened security preceding the Games, a Cabinet
minister ordered police to maintain surveillance on foreigners
spending long periods of time in South Korea without a definite
purpose.
   In downtown Seoul, angry passers-by shouted ``Shame!'' as some
of an estimated 7,000 riot police fired tear gas and repeatedly
charged about 3,000 radical students.
   Police chased protesters into subways and tossed tear gas
grenades at passers-by who protested. Several officers lifted a
protesting businessman in a blue suit above their heads and carried
him away.
   Police broke up an attempted sit-in at City Hall and an attempt
by about 500 students to march toward the U.S. Information Service
library. They arrested dozens of students, beating and kicking many
of the protesters and hitting them with clubs as they were dragged
away.
   There were no reports of injuries, and police did not give an
overall arrest figure.
   Some students hurled firebombs and rocks at police, but most
just chanted anti-government and anti-U.S. slogans.
   ``Down with the military dictatorship!'' ``Punish Roh Tae-woo!''
and ``Drive out the Yankees!'' they yelled.
   Radical students claim the United States supports military rule
in South Korea and enforces partition of the Korean peninsula,
divided since 1945. The protesters demand the expulsion of the
42,000 U.S. troops based in South Korea.
   Protesters have attacked U.S. diplomatic buildings during the
protests, including the U.S. Embassy. No Americans have been hurt.
   Protesters have also demanded that South Korea and North Korea
serve as co-hosts of the Olympics as a move toward reunification of
the two countries.
   Roh called the radicals a threat to the safety of the Games and
said, ``It is imperative that all possible measures be taken to
forestall acts of violence by domestic radical groups.''
   Roh also warned that North Korea ``may stage any kind of
adventure and provocation to mar the success of the Games.''
   Home Minister Lee Choon-koo, who is in charge of the nation's
135,000 police, ordered the watch on certain foreigners to prevent
infiltration by terrorists at the Olympics.
   The government inaugurated a 13,000-member police Security Task
Force to guard Olympic athletes and facilities. Members were
selected for martial arts and foreign language skills.
   Police also distributed 5,000 leaflets nationwide with portraits
of seven people suspected in the hijacking in 1970 of a Japanese
jetliner to North Korea by the terrorist Red Army group.
   One person suspected in the hijacking, Yasuhiro Shibata, 34, was
arrested in Tokyo after returning from North Korea on a false
passport, police said.
   In Tokyo, a police spokesman said officers were questioning
Shibata to try to determine if the Red Army planned any renewed
terrorist action.
   In the southern city of Kwangju, about 5,000 people marched
peacefully to mark the anniversary of the end of a 1980
anti-government uprising in which at least 191 people died.
   A memorial service was held in Kwangju, about 165 miles south of
Seoul. Afterward, marchers, with a coffin bearing pictures of the
dead, walked through the city.
   Radicals claim Roh, an army general at the time, helped direct
the police action.
</TEXT>
