<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeathLawyers     05-27 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Death Lawyers,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Row Lawyers Broke, Seek Execution Delays</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State-paid lawyers for Florida's death
row inmates say they can no longer defend their clients because
they are out of money and have asked the state Supreme Court to
halt all executions or have counties pay up.
   Five men are scheduled for execution between June 22 and July 8,
but their lawyers don't have money to travel to hearings or summon
expert witnesses, Larry Spalding, director of the Office of Capital
Collateral Representative, said Thursday.
   He accused Gov. Bob Martinez of signing death warrants on
``sheer whim'' to keep the pressure on defense lawyers. Spalding
blamed his money woes on an unprecedented number of pending death
warrants and being forced to move his office to more expensive
quarters when the Tallahassee municipal government took over its
former building.
   Spalding on Thursday asked Florida's high court to halt all
executions or order counties where the convicts were sentenced to
pay their legal costs.
   The court scheduled oral arguments on the request for June 7.
   Martinez has signed 20 warrants since the beginning of the year,
almost as many as in all of 1987. Only one execution, however, has
been carried out so far this year, that of Willie Jasper Darden on
March 15.
   Joe Spicola, the governor's general counsel, responded that
Spalding's inability to handle his agency's budget is a perfect
example of why Martinez has ordered a criminal investigation of the
office.
   The governor earlier this year directed the Florida Department
of Law Enforcement to examine the agency's handling of funds and
allegations that witnesses used by the its lawyers may have
committed perjury.
   Spicola said he cannot understand Spalding's budget problems
because his budget was increased from $800,000 in the last budget
year to $1.4 million for the year ending June 30.

</TEXT>
