<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ScratchedMemorial     05-27 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scratched Memorial,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unsolicited Donations Pour in To Repair Vandalism to Vietnam
Memorial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than $60,000 has been raised to repair
scratches made by vandals on the Vietnam Veterans Memorial, thanks
to the efforts of veterans organizations and radio stations
nationwide, a fund-raising official said Friday.
   ``People have been exceedingly generous,'' Jan Scruggs, founder
and president of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial Fund, said.
   Scruggs, whose struggle to get the memorial built will be
portrayed Sunday in the NBC-TV movie ``To Heal A Nation,'' said he
was surprised that so many people were interested in contributing
money to repair the memorial, which has become the most heavily
visited monument in Washington since it was dedicated six years ago.
   The National Park Service on May 2 said it had discovered 8-inch
scratches, including one resembling a swastika, on two of the
memorial's 140 polished granite panels. Scratches also were found
later on a third panel on the 493-foot wall, which contains the
names of those killed in the Southeast Asian war.
   Scruggs said neither the fund nor the Park Service solicited
contributions. Instead, the money, which he called ``gratifying,''
was raised by groups and individuals who decided on their own to
make donations following news accounts of the vandalism _ the first
ever reported at the memorial.
   A Vermont granite expert has been studying ways to remove the
scratches from the polished granite, Scruggs said. The cost of
repairs was not yet known.
   In the meantime, a stone expert has been hired to make temporary
repairs by filling the scratch marks with synthetic resin that
matches the mirror-like surface of the panels, according to Park
Service spokesman Earle Kittleman.
   ``After the repairs are made, we will use the extra money to buy
more granite so we will have panels ready to make replacements if
the need arises,'' Scruggs said.
   Officials at the Park Service and the veterans fund still are
hoping to find out who vandalized the memorial. U.S. Park Police
have been patrolling around the clock since the damage was
revealed, Kittleman said.
   On Monday, the Park Service and the fund will hold their
traditional Memorial Day ceremony at the memorial, with speeches
military music and a wreath laying.
</TEXT>
