<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dick Ferry no longer will have to use the
bank's automatic teller machine to hear the voice of his Scottish
dream girl _ he can just turn on the radio.
   Sally Masterson is trading her London talk-show for a job at WDZ
in this central Illinois city of about 94,000.
   ``The ... amazing thing is that we can't go anywhere without
people asking us about her,'' said Ferry, 61, who wrote a column
about his infatuation with her voice. ``People have taken her to
their hearts and I think they feel a lot of pride in her coming
here.''
   Ferry's column about the taped voice on a Decatur bank's
automatic teller, which Ms. Masterson had recorded, appeared Feb. 4
in the Decatur Herald & Review.
   The newspaper tracked down Ms. Masterson, 30, and brought her to
Decatur in April to meet Ferry and his wife and tour the city.
   ``I think he's smashing,'' she said.
   ``I thought she was charming,'' Mrs. Ferry said, and her
husband, an education professor at Millikin University, agreed.
   Ms. Masterson told the Herald & Review earlier this week that
she has accepted a broadcast job with WDZ radio and will arrive
Sept. 5.
   David Webb, vice president and general manager of WDZ and WDZQ
said Ms. Masterson will have a midday show Monday through Friday,
with the format still to be worked out.
   ``It could be losing some of its magic to see her grocery
shopping,'' Ferry joked about Ms. Masterson's intended move.
   ``I said I was in love with a voice, and I was,'' he added.
``But, I'm in love with my wife. I would hope that Sally is a good
friend.''
