<HEAD>LaserPhoto GRI1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND ISLAND, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jo Manolidis had been struggling for
two weeks to get AT&T to replace her telephone when 21 bright red
numbers arrived in three cases at the door.
   Ms. Manolidis, owner of Jo's Beauty Salon, said she was glad to
finally have her phone service back and a red unit was exactly what
she wanted, but 21 seemed a bit excessive.
   ``The girls at work called and said, `Do you know you have 21
phones here and they all are red?''' she said Thursday.
   The saga began when Ms. Manolidis was told by AT&T on May 6 she
could pick up a replacement for her leased phone at a local outlet.
   That outlet, however, was out of the model she wanted, so she
ordered one. It never came. So while visiting Omaha on Saturday,
she picked up a new red telephone.
   When she plugged in the new telephone at her salon Monday, the
line was dead. She called AT&T to report the faulty telephone and
was told they would have one to her by Friday.
   Ms. Manolidis said she needed one sooner than that and was told
that would mean an extra charge for an emergency delivery. She
objected but was forced to hang up before the controversy could be
resolved.
   The next day the 21 red telephones arrived via overnight mail.
Accompanying instructions asked her to send back the faulty
telephone she'd picked up in Omaha.
   An AT&T official said Thursday she didn't know what caused the
mistake. She guessed it was probably a typing error.
