<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AnimalRights     05-27 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Animal Rights,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swedish Law Protects Dogs' Tails And Barnyard Animals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dogs will keep their tails and chickens
may fly the coop under a law passed Friday to improve the lives of
domestic animals.
   The Ministry of Agriculture said the law, drafted by the
governing Social Democrats, would allow animals ``to behave
naturally.''
   The bill, which takes effect July 1, mandates a minimum living
space for chikens, fur animals and pigs. It also says calves should
stay with their mothers for not less than two months before being
sold.
   The bill was prompted by an animal rights campaign led by Astrid
Lindgren, the author of children's books who created the character
Pippi Longstocking.
   Within 10 years, farmers will have to release chickens from
cages and allow them to roam outside. The law makes Sweden the
second country in the world after Norway, to ban the cropping of
dogs' tails for cosmetic reasons.
   A parliamentary committee also asked the government to oversee
the labeling of cosmetics so that products tested on animals are
marked as such. It said moves should be taken to ban such testing.
   Parliament rejected language that would make it illegal to keep
cows in stalls all year but said farmers must give the animals a
chance to go outside during the summer.
   The bill also calls for the licensing of riding schools and
farms for fur animals.
</TEXT>
