<HEAD>Invites to Jesse Jackson Fundraiser Get Explosive Reaction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENDALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When radio personality Casey Kasem and
his wife, Jean, sent out invitations to a $1,000-a-person
fund-raiser for Jesse Jackson's presidential campaign, they didn't
expect such an explosive reaction.
   The invitations to the ``Rainbow Roundup'' at Spago restaurant
June 5 were delivered by private delivery service this week in
burlap-wrapped gift boxes that contained chocolates and a miniature
cowboy boot.
   But some people feared the suspicious brown packages left on
their doorstep at night were letter bombs, the Glendale News-Press
reported.
   Maha Youness, 17, balked when a man at her front gate intercom
asked her to pick up the package delivered to her parent's home at
9 p.m. Monday. Home alone, she called police.
   Glendale police also were suspicious of the package and called
in the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Bomb Squad. After an
inspection, the package was deemed safe.
   Some celebrities had similar reactions, said Mrs. Kasem, who was
married eight years ago to Kasem in a ceremony performed by
Jackson, a candidate for the Democratic presidential nomination.
   Singer Barry White and his wife, Glodean, cleared a room in
their house, she said. Daily Variety columnist Army Archerd was
also reportedly shaken. And actress Isabel Sanford of ``The
Jeffersons'' was also upset by the invite, Mrs. Kasem said.
   ``I had no idea that I would be scaring everyone, or that
(officials) would be called out to defuse my invitations,'' she
said.
