<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     05-27 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombs Explode In Assassination Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs exploded in a park Friday in
an attempt by Sinhalese nationalists to assassinate Prime Minister
Ranasinghe Premadasa and two other government officials, police
said.
   Premadasa and the other ministers were not hurt in the blast,
said Gamini Gunewardene, deputy inspector general of police. The
bombs detonated prematurely about 200 yards from where the men were
chairing an outdoor public meeting, he said.
   Police found a third bomb and defused it, Gunewardene said.
   ``It was a clear attempt to assassinate the ministers,''
Gunewardene told The Associated Press by telephone from the town of
Muwara Eliya, where the explosions occured.
   Muwara Eliya is in central Sri Lanka, about 55 miles northeast
of Colombo.
   The officials had gone there to campaign for next Thursday's
provincial elections. It wasn't known how many people were at the
meeting. Police said it was ``well attended.''
   Gunewardene said two critically injured Sinhalese men were found
at the bomb site. The men were believed to be carrying the bombs
toward the meeting when they went off.
   Gunewardene said the injured men were being treated and would be
interrogated later.
   Both were believed to belong to the nationalist Sinhalese
People's Liberation Front, Gunewardene said.
   The front is opposed to the peace accord signed last July to end
the nearly five-year Tamil separatist war in the north and east of
the island.
   The front has been blamed for the deaths of more than 290
politicians and government workers since the agreement was signed
July 29 by President Junius R. Jayewardene and Indian Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi.
   Many members of the island's majority Sinhalese community
contend that the pact makes too many concessions to the minority
Tamils.
   The other ministers at the meeting were Lands Minister Gamini
Dissanayake and Rural Industries Minister Sayuramoorthy Thondaman.
Dissanayake has been mentioned as a possible successor to
Jayewardene.
   The prime minister's office in Colombo refused to comment on the
incident.
   In Colombo, police arrested a Sinhalese man after he was found
carrying a long knife on a visit to a minister's home.
   The man, who was not identified by name, was arrested when he
tried to meet Transport and Moslem Affairs Minister M.H. Mohamed at
his Colombo residence.
   Sinhalese, who are Buddhists, account for 75 percent of the
island's 16 million population.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, make up 18 percent. They claim
they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who control the
government and the army.
   The accord has failed to bring peace because the most powerful
of the Tamil separatist groups, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, has rejected it.
   India, which has a large Tamil population of its own, has sent
more than 50,000 troops to the island to try to put down the
Tigers' rebellion.
</TEXT>
