<HEAD>Pleads Guilty in Iran Radio Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of an electronics company has
pleaded guilty to conspiring to ship military radios to Iran.
   Bernard Bowitz agreed to the plea in an arrangement with the
U.S. attorney's office Thursday.
   A 1985 federal indictment charged that Bowitz Electronics USA
promised to sell up to 6,000 radios to Iran through two Iranian
agents operating out of Spain.
   The radios were the type used by the U.S. Army, Marines and NATO.
   Bowitz also pleaded guilty on behalf of his company to a charge
of planning to illegally export $300,000 in listening devices to
Indonesia.
   His wife, Rachel, agreed to plead guilty to illegal possession
of a machine gun and to a charge of planning the illegal export of
radios to Jordan.
   The couple and their company face potential fines and
restitution payments of at least $4.6 million, according to court
documents. The crimes also carry maximum five-year prison terms,
but the government stipulated that prison sentences be suspended.
   Under the plea bargain, Bowitz has agreed to leave the United
States within six months of his sentencing, scheduled June 29.
