<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1831EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WaterWoes     05-27 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Water Woes,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Don't Drink the Water,' Schools Tell Students</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Students in a rural Alabama school district and in eight Boston
schools were told, ``Don't drink the water,'' after potentially
hazardous matter was found in their drinking supplies.
   The order to stop using the water at Snow Hill School, about 40
miles southwest of Montgomery, Ala., came Thursday on the last day
of class. The Alabama Department of Environmental Management, which
tested the water earlier this month, found that its coliform
bacteria count was more than 25 times the level considered
potentially dangerous.
   Coliform bacteria are normally found in animals' colon; in water
supplies, they indicate contamination by fecal matter. Continued
high exposure to the bacteria make a person more susceptible to
digestive disorders, said Catherine Lamar, a spokeswoman for the
environmental agency.
   In Boston, the problem was excessive amounts of lead, discovered
in the water supplies of eight public schools in a television
station's survey. The report prompted testing at all city schools
over the Memorial Day weekend, said John Stobierski of the state
Department of Public Health.
   ``These schools that have high levels of lead or those that we
don't have results for will be on bottled water when schools reopen
on Tuesday, after the holiday,'' Stobierski said.
   The drinking water at Snow Hill School was ``as bad as you can
get,'' said Joe Power, chief of the ADEM's public water supply
branch. ``It's like drinking untreated water from a creek or
river.''
   Power said samples taken by his agency May 16 showed the water
to be contaminated at more than 25 times the potentially dangerous
level of coliform bacteria. School systems in the state are
supposed to test their water monthly and report bacterial levels to
the state, and the agency stepped in when it failed to receive the
reports from the district.
   He said students at Snow Hill have been drinking well water
contaminated at more than seven times the danger level since
January, when the school reopened after being shut for 15 years.
   The 347 students were switched to Snow Hill from a school in
Pine Hill after state officials ordered the county not to use the
Pine Hill school, which was plagued by leakage of raw sewage and
other problems. A fire destroyed the main campus building at Pine
Hill last fall.
   Power said stomach aches, viruses or other illness contracted by
students since January possibly could have been caused by the
drinking water.
   The district's superintendent, Odell Tumblin, said she does not
believe the problem is as serious as ADEM indicates.
   ``That water is clear and pure and a lot of families in the area
have been using the same well for years,'' she said. ``I don't see
how the water system got poisoned just because the students got
there.''
   A new high school is being built in Camden, but school officials
plan to use Snow Hill at least another year.
   Boston's WNEV-TV had water samples from 24 elementary schools
analyzed and discovered that 10, including two private schools, had
lead levels exceeding federal standards.
   Stobierski said the tainted water was unlikely to cause acute
lead poisoning, but said scientists still don't fully understand
the chronic effects of low-level lead poisoning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
