<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Afghan 1stLd-Writethru a0683 05-27 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0683,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Protests US Arms Shipments to Afghan Guerrillas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS pvs 7th graf bgng, (In Washington) with 2 new grafs
giving State Department reaction.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An adviser to Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev
said Friday that the United States is violating a peace accord by
continuing to ship arms to Afghanistan's anti-communist Mujahedeen
guerrillas.
   ``They are arming, quite openly, those who want to go on in
their civil war,'' said Yevgeny Primakov, who has advised Gorbachev
on arranging the Soviet troop withdrawal from Afghanistan.
   Primakov, head of the Institute of the World Economy and
International Relations, did not specify when the United States
sent its most recent arms shipment to the Mujahedeen.
   No did he say whether continued U.S. shipments might halt
withdrawal of the estimated 105,500 Soviet troops who are still in
Afghanistan.
   ``This means that the United States will jeopardize the
situation,'' Primakov told a news conference for reporters covering
next week's summit talks between Gorbachev and President Reagan.
   ``It means they will push Pakistan into a corner,'' he said.
``It destroys the Geneva accords.''
   (In Washington, State Department spokesman Ben Justesen said in
response to Primakov's charges:
   (``The turnover of large amounts of military supplies
constitutes a continuation of military aid. The Soviets should take
their military equipment out with them. We will watch Soviet
actions in this area carefully and will follow symmetry in making
our decisions.''
   Marshal Sergei Akhromeyev, chief of staff of the Soviet armed
forces, told reporters Thursday that 9,500 of his troops have left
Afghanistan since the pullout began May 15.
   Under the peace accord, the Soviet withdrawal is supposed to be
completed by early 1989.
   Primakov's charge appeared to be part of a pattern of protests
aimed at pressuring Pakistan and the United States to stop aiding
the Mujahedeen.
   On Thursday, the Afghan government lodged its fourth protest
with a U.N. observer mission, accusing Pakistan of continuing to
channel arms to the guerrillas.
   The guerrillas have said they will continue to fight the
Soviet-backed government in Kabul and will ignore the Geneva
accords signed by Pakistan and the Kabul regime.
   The United States and Soviet Union agreed to act as guarantors
of the agreement. In an exchange of letters, each side agreed to
stop arming its allies in Afghanistan if the other followed suit.
   The letters, which have not been made public, also are reported
to have specified that if either side continued to arm its Afghan
ally, the other would provide a commensurate level of weapons to
its side.
   Moscow has halted its arms shipments, Western diplomats say, but
is leaving Soviet military bases and massive arms supplies to the
Kabul government as its forces pull out.
   The United States has been supplying the Mujahedeen with an
estimated $500 million annually in arms and military supplies
channeled through Pakistan.
   About 2.5 million Afghans have fled to Pakistan since the
Soviets invaded Afganistan in December 1979, and the Mujahedeen
operate out of basis on Pakistani soil.
   China and Saudi Arabia also have supplied arms to the Mujahedeen
but have not signed the Geneva accords.
   An additional 1.5 million Afghan refugees are living in Iran,
which is supporting Islamic fundamentalist guerrilla groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1835EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Taiwan     05-27 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Divided On Reimposing Martial Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Old-guard lawmakers from the governing
Nationalist Party called for the return of martial law Friday after
violent protests that injured hundreds of people, but their younger
colleagues denounced the idea.
   Martial law was lifted in July after 38 years in force. Last
Friday and Saturday, riot police and demonstrators battled in
Taipei for 18 hours, and there has been talk the government might
bring back martial law.
   More than 200 people reportedly were injured and 96 protesters
were detained in the riots, which broke out after a farmers' rights
demonstration. The violence was the worst on this island since
1947, when native Taiwanese staged an uprising against Nationalist
forces who had arrived from the Chinese mainland.
   A group of 75 legislators issued a statement calling the recent
rioting ``a bloody incident unprecedented in 40 years.'' They urged
the government to partially reimpose martial law because the nation
had reached ``the moment of life and death.''
   The statement said violent protests threatened national security
and Taiwan's economic development.
   Most members of the Legislative Yuan who signed the statement
were elected on mainland China shortly before 1949, when they and
the rest of the Nationalist government fled to Taiwan after losing
a civil war to the Communists.
   The Nationalist government claims to be the rightful ruler of
all China.
   A group of 27 lawmakers comprised mostly of Nationalist
legislators elected in Taiwan issued a statement opposed to a
return to martial law and said it would drive ``the vehicle of
democracy backward.''
   The rioting was a temporary disorder and the government should
not easily give up its achievement in democracy, the statement said.
   Since the lifting of martial law, under which demonstrations
were banned, protests have been held almost daily by dissidents and
other groups pressing a wide variety of political and economic
demands.
   Newspapers reported Thursday that members of the party's
policy-making Central Standing Committee held heated discussions at
a weekly meeting Wednesday about whether the government should
reimpose martial law.
   Taipei police, meanwhile, turned down an application by a
farmer's group to march in Taipei on Tuesday, claiming the
organization violated demonstration laws during previous protests.
   Lin Feng-hsi, spokesman of the group, said the farmers wanted to
march to apologize to Taipei residents for last week's violent
protest.
   Also Friday, the Nationalist Party announced that three sons of
the late President Chiang Ching-kuo were elected delegates to the
Nationalist Party congress this summer.
   Chiang, who died in January, was the son of Chiang Kai-shek, who
led the Nationalists to Taiwan in 1949. He was the main architect
of the recent policies of easing the Nationalists' authoritarian
grip on Taiwan and allowing unofficial contacts with China.
</TEXT>
