<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Norway-FishDeath     05-27 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Norway-Fish Death,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Algae Killing Tons Of Fish In Scandinavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 300-mile carpet of algae along the
southern coast of Norway and Sweden has killed tons of salmon and
rainbow trout, a Norweigan newspaper reported Friday.
   The single-cell algae has killed all marine life down to a depth
of 26 feet in some parts of Skagerrak Strait between Denmark and
Norway and in the Kattegat belt between Denmark and Sweden, the
Oslo daily Aftenposten said.
   Denmark, alarmed by weather reports showing the algae could be
blown to its shores, dispatched a research boat Friday to track the
growth.
   ``I've never experienced anything like it. The situation is
highly dramatic,'' Arne Nielsen, head of the Sea Pollution
Laboratory of Denmark's Environment Ministry, said Friday.
   Nielsen blamed nitrates and phosphorus washed into the sea from
farms.
   Authorities say the algae is not harmful to humans, but it turns
to slime on the gills of fish and chokes them to death.
   The algae growth extends about 310 miles along the southwest
coast of Sweden from Goteborg to the oil center of Stavanger,
Norway.
   Wild fish such as herring and flounder have not been as hard hit
as the trout and salmon grown by Norwegian farmers in seaside pens,
experts said. Those farmers have been advised by marine biologists
to slaughter their fish.
   Some major fish farms in western Norway have started to tow
their nets away from coastal areas into Norway's deep, cool fiords
to avoid the algae threat.
   Marine biologist Einar Dahl said it could take weeks or months
for the algae to disappear, according to the newspaper.
   He said the algae has always been present in the North Sea but
never in such quantities.
</TEXT>
