<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Arrest,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Undercover Police Veteran Arrested On Drug Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 31-year veteran undercover officer whose
testimony helped convict an officer of the scandal-ridden 77th
Precinct has been arrested on drug charges, authorities said.
   Detective Eugene Poulson, 56, of Queens, who had spent the last
13 years in the Internal Affairs Division investigating corrupt
cops, was himself arrested by IAD investigators Thursday, IAD Chief
Daniel Sullivan said.
   ``He was a very dedicated and good performer,'' the chief said.
``I'm shocked and saddened that he would give up his 30 years of
police service and his pension for this brief encounter.''
   In 1987, Poulson had posed as a cocaine dealer during an
investigation of police corruption at the 77th Precinct, which
resulted in the indictment of 13 officers. Videotapes of Poulson
offering an officer a $500 payoff for protection helped convict the
officer.
   A unidentified woman arrested in April on drug charges told
narcotics officers Poulson had introduced her to drugs four years
ago, Sullivan said. The woman contacted Poulson and he agreed to
meet her Thursday night at a house police had wired for sound.
   Investigators said Poulson possessed slightly less than an
eighth of an ounce of cocaine that he was going to give to the
woman. ``There were indications he had been using drugs recently,''
Sullivan said.
   The detective refused to take a drug test on the advice of his
attorney. There were no indications that Poulson had been dealing
cocaine, or that he had obtained the narcotic from police seizures,
the chief added.
   Poulson was charged with one count of drug possession and two
counts of drug possession with intent to sell. The maximum penalty
for the last two counts is a prison term of up to 25 years.
   Poulson earned about $50,000 a year. Under police regulations,
he was eligible to retire with a pension worth two-thirds of his
annual salary after 30 years.
</TEXT>
