<HEAD>Orbiting Cosmonauts Voice Hopes for Summit Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev received encouragement from on high Friday for their
summit talks next week.
   ``We as people hope that the summit brings peace,'' cosmonaut
Vladimir Titov said in a live television interview as he orbited
Earth in the Soviet space station Mir, which means ``peace'' in
Russian.
   A group of reporters in Moscow asked Titov and fellow cosmonaut
Musa Manarov about Gorbachev's comment in a recent interview with
The Washington Post and Newsweek magazine that he will ask Reagan
to support a joint U.S.-Soviet mission to Mars.
   ``As for joint scientific projects, our country has always been
for them. We confirm that,'' said Titov, who wore a gray-blue
flight suit. He predicted that a manned expedition to Mars could be
carried out within 10 years.
   Gorbachev did not specify whether he was proposing a manned or
unmanned flight to Mars. Other Soviet officials said Gorbachev
envisioned an unmanned mission.
   Titov, 41, who is from the Siberian town of Sretensk, has been
aboard the Mir spacecraft as commander since December. Mir was
launched in February 1986 as a permanent manned space station, and
cosmonauts have been conducting scientific and medical experiments
on board since it soared into orbit.
   Titov and Manarov, a 37-year-old member of the tiny Soviet
ethnic group called the Lakets, spoke by television to reporters
who toured the Soviet mission control center north of Moscow.
   Stepan F. Bogodyazh of the Glavkosmos space agency said the
Soviet Union had developed detailed plans for a joint Mars
expedition. ``We hope our leaders will have time to discuss these
proposals,'' he said.
