<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     05-27 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Gunboats Hit Maltese Ship in Fourth Recent Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Iran-Iraq, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX MINASIAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian gunboats attacked a Maltese
freighter and set it ablaze Friday in the Strait of Hormuz. It was
Iran's fourth raid in 10 days on ships sailing to or from Saudi
ports.
   Iran apparently was retaliating for a spate of Iraqi raids on
its oil- shipping lanes, including one attack that devastated five
tankers May 14.
   Iran targets vessels trading with Saudi Arabia or Kuwait because
it accuses the two oil-rich powers of aiding Iraq, its enemy in the
7{-year-old Persian Gulf war.
   The 18,000-ton Don Miguel was left burning fiercely after the
morning attack in the Strait of Hormuz, the gateway to the gulf.
The 18-member South Korean crew abandoned the vessel, shipping
executives said.
   The executives, speaking on condition of anonymity, also said
the Iranians fired at a helicopter chartered by the U.S. television
network CBS when it approached the site of the attack. The aircraft
was not hit.
   The shipping officials said they were not aware of any U.S.
warships, which patrol the gulf to protect shipping, near where the
Iranians struck.
   In the past 10 days, Iran has attacked three other foreign
ships. The Don Miguel was hit about 12 hours after the
Norwegian-operated Mundogas Rio was attacked in the same area,
about 25 miles south of Iran's Larak island oil terminal.
   Kuwait turned to the United States and the Soviet Union for
protection of its vital oil shipments from such attacks last year,
putting 11 tankers under the U.S. flag and chartering three others
from Moscow. On May 3, the Pentagon broadened its role in the gulf
to allow U.S. ships to aid stricken vessels that aren't flying the
Stars and Stripes.
   Oman, which shares with Iran control of Hormuz, sent a small
gunboat to help the Don Miguel and pick up crewmen from lifeboats.
Tugboats of the Dutch firm Smit helped fight the fire, which burned
for hours.
   Executives said the ship was badly damaged.
   The Don Miguel is Greek-owned with a Maltese
flag-of-convenience. The vessel was under charter to the
London-based Trans Ammonia, international traders in sulphur.
   Shipping executives said the vessel was heading for the Saudi
port of Jubail to pick a load of the sulphur but would now be towed
to Fujairah, outside the Hormuz, for inspection of damage.
</TEXT>
