<HEAD>Chemical Ship Sinks Off Netherlands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IJMUIDEN, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dutch ship carrying highly
flammable chemicals sank Friday after a collision with a Swedish
freighter, a coast guard spokesman said.
   One sailor was reported missing from the Anna Broere, which was
carrying 1,600 tons of acrylon nitryl at the time of the collision
with the Atlantic Compass about 50 miles off this fishing port.
   A navy helicopter took another crewman to a hospital near here
but the coast guard official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the nature of his injuries was not known.
   He said the Anna Broere's 10 other crew members were taken
aboard the Swedish ship.
   The collision occurred at 5 p.m in one of the world's busiest
shipping lanes. The cause was not known immediately.
   According to the spokesman, the Atlantic Compass was bound from
Goteborg, Sweden, to Antwerp, Belgium, but the Anna Broere's
destination was not known. It sailed from Rotterdam earlier Friday.
   Acrylon nitryl is a chemical used in the plastics industry.
Contact with the eyes or skin can cause serious injury.
