<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nixon-Summit     05-27 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nixon-Summit,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nixon Says Post-Convention Summit Would Be `Three-Ring Circus'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit-Reagan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Nixon says a proposed fifth
Reagan-Gorbachev summit after the Democratic and Republican
conventions this summer would be meaningless unless both parties'
presidential candidates also agree to attend.
   Such a meeting, Nixon said, ``would be a ludicrous three-ring
circus.''
   President Reagan held out the possibility of yet another summit
before he departed Wednesday for summit talks with Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev in Moscow next week.
   The German newspaper Die Welt quoted Reagan as saying the
Soviets are interested in concluding a Strategic Arms Reduction
Talks or START treaty with him, rather than waiting until his
successor takes over in January.
   Nixon said that with only five months remaining before the Nov.
8 presidential election, too little time remains for the Reagan
administration to complete an arms control agreement that would be
in the national interest.
   ``Once the two major parties choose their tickets for the
general election, an incumbent's authority _ in Soviet eyes _ drops
to nil,'' he said.
   ``Any summit after the two conventions will be meaningless
unless both the Republican and Democratic nominees agreed to
attend. In the unlikely event that they did, it would be a
ludicrous three-ring circus.''
   Nixon's views are contained in a column he wrote for this
weekend's editions of the Sunday Times of London. A copy was
obtained by The Associated Press.
   Nixon, who had three summit meetings with Soviet leaders while
he was president, said Reagan doesn't have enough time left as
president to resolve several important Soviet-American issues.
   Among them, he said, are the relationship between defensive and
offensive weapons systems, whether to allow mobile strategic
missiles, and verification of cruise and mobile missiles.
   Therefore, Nixon said, Reagan should concentrate in Moscow on
conventional arms control and regional political conflicts.
   Trying to rush the START talks toward settlement ``would put the
United States in the intolerable position of negotiating against a
deadline in questions that directly affect our survival,'' Nixon
said.
   Even signing a draft agreement would be a mistake, he said.
   ``That would lock the next administration into an approach that
focused excessively on cuts in the number of nuclear weapons
instead of the critical issue: the stability of the strategic
balance,'' he wrote.
   Nixon said the centerpiece of the U.S. approach should be
conventional arms control in Europe and not any goal of making
equal cutbacks in U.S. and Soviet forces in Europe.
   ``While American forces would retreat to the other side of an
ocean, Moscow's forces would simply take a short train ride to the
western border of the Soviet Union,'' he said. ``Instead, we should
seek asymetrical reductions in the Kremlin's armies.''
   The former president said progress on U.S.-Soviet economic
cooperation must be linked to resolving regional disputes in which
Moscow's actions threaten American interests, ``if we want
Gorbachev to take our positions on these issues seriously.''
   ``If we do not insist on linkage at the Moscow summit, we will
end up subsidizing our own destruction,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1550EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Party     05-27 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Party,0732</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radical Reforms Outlined, But Economic Change Unclear</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party has outlined a series of
reforms that could sweep away many political and judicial remnants
of Stalinism. But it has failed to say how it will transform the
economy.
   The changes are sketched in a program that will be debated next
month at a party conference considered crucial to the future of
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms.
   The document, published in Soviet newspapers Friday, was
approved at a Central Committee meeting this week and stresses the
Soviet Union's need to modernize all aspects of society.
   It speaks of elections for some posts, of reducing some
adminstrative powers of Communist Party, of limiting the terms of
office and of democratic reforms.
   While the proposal makes no concessions to demands for a
multi-party system, it says social organizations that are not
limited to Communist Party members should have ``a bigger say in
the political process in future.''
   The nation's laws will be reviewed, the document says, and ``We
must firmly adhere to the following principle: Everything is
permissible unless prohibited by the law.''
   Gorbachev has stressed reforms of the judicial and political
system as crucial to ending the vestiges of Stalin's dictatorship.
But even if the Communist Party conference approves all the
changes, their implementation may be slowed by resistance in some
quarters.
   Changes envisaged in the political system include a limit of two
five-year terms for for party and government officials all the way
up to the policy-setting Central Committee and the Supreme Soviet,
the nation's parliament. The party also is ordered to keep hands
off day-to-day management of the economy and government, and
concentrate on setting goals.
   Almost all the proposed changes, called the ``theses'' for the
party conference opening June 28, had been raised before by
Gorbachev or his followers.
   But in an apparent victory for Gorbachev, the principle of
secret ballot elections for some posts was adopted.
   The party leader also appears to have gained a chance to sweep
opponents from positions of influence. The conference will consider
calling for a review of all the party's 19 million members.
   The review is likely to focus on the clear struggle between
orthodox Communists used to the authoritarian party system set up
by Stalin and reformers who want to see Gorbachev's reforms succeed.
   The theses contained strong criticism of what it said was the
abuse of power under the system built up by Stalin, and of the
political and economic stagnation that set in under Leonid I.
Brezhnev, who was in power from 1964 to 1982.
   It declared the Soviet Union was ``on the brink of an economic
crisis'' after Brezhnev.
   Although progress has been made, the program said the economy
still is far from the modern financial and monetary system
Gorbachev wants.
   An economist close to Gorbachev, Abel Aganbegyan, told reporters
Friday that despite three years of reform efforts, most average
Soviets have seen no improvement in their lives.
   He said a reform of prices, which is promised for the early
1990s, is essential.
   Nikolai Shmelev, an economist known for his controversial
proposals, said the Soviet economy suffers from gross inefficiency.
It has a shortage of 20 million workers in some sectors, but 25
million extra workers in other sectors, he said.
   In apparent deference to growing grumbling among consumer about
shortages, the theses also stressed that supplies of food and
consumer goods must be sharply increased.
   Scientists and educators were castigated for not doing enough to
introduce new technology and new thinking, but the biggest
criticism was reserved for managers and bureaucrats who still want
to boss others around.
   The only sector of the population praised for its contribution
to the reform effort was the intelligentsia, who have proved the
most vocal supporters of Gorbachev's reforms.
   That reflects in part changes that have given Soviets more
interesting newspapers, livelier television programs and some
previously banned films, books and music.
   If the document is accepted by the 5,000 delegates to the
Communist Party conference, it will mark an important consolidation
of reforms to date for Gorbachev and give him the basis to go
further in transforming the Stalinist system he inherited.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1842EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietProgram     05-27 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Program,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Main Points of Soviet Party Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the main points of Central Committee
proposals published in Friday's Soviet newspapers:
   _On political pluralism. The paper says ``a salient feature of
our time is the appearance of a real pluralism of opinions, open
comparison of ideas and interests.'' It does not envisage
abandonment of the one-party system, but suggests that some social
organizations outside the party should have a bigger say in the
political process in future
   _Local and regional legislatures and the national Parliament are
to play an enhanced role in political debate and to operate under
legal guarantees that their decisions will not be undone by
bureaucratic interference.
   _The legal system is to be strengthened, presuming the innocence
of those on trial and radically reforming the operation of state
prosecutors. Soviet laws are to be rewritten and the principle
adopted that ``everything is permissible unless prohibited by the
law.''
   _Reforms should allow for the exercise of constitutional
freedoms _ freedom of press, conscience, assembly, street
demonstrations and ``firmer guarantees of personal rights, such as
the inviolability of the person and the home, and privacy of
correspondence and telephone conversations, to name but a few.''
   _Party and government officials should be limited to two
five-year terms in office, with third terms permissible only by
majority vote in secret ballot of party and government offices
concerned. The proposals say this practice should extend all the
way to the Central Committee and to the Supreme Soviet, or national
parliament.
   _Due attention should be paid to ethnic relations, and political
institutions formed to articulate ethnic interests made ``more
active.''
   _The party should be reformed to prevent a repeat of the abuses
of power developed under Stalin and ``those who in the past fell
victim to unjustified political accusations and illegality'' should
be rehabilitated.
</TEXT>
