<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChildPreacher     05-27 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Preacher,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Duffey Strode Suspended for Fifth Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARION, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A child whose fire-and-brimstone preaching
has disrupted his school was suspended for a fifth time Friday as
parents gave his father a petition asking him to stop the boy and
his two younger children from preaching at school.
   The petition was signed by 474 parents and opponents of the
street preaching by the Strode children _ Duffey, 10, Pepper, 6,
and Matthew, 5.
   On Friday, Duffey again ignored requests from Eastfield
Elementary School Assistant Principal Shirley Ramsey to come into
school and begin class. He was suspended for six days, until summer
break begins.
   Pepper and Matthew are to return to school Thursday.
   A group led by parent Lisa Mahan asked permission to present the
petition to the boy's father, street preacher David Strode, while
he and Duffey were receiving Duffey's latest suspension papers. But
school officials asked the group to make the presentation off
school grounds.
   The elder Strode told the group they didn't know the gospel and
were going hell. The parents responded that they do know the gospel
and asked Strode to stop the preaching by his children.
   ``Something bad is going to happen to them,'' said Frances
McPeters, one of the parents. ``I have no mercy on them. I don't
care what happens to them.''
   Mrs. McPeters said the Strode children don't understand what
they're saying, but that they only repeat what they have been told
at home.
   ``Sometimes they'll hold up their Bibles and holler `the Bible
says' and then forget what they're suppose to say,'' she said.
``They're not preachers, they're children.''
   Strode said Friday that the family would be moving before school
began in the fall and the children would enroll in West Marion
Elementary, which is in a different district.
   But Mrs. Ramsey said she did not think the controversy would end
because that school district has the same policy requiring students
to enter the building at 7:30 a.m.
   School officials have repeatedly said the children are being
suspended for violating that policy, not because they preach.
</TEXT>
