<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ToyPistol     05-27 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toy Pistol,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Refuses To Indict Officers In Shooting Of Man With Toy
Gun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury refused to indict two police
officers accused of shooting a former mental patient who had a toy
pistol, but the officers and the toy manufacturer face a $25
million lawsuit.
   Police overreacted and the gun looked too real, claims the
lawsuit filed by the victim, Gerard A. Mathieu, 36. City officials
also are defendants in the lawsuit.
   Mathieu was paralyzed from the waist down by a police gunshot
that cut his spinal cord on May 16, the suit said.
   An Orleans Parish grand jury Thursday found ``no evidence of
wrongdoing'' and refused to indict the involved officers, whom
police have not publicly identified.
   The shooting happened after police responded to a report that
someone was looking into the windows of a nursing home. The
officers came upon Mathieu sleeping under a tree near the home's
parking lot.
   ``As the police officers approached the sleeping Mr. Mathieu, a
neighbor yelled, `Don't shoot him, he hasn't got any sense!' The
police officers then yelled at the sleeping Mr. Mathieu and he
jumped up with his hands up in the air,'' the suit said. Police
said on the day of the shooting that Mathieu pointed a gun at
officers, but the suit does not address that issue.
   ``The police officers then hit the ground and opened fire on Mr.
Mathieu,'' the suit says, adding that the officers kept firing
after Mathieu hit the ground, hitting him 11 times.
   The suit, filed by attorney Bill Quigley, said the toy pistol
was designed to look real.
   ``The merchandising, advertising and selling of the plastic toy
gun is based in large part on the work done by the Imperial Toy
Corp. in making the full scale model of the 9mm automatic pistol
look like a real gun,'' Quigley says in the suit.
   In Los Angeles, a vice president of Imperial disclaimed any
liability. ``When the toy is used as a toy, there has never been a
problem, and no problem is even foreseeable,'' said Jordan Kort.
   The suit also alleges the policemen, named in the suit as John
Doe and Ron Doe, acted too hastily and shouldn't have shot Mathieu
11 times even if they felt threatened.
   The city public affairs office refused comment on the suit.
</TEXT>
