<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1806EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TV-Sweeps     05-27 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TV-Sweeps,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Wins May Sweeps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC won the May sweeps by the highest margin for
a May sweeps ever and by the second-highest margin for any sweeps,
according to figures from the A.C. Nielsen Co. released by the
network.
   There are four sweeps months a year during which local ratings
are measured for use in negotiating advertising rates. The networks
generally load schedules with special programming designed to help
their affiliates.
   The May sweeps ratings showed an increase in network audience
since May sweeps of last year, and a change in the trend shown by
end-of-season ratings last month of a decline in network viewership
this season compared to 1986-87.
   NBC won the sweeps with an average, prime-time rating of 14.9
and a 26 share. CBS was second with a 12.0 and 21, and ABC third
with an 11.7 and 20 share. It was NBC's 12th sweeps win in a row.
   The last time any network won by a larger margin was when ABC
won in July 1984, according to NBC.
   The networks had a total rating of 37.9 in May of 1987. In May
of this year, their total was 38.6.
   The rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million
households with televisions. The share is a percentage of sets in
use.
   The highest-rated show of the May sweeps was the two-hour
``Magnum, P.I.'' finale on CBS. It had a 32.0 rating and 48 share.
In second was NBC's movie, ``Perry Mason: The Case of the Lady in
the Lake,'' with a 22.6 rating and 35 share.
   The highest-rated series was ``A Different World'' on NBC, with
a 22.0 rating and 38 share, barely ahead of ``The Cosby Show,''
which had a 21.9 rating and 40 share.
   The larger share for ``Cosby'' indicates fewer sets in use at
the earlier time period.
   The highest-rated miniseries was NBC's ``Something Is Out
There,'' with a 19.2 and 30 share. ABC's ``The Bourne Identity''
was second with 18.5 and 30.
   Though miniseries are shorter and fewer, their ratings show them
to be ``still a viable programming source,'' said NBC analyst
Gerald Jaffe. ``You just have to be careful which ones you make and
when you schedule them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
