<1ST_LINE>r i AM-JailedJournalists     05-27 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jailed Journalists,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghans to Free Jailed French Photographer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Afghan government has pardoned a
French photographer jailed after he was convicted of spying,
state-owned radio announced Friday.
   A French diplomat said the Frenchman would be released within
two or three days.
   Western sources said they expected an Italian journalist also to
be released soon. The two are the only foreigners known to be held
in Aghanistan.
   Radio Kabul quoted Afghan President Najib as announcing the
pardon of French photographer Alain Guillo. The decision was taken
in view of ``the old friendship between France and Afghanistan,''
the president was quoted as saying in the report monitored in
Islamabad.
   He said the move was made in light of an accord signed last
month to withdraw Soviet troops from Afghanistan. Najib has made
increased efforts to polish his international image since then.
   The radio broadcast said Najib made the announcement after
Gilbert Perol, secretary-general of the French External Affairs
Ministry, visited Najib in Kabul. He delivered a personal message
from French President Francois Mitterrand, according to the radio
station.
   Guillo was detained while filming the civil war in northern
Afghanistan and sentenced to 10 years in prison in September.
   In Paris, his girlfriend, Jeanne Lesieur, told The Associated
Press that she had been informed by the French Foreign Ministry
that the journalist would be released Saturday morning. She said
she did not know when he would return to Paris.
   Eric Fornier, spokesman for the French Embassy in Islamabad,
said Friday that Guillo would be freed ``in the next two to three
days.'' He said details of the release were still being worked out.
   Guillo has shared a prison cell in Kabul with Italian journalist
Fausto Biloslavo, who was serving a similar sentence.
   There was no official word Friday on whether the Italian would
be released. However, Western diplomatic sources, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said they also expected Biloslavo's freedom
soon.
</TEXT>
