<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Dog,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Community Jumps to Call for Donations for Lifesaving Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fund-raising effort to pay for a life-saving
operation for Reno's top-ranked police dog was called off almost as
soon as it started Friday because of the overwhelming response,
Sgt. Greg Dion said.
   Dion said police stopped accepting contributions at 8 a.m.
because the $1,000 raised was more than the $600 needed to rid Zeus
of a cancerous tumor in his eye.
   Residents learned about Zeus' troubles through a newspaper
article Friday and from radio stations.
   ``We want to thank the public for their generous offers, but the
phone's burning up down here and we've got more money than we know
what to do with,'' Dion said.
   Officer Mike Kendig said the city would not pay for 7-year-old
Zeus' operation.
   Zeus is credited with 11 felony arrests and gained the nickname
``land shark'' because he once pulled a prowler out of some bushes.
   Zeus, who veterinarians said is not suffering pain, will retire
in July. Kendig, the dog's working companion, plans to adopt the
German shepherd.
