<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia     05-27 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiator Says Peasants, Housewives Occupying Embassy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government negotiator said Friday that
masked invaders occupying the Mexican Embassy were not leftist
guerrillas as a radio network reported, but workers, peasants,
students and housewives.
   Another government spokesman said two leftist political parties
agreed Friday to end a huge rural protest by peasants.
   A Defense Ministry communique said 16 people had been killed and
30 wounded in the past week in a guerrilla attack and several
clashes between militant peasants and government security forces.
   The radio network Caracol reported soon after protesters rushed
into the Mexican Embassy on Thursday that leftist guerrillas had
taken it over.
   Omar Velazco, an assistant attorney general, met with
representatives of the protesters for eight hours Friday and gave a
different description of them to reporters.
   He said he was hopeful the sit-in would end peacefully.
   Sit-ins at embassies and consulates in Bogota are fairly common
and seldom have anything to do with the country involved. The
demands of this group include water for slum areas, which are being
supplied only once a week during Bogota's worst drought in 53 years.
   A dozen sit-ins have occurred in the past four years, including
two others at the Mexican Embassy. All have ended with no one being
hurt.
   Dozens of soldiers surrounded the two-story building in a
residential area of northern Bogota. No guns were seen among the
protesters, who appeared frequently at windows.
   Mexican diplomats and Colombian employees entered and left the
building undisturbed. Spectators, including journalists, were kept
a block away.
   About 40 people occupied the building. In addition to water for
the slums, they want an investigation of allegations by leftist
parties that the army sponsors death squads that have killed more
than 800 leftists in three years.
   The military denies the allegation.
   Peasants who started marching on half a dozen towns last Monday
also demand an investigation of the death squads.
   Only three marches continued Thursday _ in the northern states
of Santander, North Santander and Cesar. Fernando Brito, assistant
minister of government, said Friday the leftist political parties
Patriotic Union and People's Front had agreed to end them.
   He said the promise was made after government negotiators
listened to peasant complaints. In addition to allegations about
death squads, the peasants have said they want more effective land
reform and nationalization of foreign oil companies.
   According to the Defense Ministry, those killed in the past week
included four policemen ambushed by guerrillas near Medellin,
headquarters of the illegal cocaine traffic.
   The others were peasants killed when police, claiming they were
fired on, shot into crowds of marchers, the ministry said.
   A military alert was declared Thursday because of the violence.
   Former President Misael Pastrana, the opposition leader, urged
President President Virgilio Barco to return from abroad.
   Pastrana said in a broadcast address Thursday that the ``country
is in flames.''
   Barco said in Lisbon, Portugal: ``The situation in Colombia is
totally normal, in Bogota and the rest of the country. ... I don't
see any reason to abandon the trip. We have experienced situations
such as these in Colombia for 30 years.''
   He said opposition demands for his return were part of a
``psychological war aimed at damaging a very important trip.''
   After three days in Portugal, Barco will visit the Vatican for
an audience with Pope John Paul II and then go to Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
