<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1611EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush     05-27 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush: `I'm The Underdog And I Like It'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush declared
Friday ``I'm the underdog and I like it'' and said his weak showing
against Democrat Michael Dukakis in recent public opinion polls is
not a liability.
   Bush told reporters at his oceanside retreat that the polls spur
him to wage a more aggressive general election campaign. He cited
his comeback to clinch the Republican presidential nomination after
losing in Iowa's first-in-the-nation caucuses.
   The vice president also urged a renewal in collapsed
negotiations to persuade Panamanian Gen. Manuel Noriega to leave
power, although he earlier opposed those talks.
   ``If we can find some way to get him out and still bring him to
justice, that would suit me just fine,'' Bush said, adding that he
would prefer to bring other Western Hemisphere leaders into the
negotiating process.
   At the same time, Bush characterized as ``an outrageous lie''
what he said was a reported suggestion that the Reagan
administration had initiated the talks to help his campaign.
   ``When you read these outrageous charges by a drug-related,
indicted dictator, discount them. They are total lies.''
   ``And I don't like it being injected by Michael Dukakis and
Jesse Jackson either. If they have some proof, or they have
something other than nuance and insinuation, let them speak out.''
   With the Atlantic surf pounding behind him, Bush told reporters
on the lawn of his family retreat that recent polls, including a
new Washington Post-ABC poll showing him trailing Dukakis by 13
points, were helping to generate his competitive juices.
   ``I'm the underdog and I like it,'' Bush said. ``It is May and
the election is in November. Do I worry about it? I don't worry
about it. I like fighting back. (Dukakis) is the front-runner. He's
been decreed that in poll after poll. And I like fighting back. I
remember Iowa.''
   Bush has scheduled meetings here over the next week with
advisers and prominent Republicans in an effort to get his campaign
back on track.
   Among those he met with on Friday were Govs. John McKernan of
Maine, John Sununu of New Hampshire, James Thompson of Illinois,
former housing secretary Carla Hills, former deputy Treasury
Secretary Richard Darman, and Martin Anderson, former domestic
policy adviser to President Reagan.
   Bush conceded that polls showing he far lags behind Dukakis
among women voters were of particular concern.
   ``What I've got to do is more clearly define what I feel on
certain women's issues. One of them will be day care,'' he said.
   Bush attributed some of his upbeat attitude to his surroundings.
   ``It's the Maine air,'' he said. ``When I get up here I feel _
it's not feistiness _ but I feel very relaxed about it. I don't
feel troubled by somebody pointing out I'm behind in the polls. ...
I'm coming out of 10 points down in these polls and I've got five
months to fight back.''
   ``There's a little bit of a cholesterol rise, the frustration
level going up, in terms of sitting around and listening to (Jesse)
Jackson and Michael Dukakis dump all over me and the
administration. So I'm beginning to get a little more combative.''
   Bush also scoffed at polls that suggested Americans view Michael
Dukakis as more conservative than he.
   ``That, by any stretch of the imagination, is hard to believe,''
he said.
   ``In terms of neighborhood values _ anticrime, pledge of
allegiance (in schools), penalties for those who are really
corrupting these neighborhoods _ he is on the far left side of
things. I don't think that blue-collar America, or ethnic America,
wants to move away from the kinds of values I've been talking
about.''
</TEXT>
