<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Spies     05-27 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Spies,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Two Top Spies Want To Return from East</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper said Friday that two of
West Germany's best-known traitors, Guenter Guillaume and
Hans-Joachim Tiedge, want to return from East Germany. The
government discounted the report.
   Officials denied the two men had been in contact with Bonn
authorities, as the mass-circulation newspaper Bild reported. ``We
have no knowledge'' that the spies want to return, government
spokesman Herbert Schmuelling told reporters.
   Bild also said that, as former top officials, Tiedge and
Guillaume would be eligible for more than 4,000 marks ($2,300) a
month each in pensions if they returned. Schmuelling said: ``That
is something I am not able to confirm.''
   Ludger Reuber, spokesman for the Employment Ministry, said a law
is being drafted that would prohibit convicted spies from receiving
government pensions.
   Guillaume was unmasked in 1974 while serving as a close aide to
Willy Brandt, who then resigned as chancellor. Guillaume was
sentenced to 13 years in prison in 1975 and was traded to the East
in a spy swap six years later.
   Tiedge was a top official of the main counter-espionage agency
when he disappeared in June 1985. He turned up later in East
Germany.
</TEXT>
