<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Soviets     05-27 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Soviets,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Said to be More Flexible on Arab-Israeli Conflict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union is showing a new flexibility
on such Middle East issues as a Palestinian state and Israel's
refusal to negotiate with the PLO, a Foreign Ministry official said
Friday.
   In a separate development, Soviet officials have agreed to
collaborate with an Israeli rabbi and Western scholars on a project
to research Soviet collections of Jewish historical materials.
   A Soviet delegation outlined the new position during secret
talks in Madrid this month with Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, said
the official, who briefed reporters on condition of anonymity.
   ``If what they have hinted at is indeed their official position
... then the gaps between us seem bridgeable,'' the official said.
   He said the Soviets no longer insist that an independent
Palestinian state in the Israeli-occupied territories be a required
result of an international conference on the Middle East.
   ``The way they phrase it, it is up to the Palestinians to decide
who they want to be confederated with,'' he said.
   Moscow also showed flexibility about the Palestine Liberation
Organization, he said. Israel calls the PLO a terrorist group and
refuses to negotiate with it.
   According to the official, the Soviets want the PLO invited to
an international conference but said the invitation should carry a
condition that all participants accept U.N. resolutions recognizing
Israel's right to exist.
   ``We see a very clear distinction between the Soviet attitude to
the PLO and to Syria, for example,'' he said. ``Syria is a very
important asset, the PLO less so. They will not sell the PLO down
the river easily, but they feel what they have to do to protect the
PLO is less.''
   The Soviet position paper was prepared by Alexander Zotov, the
Communist Party Central Committee's deputy director for the Middle
East, the official said, adding that Peres met with a Soviet
delegation first in Madrid, during a a Socialist International
conference, and then in Washington and Geneva.
   Chaim Billat of the Israel Institute for Talmudic Publications,
directed by Rabbi Adin Steinsaltz, announced the research project
Thursday. He also said the Steinsaltz would be allowed to open an
institute in the Soviet Union to train Jewish scholars.
   ``We consider this as a major breakthrough, and what is
important is that it was the Soviet initiative,'' Billat said.
   The Soviet Union severed diplomatic ties with Israel after the
1967 Middle East war, but the Foreign Ministry said agreement has
been reached for an Israeli consular delegation to be sent there
for the first time since the break.
   A Foreign Ministry official said the ministry was not aware of
the research project but welcomed it as a ``positive development.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
