<2ND_LINE>AM-Garbage Ship,0142</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Genoa May Allow Syrian Ship To Dump Chemical Waste</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENOA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials in this northern port city may
allow the Syrian freighter Zanoobia to unload about 2,200 tons of
chemical waste the ship has been trying to dump in various harbors
around the world.
   ``Genoa is the only Italian port which can safely handle
unloading and disposal of the chemicals,'' said Giuseppe Francese,
the port commissioner.
   He added, however, that the authorities must give final approval
to unload the 12,000 drums of unidentified toxic waste, which
belong to Italian industries. The waste, once unloaded, would be
burned.
   The drums were returned to Italy after 13 months of efforts to
deposit them elsewhere, including in Djibouti, Venezuela, Syria and
Greece.
   The Zanoobia is anchored off the Tuscan port of Marina di
Carrara.
</TEXT>
