<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AirplaneBombThreat     05-27 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airplane Bomb Threat,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Speedy Evacuation After Bomb Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NANTES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Alitalia jumbo jet carrying 398
passengers from New York to Milan made an emergency landing Friday
in western France after a caller said a bomb had been placed aboard
the plane, police said.
   No explosives were found during a search of the aircraft.
   Eight passengers were slightly injured in the evacuation of the
Boeing 747, said Alitalia officials in Nantes who spoke on
condition of anonymity. All passengers left for Milan later in the
day on another plane, police said.
   Cabin chief Enrico Hazan, one of 20 crew members, said Alitalia
officials in Milan received a phone call at 8:05 a.m. saying a bomb
would explode in 25 minutes.
   Within 20 minutes, Italian police had contacted French
authorities who instructed the plane to land at the
Nantes-Chateau-Bougon airport in Brittany, police said.
   The plane landed and was searched by security personnel.
</TEXT>
