<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1638EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile-Attack     05-27 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Attack,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Fire at Prosecutor Handling Pinochet Assassination Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men on a motorcycle fired at least
six shots Friday at a military prosecutor handling the cases
against leftist guerrillas who tried to kill President Augusto
Pinochet in 1986, police said.
   The prosecutor, army Col. Fernando Torres, was unharmed after
the men fired at his car.
   Torres said the attack was being investigated, ``but as far as I
am concerned, it was just a traffic incident.''
   Torres' bodyguards shot back at the attackers as they fled, said
Santiago police chief Gen. Gabriel Ormeno.
   The attack occurred around noon at a busy intersection in a
fashionable Santiago neighborhood.
   Local radio stations said the attackers also tried to plant a
bomb on top of Torres' car as it stopped at a traffic light. Police
did not confirm the report, and no bomb was found.
   Torres is prosecuting dozens of suspected leftist guerrillas
charged with a number of attacks against government and police
officials. Among them are at least 25 members of a leftist
guerrilla group that claimed responsibility for the unsuccessful
but bloody attempt to kill Pinochet in September 1986.
   Pinochet survived the attack on his motorcade at a mountain road
in the Andes foothills near Santiago, but five of his bodyguards
were killed and 11 wounded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
