<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1640EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Reagan 3rdLd-Writethru a0756 05-27 1313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Reagan, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0756,1,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Lauds `New and Good' Soviet Performance on Human Rights</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS new grafs 4-5 bgng, Reagan issued, with reaction to
Senate vote, invitation to Byrd and Dole to fly to Moscow; SUBS pvs
4th graf bgng, Reagan made, to reword for transition.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, underscoring a key
theme for the superpower summit, said Friday reforms championed by
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev are ``new and good'' but that
the Kremlin still falls short of meeting international standards on
human rights and freedom.
   Two days before his arrival in Moscow, Reagan said, ``Soviet
practice does not _ or does not yet _ measure up to Soviet
commitment'' under the 1975 East-West agreement known as the
Helsinki Final Act.
   The Senate gave Reagan a big pre-summit boost Friday when it
ratified by an overwhelming 93-5 vote the treaty outlawing
medium-range nuclear missiles which the president and Gorbachev
signed at their Washington summit last December.
   Reagan issued a statement saying he was ``very pleased'' with
the Senate vote, which he said ``clearly shows support for our arms
reduction objectives.''
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., and Minority
Leader Robert Dole, R-Kan., who telephoned the president in
Helsinki with the news, accepted Reagan's invitation to fly to
Moscow on Tuesday to witness a ratification ceremony the following
day.
   Reagan made his human rights speech before an invited audience
of about 1,200 people in the austerely-designed marble auditorium
of Finlandia Hall, where the Helsinki accords were signed by 35
nations, including the Soviet Union and United States.
   Under the agreement, the Soviets pledged to provide more liberty
for their people and those in Eastern Europe. And yet, 13 years
later, Reagan said, the cases of divided families and blocked
marriages remain on the East-West agenda, while Russians trying to
emigrate are subjected to artificial quotas and arbitrary rulings.
   ``And what are we to think of the continued suppression of those
who wish to practice their religious beliefs?'' Reagan asked.
   At the same time, he said Gorbachev's twin campaigns of
``glasnost,'' or openness, and ``perestroika,'' the restructuring
of the economy, are ``words that to our ears have a particularly
welcome sound.''
   Thirteen years ago, Reagan and other conservatives had opposed
the U.S. signing of the Helsinki agreement because it implicitly
accepted Eastern European boundaries set after World War II in
Moscow's favor.
   Yet Reagan spoke glowingly of the accords Friday, saying, ``And,
despite the doubts of the critics, for the past 13 years the
signatory states have mustered the political will to keep on
working and making progress.''
   The address, coupled with an official welcoming ceremony earlier
at the presidential palace, marked the only time Reagan ventured
from the seclusion of a government guest house where he is spending
3{ days resting and preparing for the summit.
   In other developments:
   _A Soviet source in Moscow, declining to be named publicly, said
Gorbachev plans to hold a news conference during the summit _ the
first time a Communist Party general secretary will have held such
a session on home territory.
   _Yevgeny Primakov, a Gorbachev adviser, accused the United
States of violating a peace accord by continuing to ship arms to
Afghanistan's anti-communist Mujahedeen guerrillas.
   _Viktor Karpov, a top Soviet arms control official, called on
the United States to speed up negotiations on a treaty to cut
long-range nuclear arsenals by making good on promises of
compromise.
   _The White House said that Reagan intends to raise the issue of
the Vietnamese occupation of Cambodia with Gorbachev and said it
hopes reports of a possible troop withdrawal provide impetus for
the talks.
   Accompanied by his wife, Nancy, the president will depart Sunday
morning on a 1{-hour flight to Moscow for his fourth summit with
Gorbachev since November 1985. They are to meet a total of six
hours from Sunday afternoon until Wednesday morning. The two will
say good-bye to each other Thursday.
   At Soviet insistence, the number of meetings was cut from five
to four. Reagan professed to be unconcerned, telling reporters at
the palace there only had been four meetings at the Washington
summit last December.
   ``I think we have to recognize that the (Soviet) government has
normal business that has to be conducted, and we have to schedule
accordingly. That's what we did in our summit in our town,'' Reagan
said as he posed for pictures with Finnish President Mauno Koivisto
in a second-floor salon adorned with silken draperies and crystal
chandeliers.
   Reagan also was asked about reports that the Soviets were
blocking various dissidents from attending a planned meeting with
him in Moscow on Monday. He looked quizzically at Secretary of
State George P. Shultz, seated to his right, and replied, ``We do
the best we can.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the U.S. Embassy in
Moscow has received assurances from the Soviets they will not block
dissidents and ``refuseniks'' from attending the meeting.
   ``The event is on as scheduled and the people we wanted there
will be there,'' he added. Fitzwater said the guests were picked
because ``they represent the problem that he (Reagan) is trying to
dramatize.''
   As for the reports that some people were being stopped from
attending, Fitzwater said, ``We're trying to ascertain the facts
and have made an inquiry of the Soviets.''
   Underscoring the sensitivity of the topic, Jewish groups
gathered in the Finnish capital to mount public pressure on Moscow
in behalf of Soviet Jews waiting for exit permits and those seeking
wider latitude to teach and practice their religion.
   In his speech, Reagan said human rights would be ``an integral
component'' of his dialogue with Gorbachev. In a pre-summit
briefing, Assistant Secretary of State Rozanne Ridgway said it
would be ``subject No. 1.''
   The fact that the superpowers were not able to reach agreement
on a strategic arms treaty to be signed at the summit probably will
give even more visibility to the human rights issue.
   Praising Gorbachev for his ``glasnost''' and perestroika,''
Reagan said that ``since he began his campaign, things have
happened that all of us applaud.''
   He hailed the release from exile or labor camps Andrei Sakharov,
Irina Ratushinskaya, Anatoliy Koryagin, Josef Begun and other
dissidents and ``prisoners of conscience.''
   Reagan also noted that controversial books and movies are being
distributed, even though they are critical of the Soviet past and
present. The Soviets also are allowing a higher level of emigration
and greater toleration of dissent and are beginning to pull their
troops out of Afghanistan, he said.
   ``All this is new and good,'' he said. ``But there is another
list, defined not by us but by the standard of the Helsinki Final
Act and the sovereign choice of all participants, including the
Soviet Union, to subscribe to it.''
   Reagan on Friday said he welcomed ``every sign that the Soviets
and their allies are ready, not only to embrace, but to put into
practice'' Western values.
   ``The House of Democracy is a House whose doors are open to
all,'' Reagan said.
   He renewed his call for Gorbachev to tear down the Berlin Wall
and other barriers between East and West.
   ``They could also give legal and practical protection to free
expression and worship,'' Reagan said.
   He also urged adoption of an independent judiciary, free
election of lawmakers, use of secret ballots in voting and freedom
of assembly.
   Before Reagan spoke, U.S. Jewish activists for Soviet Jews urged
the president to remind the Soviets that human rights were
indirectly linked to progress in arms control.
   Morris B. Abram, chairman of the National Council for Soviet
Jewry, said Jewish emigration is a ``test of whether arms
reductions can succeed.''
   Abram called the improvement in Jewish emigration figures
``insignificant compared with those who wish to leave ... It's
smoke and mirrors as far as the the right to leave is concerned.''
</TEXT>
