<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Chase-Securities     05-27 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chase-Securities,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Fed Decision On Chase Securities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Friday upheld a
Federal Reserve Board decision to allow an affiliate of Chase
Manhattan Corp. to underwrite and deal in commercial loan paper
under strict limitations.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here rejected a challenge by
the Securities Industry Association, which contended that allowing
an affiliate of a commercial bank to deal in loan securities
violated the Glass-Steagall Act of 1933.
   But a three-judge court unanimously upheld the Fed's decision to
allow the Chase Commercial Corp. to underwrite and deal in
commercial paper provided the transactions did not exceed 5 percent
of its gross revenues.
   The court, in an opinion by Circuit Judge James Buckley, noted
that the Fed had approved a similar application by Bankers Trust
New York Corp.
   Buckley, joined by Judges Harry Edwards and David Sentelle, said
the Fed had correctly interpreted the law as allowing a bank
affiliate to engage in a limited number of commercial paper
transactions.
   The Fed correctly decided that the prohibition on bank
affiliates ``principally engaged'' in securities transactions did
not apply in this case, the court said.
   ``The statute permits banks to affiliate with firms that are not
`principally' engaged'' in securities transactions, Buckley wrote.
``The board reasonably concluded that ``principally'' does not
include a firm whose commercial paper transactions are subject to
the limits included in its order.''
</TEXT>
