<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ShuttleTanks     05-27 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Tanks,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Inviting Industry Ideas For Using External Fuel Tanks In
Orbit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA, which expects to use and lose 40 space
shuttle external fuel tanks in flights over the next five years,
invited industry on Friday to come up with ideas for making
productive use of the tanks in orbit.
   Now, they are allowed to break up in the atmosphere and fall
into the ocean.
   The 152-foot tanks, which cost $25 million each, will be given
away free but the user must pay for any costs not incurred under
the present system of discarding them. The National Aeronautics and
Space Administration wants the money up front.
   A Colorado group, which represents 57 university research
institutions, has proposed to use tanks for ``a wide variety of
scientific and commercial concerns.'' The group, University
Corporation for Atmospheric Research, proposes ``parking'' the
exhausted tanks in orbit but NASA ruled out any such plan.
   The use must be stated in advance and a $100,000 deposit will be
required before the space agency provides services or technical
assistance.
   The external tank, about the size of a 747 jet transport,
consists of two pressurized fuel tanks _ one loaded with liquid
oxygen and one with liquid hydrogen. The half-million gallons of
fuel are used up in the 10 minutes it takes for the shuttle to get
into orbit and the tank is jettisoned just before that point.
   The space agency's announcement asks interested American
companies and non-profit organizations to propose uses within 90
days. It is in line with President Reagan's space policy which
calls for using the tanks for commercial purposes.
   NASA plans to launch 40 shuttles through 1994. It said the exact
number of tanks that could be made available will be decided
flight-by-flight depending on the characteristics of the mission
and the proposed use for a particular tank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
