<DOCNO> AP880527-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 2049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Africa-Dumping     05-27 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Africa-Dumping,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>African Leaders Angry Over Dumping of Western Waste</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   African leaders Friday condemned
Western companies for dumping their nuclear and other wastes in
Africa and agreed to ask the United Nations to call for an end to
the practice.
   ``The dumping of nuclear and dangerous industrial waste in
Africa is a crime against Africa and the African peoples,'' the
Organization of African Unity said in a resolution adopted by heads
of state during the second day of their three-day summit. More than
30 leaders gathered with their aides at the 50-member body's
headquarters here.
   ``We will make an appeal to the conscience of the world,'' said
Foreign Minister Ike Nwachukwu of Nigeria, which sponsored Friday's
resolutions. ``All Africa feels strongly about it.''
   But Nigeria and other African states privately chastized some of
their fellow group nmembers for agreeing to take industrial waste
in return for millions of dollars. One resolution appealed to
African countries that have signed such agreements to abrogate them
and those still negotiating to break off talks.
   The controversy began this month in Guinea when officials
discovered that a Norwegian company had been dumping toxic waste on
an offshore island. The dumping was discovered when the island's
trees began to shrivel.
   Several African nations either have signed contracts to accept
industrial wastes, are negotiating, or have been approached, summit
sources said. The West African nations of Benin, Congo, Guinea
Bissau and Niger reportedly have signed contracts, and the tiny
southern African nation of Swaziland and Djibouti in East Africa
have been approached.
   Egypt, Gambia and Sierra Leone confirmed during Friday's debate
that they had been approached by companies looking for dump sites
for toxic wastes, but each government said it had rejected the
proposals. All three mentioned a company based on Gibraltar but
would not reveal the name.
   Guinea Bissau said it had asked the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency to evaluate a request from a U.S. company to
export 6 million tons of hazardous waste to the West African nation.
   Foreign Secretary Marcellino Lima did not say what Guinea Bissau
was offered. But an environmental source, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the deal was worth $15 million.
   Lima said he doubted Guinea Bissau would accept.
   Summit sources and reports from the Netherlands also said a
Dutch company had signed an $84 million contract with Congo to dump
1 million tons of chemical wastes in the West African state.
</TEXT>
