<DOCNO> AP880527-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Accutane Bjt   05-27 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Accutane, Bjt,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dramatic Photo Warning on Acne Drug Unlikely To Be First of Many</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unprecedented government order to include
the image of a deformed baby in packaging for the acne drug
Accutane is unlikely to be followed by similar orders for other
drugs with potential side-effects, analysts said Friday.
   On Thursday, the drug's maker, Hoffman-La Roche Inc. of Nutley,
released a Food and Drug Administration letter outlining stricter
warning requirements for the drug, which can cause life-threatening
damage to fetuses when taken by pregnant women.
   Among other restrictions, the FDA also wants La Roche to provide
a consent form to be signed by physician and patient saying they
understand the risks associated with the drug.
   Louis C. Webb of Advest Group Inc. in Hartford, Conn., a
business research firm, said he doubted that the use of a jolting
image such as a deformed baby would become widespread in the drug
industry.
   He called the photograph a compromise between banning the drug
and doing nothing, and said such a strong warning was acceptable to
regulators and the company because Accutane is not a lifesaving
drug.
   FDA spokesman Bill Grigg said the side effects of other drugs
are not as easily captured in a picture as a deformed infant, so
trying to apply images to other products would be impractical.
   Accutane, which was put on the market in 1982, can cause missing
facial features, heart problems and mental retardation in babies
born to women taking it. The FDA said 62 cases of birth defects
have been reported.
   But dermatologists have praised the drug as the only one on the
market capable of curing the severe acne that causes deep scarring.
   The new FDA requirements are based on the recommendations of an
advisory panel of outside experts, who also recommended that the
drug stay on the market. Accutane already carries explicit warnings
that its use by pregnant women carries a high risk of birth defects.
   Analysts and FDA officials said that including a deformed
infant's picture with the drug was a first.
   ``Because of the controversy, you're going to see a significant
decrease in the use of the drug,'' said Karl Habermas, an analyst
with Sanford C. Bernstein Inc. in New York.
   Webb called the drug a ``significant'' but not major factor in
Swiss-owned La Roche's U.S. sales. Accutane sales last year
amounted to $60 million, or 16 percent of the company's U.S. oral
drug sales, he said.
   The deformed infant picture could affect sales, just as
``whenever you emphasize negatives,'' Webb said.
   ``I think that they're just trying to be absolutely clear that a
certain category (of patient) shouldn't use it,'' he said.
   La Roche spokeswoman Carolyn R. Glynn said ``our only goal is
making sure users don't get pregnant.''
   Ms. Glynn and Grigg said that the company and regulatory agency
basically agreed on the proposals outlined by the FDA, which were
contained in a letter dated May 19. The company is preparing a
formal response to the letter.
   One point of possible contention is the exact location of the
photograph. The FDA said the picture should go with packaging, but
Ms. Grigg said the company favors its inclusion somewhere in
``educational materials'' the company is developing to be provided
to prescribing physicians.
   ``There's not going to be a problem over that situation,'' said
Grigg. He said the agency and company already have discussed coming
up with a final proposal, and one possibility would be to put the
photograph with the consent form.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-Lobstermen     05-27 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Lobstermen,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Lobstermen Can Stay Near His Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush made a campaign promise
on Friday to his neighbors: Local lobstermen won't be barred from
the waters near his vacation home because of him.
   ``These men and women make their livelihood pulling lobsters out
of this bay. They've done it for years. And they're going to
continue to do it,'' he said.
   Bush, here for a week of rest and strategy talks, voiced concern
over local news accounts suggesting that if he wins the presidency
in November some of the waters of this seacoast town might be
closed to boaters, including lobstermen, for security reasons.
   ``That's absolutely absurd,'' he told a news conference at his
compound as a lone lobsterman plied his trade from his boat just a
few hundred yards away.
   Bush's family compound, comprising two homes and several smaller
guest cottages, sits on a narrow point _ Walker Point _ that juts
into the Atlantic Ocean.
   On the inland side, a dozen crab pots dot the small cove between
the Bush compound and the shore, all within a stone's throw.
   The shoreline and the road leading into the compound are heavily
guarded, but local lobstermen are currently permitted to work the
waters adjacent to Bush's property.
   ``I don't want to inconvenience our neighbors,'' said Bush, who
said he had been coming to the retreat for every summer of the 63
years of his life except one _ 1944, when he was at war.
   ``These people have been fishing in these waters, wartime or not
wartime, and I can't ever remember any different,'' he said.
   The issue of whether the Secret Service would declare the waters
around the Bush compound off-limits if he is elected has been the
subject of much recent local speculation. Bush said he wanted to
put the issue to rest.
   ``I don't want to convolute the life of people who earn their
livings here all year-round,'' Bush said.
   ``If it became a choice between whether these lobstermen can
fish in this bay, or I would stop coming to this place I love, I
would not come here,'' he said. ``And it would break my heart.''
   ``But it's not going to come to that,'' he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
