<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 2057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Alcohol     05-27 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Alcohol,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economist Says Anti-Alcohol Campaign Handled Poorly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet economist said Friday that Mikhail S.
Gorbachev has mishandled his anti-drunkenness campaign by
emphasizing police methods instead of taking the long-range view of
offering consumers a better choice of goods.
   Nikolai Shmelev said the Soviet leader's campaign has driven
drinking underground, encouraged moonshiners and deprived the
government of liquor sales revenue.
   Shmelev, whose stinging criticisms of the Soviet economy in the
literary journal Novy Mir have caused a wave of controversy, spoke
to reporters at the Foreign Ministry and expanded on comments he
made in a recent article.
   He said the campaign got drunks off the streets and out of the
workplace.
   But he added, ``Unfortunately, I am afraid nothing has changed.''
   ``The structure of consumption has changed. Instead of
state-produced spirits they drink moonshine, they sometimes drink
chemicals,'' he said.
   Some Soviets turned to drinking hair tonic, cologne and rubbing
alcohol in a desperate search for spirits.
   Shmelev said a more effective but long-term way to solve the
drinking problem is to improve consumer supplies ``so a man could
use his ruble to buy a bottle of vodka or a good shirt.''
   Soviet consumer goods are of notoriously poor quality and in
short supply. Gorbachev has promised to improve the lives of
Soviets by improving the quantity and quality of food and consumer
goods.
   Gorbachev's anti-alcohol campaign, his first major initiative
after taking power in March 1985, included raising the drinking
age, shortening the hours of liquor stores and cutting liquor
production.
   He and other officials credited the campaign with helping
increase the life expectancy for Soviet men in the past two years.
The Kremlin for years did not publish life expectancy figures,
presumably because they were embarrassing.
   Complaints have been voiced in the Soviet press, however, that
too many liquor stores have closed, forcing people who want to buy
an occasional bottle of wine or vodka to stand in line for hours.
   Shmelev said alcoholism will be a ``problem for a number of
generations, for a number of decades.''
   An economist close to Gorbachev, Abel Aganbegyan, told reporters
the anti-alcohol campaign achieved ``very impressive results'' in
cutting liquor sales.
   But he added, ``Now moonshine is consumed in great quantities,
even greater than before the anti-alcohol campaign was launched.''
   Aganbegyan said the effort to convince people not to drink was
poorly handled, and that sobriety societies set up across the
Soviet Union had not been effective.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
