<HEAD>Ousted Homeland Leader Charged With Corruption Goes To Austria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Austria has admitted an ousted
black homeland leader charged with corruption, the Austrian Embassy
said Friday.
   Business Day newspaper said George Matanzima, former prime
minister of the nominally independent homeland of Transkei, left
South Africa for Austria last weekend.
   The embassy confirmed he arrived in Vienna on Monday on a
British Airways flight from London and was granted an entry visa at
the airport.
   Matanzima, 70, was ousted in a military-backed coup in October
after serving as prime minister since 1979. A warrant for his
arrest was issued on May 3.
   An inquiry commission has accused Matanzima of accepting a
$500,000 bribe from a construction company. The commission alleged
Transkei lost about $22 million because of improper actions by
Matanzima and his brother, former President Kaiser Matanzima.
   Transkei, now ruled by its army commander, is one of four tribal
homelands declared independent by South Africa but not recognized
abroad. It lies along the Indian Ocean coast between the port
cities of Durban and East London, covers 18,000 square miles and
has about 3.5 million residents.
</TEXT>
