<HEAD>4 Workers Hurt In Williamsburg Bridge Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four workers plunged 30 feet from a scaffold on
the Williamsburg Bridge on Friday afternoon, injuring two of them
critically, authorities said.
   The accident occurred on the Brooklyn side of the bridge, which
was closed April 12 to automobile and subway traffic due to severe
deterioration, said police spokesman Officer Joseph Gallagher.
   The four workers suffered broken bones, bruises and cuts after
falling onto concrete, said Karen Johnson, spokeswoman for the city
Emergency Medical Services. Two of them were in critical condition,
while the other two were in serious condition, she said.
   Authorities could not immediately say exactly what workers were
doing when the accident occurred.
   Traffic on the bridge, which was reopened for one-way traffic
Thursday, was snarled as police and emergency vehicles responded.
   A Transportation Department spokesman was out of his office and
unavailable for questions immediately after the accident.
