<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Quake     05-27 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Quake,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Shakes Southern Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake Friday shook southern
Yugoslavia but apparently caused no injuries or damage, the
Belgrade seismological institute reported.
   It said the tremor occurred at 4:18 p.m. (10:18 a.m. EDT),
measured 4.9 on the Richter scale and had its epicenter in the
Homolje mountain region, 80 miles southeast of Belgrade, an
institute spokesman said.
   The quake shook wide regions of the republic of Serbia and was
also felt in Belgrade.
   ``Even though an earthquake of such intensity can cause
considerable damage, it is apparent from our first reports that
there was no damage or injuries,'' an institute spokesman told The
Associated Press, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The open-ended Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released
by an earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. An earthquake of 4.0 on the Richter scale can cause
moderate damage in the local area and 5.0 considerable damage.
</TEXT>
