<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-Killing     05-27 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Killing,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Terrorists Kill Galician Businessman In His Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA CORUNA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two women and a man forced their way
into the home of a supermarket mogul Friday and shot him to death
in front of his wife in what police said may have been a terrorist
attack by Galician separatists.
   No group claimed responsibility immediately in the death of
Claudio Sanmartin, 53, the chairman of two supermarket chains and
former chairman of Spain's largest regional savings bank, Caixa
Galicia.
   Police speculated, however, that the assailants may belong to
the Guerrilla Army of the Galician People, an obscure group seeking
independence from Spain for the northwestern region of Galicia.
   Hours earlier, a bomb explosion in Perbes, outside of La Coruna,
destroyed the unoccupied summer home of Manuel Fraga, a Galician
regional conservative leader, former Cabinet minister and now a
member of the European Parliament.
   No one was hurt and no group claimed responsibility, police
said. But the La Coruna civil governor, Andres Moreno Aguilar, said
the explosives used were of the kind used in the past by the
Guerrilla Army of the Galician People.
   Fraga, his wife and family were in Madrid where the politician
has lived for decades.
   Police said the guerrilla group has carried out 10 attacks on
high tension electric towers, bank offices, police cars and
industries in the Galician region in the past eight months.
   Sanmartin's wife told police a man and two women pretended to be
delivering flowers to the family's second-floor apartment, then
violently forced their way in. She said she called for help and her
husband came to the front door, where the man shot him in the head
and chest, officers reported.
   Police said neighbors told them the attackers then left and
calmly drove away in a waiting car.
   The bombing target, Fraga, is a native of Galicia who in 1977
founded the conservative Popular Alliance party, the largest
opposition party in the national Parliament. He resigned as party
president 1{ years ago.
   Last Saturday, the Galician branch of the party elected him as
its leader and named him its candidate for president of the
region's autonomous government in regional elections next year.
   Fraga served as tourism and information minister in the 1960s
and later as Spanish ambassador to Britain.
</TEXT>
