<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Ferry     05-27 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Ferry,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Fire On English Channel Ferry This Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second fire to break out on an English
Channel ferry this week damaged the engine room of the 3,355-ton
European Trader on Friday but was quickly brought under control,
officials said. No one was reported injured.
   The vessel, carrying 85 passengers and crew, was assisted by
tugs to the French port of Dunkirk.
   P and O European Ferries Ltd. said the fire started before dawn,
20 miles northwest of Dunkirk, and filled the engine room with
smoke.
   The company said the crew smothered the blaze with carbon
dioxide before British firefighters and rescue workers arrived on
Royal Air Force helicopters. The cause of the fire was not
immediately determined, P and O said.
   The European Trader was the first vessel to break a 15-week-old
strike on P and O's Dover-Calais route when it sailed to the French
port on May 14.
   On Monday night on the same route, the world's busiest waterway,
one crew member died and another was badly burned when a fire
started in the engine room of the 5,917-ton freight ferry
Seafreight Freeway, owned by Sealink U.K. Ltd.
   Both fires occurred as the ferries sailed from the southeast
England port of Dover to Zeebrugge, Belgium. In March 1987 the
British ferry Herald of Free Enterprise capsized at Zeebrugge,
killing 193 people.
</TEXT>
