<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SpaceStation-Japan     05-27 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Station-Japan,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Signs Onto U.S. Space Station After Two Years of
Negotiations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan, after two years of negotiations with
the United States, has substantially agreed to supply a pressurized
laboratory module to the proposed space station, U.S. space
officials said Friday.
   Japan will be the last of America's international partners to
come aboard the largest cooperative civil and technology project
ever undertaken. Agreements have been reached with the European
Space Agency, representing 13 nations, and with Canada.
   Japan's module will be a permanently attached facility providing
a shirt-sleeve work environment for the space station crew, the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration said. There also will
be an exposed facility to be used for scientific observations,
communications, advanced technology development and other
activities that require direct exposure to space.
   Negotiators for Japan and the United States will submit the
proposed agreements to their governments, NASA said.
   The space station, which is having trouble getting money from
Congress, is envisioned to be in orbit and permanently manned by
the end of 1996. The cost to the United States is projected at $16
billion, Japan's at more than $1 billion and Canada's at $1 billion.
</TEXT>
