<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BusinessForecast     05-27 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Business Forecast,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economists Boost Growth Predictions, Still See Recession in 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economists for the nation's top businesses
said Friday they had boosted their growth forecasts for 1988, but
they still expect high interest rates to push the country into a
recession sometime next year.
   The latest survey of the National Association of Business
Economists showed a substantial upward revision in growth estimates
for this year compared with a survey done three months ago.
   The economists, who advise some of the country's largest
corporations, said they were looking for the gross national product
to expand 2.9 percent this year, which would match the performance
turned in during 1986 and 1987.
   Three months ago, the economists forecast a much slower 2.2
percent GNP increase in 1988.
   The survey was taken in early May before the government released
its revised estimate of economic growth for the first quarter. On
Thursday, the Commerce Department said the GNP rose at a robust
annual rate of 3.9 percent from January through March.
   Kathleen Cooper, chief economist of the Security Pacific
National Bank in Los Angeles, said if the survey were taken now,
most economists would boost growth estimates even higher.
   Some analysts are predicting the economy could grow at a 4
percent rate this year, which would be the fastest growth since
1984.
   In the survey, the economists said the reason for the increased
optimism was a belief that the country's trade deficit would show
more improvement because of higher-than-expected growth in U.S.
exports.
   The merchandise trade deficit, which hit a record $171 billion
last year, was predicted to shrink to $150 billion this year, a
drop of 12 percent. This is only slightly less optimistic than the
Reagan administration's projection that the trade deficit will
decline by 15 percent this year.
   The economists predicted the boom in U.S. export sales would
help push industrial production up a strong 4.5 percent this year.
   However, the economists expressed concerns that the rapid growth
in foreign demand, coupled with continued high consumer spending in
this country, would contribute to inflationary pressures and prompt
the Federal Reserve to step in with higher interest rates to cool
off the economy.
   The Fed already has tightened credit conditions twice in the
past two months, driving up a variety of interest rates, including
the prime rate and mortgage rates.
   Fixed-rate mortgages rose to 10.58 percent this past week, the
highest level since the first of the year, the Federal Home Loan
Mortgage Corp. reported Friday.
   ``We see inflation coming it at 5 percent this year. That will
cause the Fed to tighten up and push interest rates up,'' Ms.
Cooper said. ``Higher interest rates are normally the way we get
into recessions in this country.''
   The survey found that a majority of the economists, 57.8
percent, believed the lengthy economic expansion, now in its sixth
year, will end with a recession beginning in 1989.
   On other issues, the survey of 58 business economists who
regularly make forecasts for their own companies found:
   _Consumer prices will rise by 4.3 percent in 1988, but the
inflation rate will jump to 5 percent in 1989.
   _The federal budget deficit, which fell to $148.9 billion in the
1987 fiscal year, will edge up slightly to $155 billion in the
current fiscal year, which ends Sept. 30.
   _Corporate profits will surge by 9.1 percent this year, even
better than the 8.7 percent profit increase of 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
