<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Chrysler-Seats     05-27 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chrysler-Seats,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Safety Probe of Power Seats in 1985-86 Chrysler Corp. Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has begun a safety
investigation into alleged failures in electrically powered front
seats in 1985 and 1986 Chrysler, Plymouth and Dodge automobiles,
the Transportation Department said Friday.
   The investigation by the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration was prompted by 132 complaints about the operation
of the automatic seats in the Chrysler LeBaron, Laser and New
Yorker; Dodge 600, Daytona and Lancer; and Plymouth Caravelle.
   The government said the complaints included seven accidents
resulting in three injuries. In all, 195,000 Chrysler cars have
seats that potentially could fail, NHTSA said.
   The agency said a failure in the seat could cause a reduction in
seat strength and increase the likelihood of injury in a
rear-impact crash or cause the seat to recline rearward, resulting
in a driver losing control of the car.
   NHTSA said Chrysler Corp. ``is aware of the two failure modes
and has taken action to correct them, but has not conducted a
safety recall.''
   The automaker has strengthened the frame of the power seat and
seat adjuster in later model cars, the agency said.
</TEXT>
