<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1749EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SchoolWedding     05-27 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Wedding,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Schoolkids Hold Their Peace During Teachers' Classroom Marriage
Ceremony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STURGIS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two elementary school teachers gave their
students a lesson in love Friday, saying their wedding vows in a
classroom surrounded by the 50 children who helped bring them
together.
   Tim Peterson, a fifth-grade teacher at Wall School, and Kamela
Britvec, who teaches first grade, tied the knot in her homeroom as
their students read poetry and sang during the ceremony.
   The pair met last spring during a school outing shortly after
Peterson joined the faculty.
   ``We hear kids talk about divorce and bad relationships, and we
wanted to show them how a good relationship develops over time,''
said Britvec, 25.
   Peterson, 30, said his students thought he was joking when he
told them the wedding would be at school _ during school hours.
   ``The kids have been in on this relationship since day one,''
Peterson said after the wedding. So much so that some of the
students took credit for the marriage, the first for both the bride
and groom.
   ``If it wasn't for us, they wouldn't even be together,'' said
Richard Potts, 11, one of Peterson's fifth-graders. ``We told him
how to ask her out. He was too scared.''
   The students helped decorate the classroom and halls of the
475-pupil school in this small town near the Indiana border with
multi-colored streamers, paper flowers, wedding bells and
congratulatory signs.
   During the wedding, Mrs. Peterson's first-graders read a poem
they had written that included the verse, ``We feel good about
love.''
   After the ceremony, which was performed by Mayor Donald
Easterday, the children gave the Petersons a quilt with panels on
which they had drawn pictures.
   Some first graders had a few qualms about the proceedings.
   ``This is mushy,'' said 7-year-old Raymond Whitehead. But he
brightened up and added, ``I'll bet the cake will be good.''
   The kids got a break from afternoon classes for the wedding, but
Principal Earl Arend said he was sure their education didn't suffer.
   ``Who's to say where children learn the most, from a math book
or from some real life experience life a marriage ceremony?'' he
said.
   The couple said their students were the first to know of their
April 1 engagement. And the students' interest in this classroom
romance doesn't look like stopping with the wedding.
   ``They're already asking when we'll have a baby,'' Peterson
said. ``But we want to show them that in real life you don't have
to have a family besides just the two of you.''
</TEXT>
