<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MurderMistake 1stLd-Writethru a0725 05-27 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murder Mistake, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0725,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murder Charges Dropped After Suspect Jailed More Than 2 Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `During his...', to add that he was jailed
without bond awaiting trail.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black Cuban refugee jailed more than two years on
a murder charge despite two witnesses' testimony that the killer
was white has been released, ending an ordeal he said was ``not
supposed to happen in this country.''
   At one point prosecutors had said they would seek the death
penalty for Rigoberto Alberja, 32, indicted for first-degree murder
in the 1982 shooting of a patron at an Allapattah bar during a
holdup.
   Alberja was arrested in January 1986 on the tip of a police
informant even though the bar's two owners said the killer was
white and had straight hair.
   Alberja always maintained his innocence and refused offers to
plea bargain. Earlier this month, the state finally conceded it
could not prove its case, and Alberja was released.
   ``It's unbelievable,'' said Alberja's public defender, Art Koch.
``If all you got is two witnesses saying the guy was Caucasian and
you arrest a guy who isn't Caucasian, well then maybe you better
think you got the wrong guy.''
   Alberja said Thursday he had never been arrested before the
murder case, and was stunned by the treatment he got from the
United States.
   ``It is a great injustice,'' said Alberja. ``This happens in
other countries, but it's not supposed to happen in this country.''
   Alberja said that during his time awaiting trial in the Dade
County Jail, he was stabbed six times by another inmate. In
Florida, those accused of first-degree murder are automatically
jailed without bond pending trial.
   Prosecutor Mike Cornely defended his case despite the
identification problems. He said lengthy appeals over pre-trial
motions hampered his efforts.
   ``We had other information, a confidential informant and certain
other witnesses who knew something,'' said Cornely. ``But by the
time the appeal was done, a lot had dried up.''
   None of the five robbery victims at the bar could be located, he
said.
   He shrugged off the the discrepancy over Alberja's race. At the
time of the robbery, bar owners Terry Taylor and Edward Liles
helped sketch a picture of the suspect, who they said was white.
   But after the tip from the informant almost four years later,
investigators called in Liles, and he identified Alberja from a
photo lineup.
   ``I don't know what Liles' thinking was at first,'' said
Cornely. ``Maybe the lighting in the bar made him think the suspect
was white, but that's just a maybe.''
   But Cornely acknowledged that Liles' change of testimony _ and a
judge's decision to throw out the photo identification _ made his
case impossible.
   ``His ID alone would not fly,'' said the prosecutor. ``We need
other witnesses, and those witnesses disappeared.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
