<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersStrike     05-27 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scriptwriters OK Independent Contracts With 70 TV, Movie Producers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking TV and movie scriptwriters will
resume work for more than 70 producers, including makers of the
top-rated ``The Cosby Show,'' under independent contracts approved
by the writers' union Friday.
   The independent contracts were approved by 86 percent of the
2,016 members of the Writers Guild of America who voted Thursday
night in New York and Los Angeles, said union spokeswoman Cheryl
Rhoden.
   The producers' bargaining group, the Alliance of Motion Picture
and Television Producers, dismissed the defections of the mostly
small production companies as an insignificant episode in the
12-week strike, which has forced delays in the start of the fall
television season.
   By Friday noon, a union list of producers who had signed
included Carsey-Werner Co., which makes ``Cosby,'' and the makers
of ``The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson,'' ``Highway to
Heaven'' and ``It's Garry Shandling's Show.''
   Alliance spokesman Herb Steinberg estimated the independent
contracts, which accede to writers' key pay demands, cover just 1
percent of the union's 3,000 working members, and none of the big
production companies that form the backbone of the industry group.
   ``It had virtually no impact on prime-time network (programs),''
Steinberg said of the vote.
   ``Not one alliance member is in this group,'' Steinberg said of
the producers who had signed on. ``They voted to put 72 writers to
work ... we're concerned with getting 3,000 writers back to work.''
   Many of those who signed were one-person writer-producer
companies, and some listed make TV shows that have been cancelled,
including the Smothers Brothers' comedy show and ``Days and Nights
of Molly Dodd,'' Steinberg said.
   But Ms. Rhoden termed the defections a symbolic victory as well
as a break in management ranks.
   ``We're very, very pleased,'' Ms. Rhoden said. ``The significant
thing is that upwards of 70 companies ... feel they can do
profitable business under a contract that also respects the needs
of writers.''
   The three-year contract accepts the writers key demand:
Retention of the present formula for the payments, known as
residuals, which writers get for reruns of one-hour television
shows.
   Citing the increasing difficulty in selling such shows for
rerun, the producers are seeking to link the amount of the residual
payments to a show's success in rerun, or syndication as it is
known in the industry.
   The contract also boosts residual payments for use of the
writers' work overseas and tightens requirements that writers be
consulted about script changes made during filming. The union
contract also boosts minimum pay scales for writers.
   The writers walked out March 7, and until this week, only one
bargaining session was held.
   Talks Wednesday at the producers' headquarters in Los Angeles'
Sherman Oaks district failed to make progress.
   The negotiators agreed to resume formal talks Tuesday under the
guidance of a federal mediator, and small groups were scheduled to
hold preliminary discussions Saturday.
</TEXT>
