<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-27 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sunshine, Mild Temperatures Herald Pleasant Weekend in Most Areas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunshine and mild temperatures covered much of the nation Friday
afternoon, heralding what is expected to be a pleasant, sunny
holiday weekend for the central and eastern United States.
   Skies were clear from the central Appalachians across the middle
and lower Mississippi Valley to the central and southern Plains,
while partly cloudy skies covered the Northeast, Florida, the
northern Plains and much of the West.
   Temperatures approached 90 degrees over western portions of the
northern and central Plains, while afternoon readings were well
into the 90s in the desert Southwest.
   Cloudy skies covered much of the Carolinas, keeping temperatures
unseasonably cool in the 60s and 70s. Asheville, N.C., set a record
low for the date with a reading of 38 degrees early in the day.
   A few showers dotted the upper Mississippi Valley, and showers
and thunderstorms hit parts of Colorado and southern Florida. Rain
also fell on parts of the Pacific Northwest.
   In the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT, Quillayute, Wash.,
received nearly hald an inch of rain. No other location reported
more than a quarter inch during the period.
   A wind advisory was in effect for southern Nevada, with gusts to
40 mph expected.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 55 degrees at Astoria,
Ore., to 99 degrees at Tucson, Ariz.
   The forecast for Saturday called for widely scattered
thunderstorms from the Rio Grande Valley of Texas across the
Rockies to portions of Idaho and Utah, from northern Michigan to
the Dakotas, and in southern Florida. Scattered showers were
predicted along the Canadian border from Maine to New York State.
   The Pacific Northwest is the only area expected to get much wet
weather this weekend. A strong cold front is headed for the region
and rain and mountain snows are forecast across the Pacific
Northwest on Saturday and in northwest Nevada by early Sunday.
   Highs were forecast in the 80s to near 90 degrees over most of
the nation; in the 70s over Maine and parts of the East Coast and
northern Michigan; in the 60s or 70s in the northern Rockies, the
Pacific Northwest and along the California coast; and in the 90s to
near 100 degrees from the Rio Grande Valley to the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
