<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Meyerson-Shoplift     05-27 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meyerson-Shoplift,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bess Myerson Charged With Shoplifting</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WPT1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bess Myerson, former Miss America and
New York cultural affairs commissioner, was arrested Friday and
charged with trying to shoplift $44 in merchandise from a
department store.
   Miss Myerson appeared before District Justice John M. McDermott
and was released on $150 cash bail.
   The 63-year-old New York City resident, already facing federal
fraud and bribery-related charges, contested South Williamsport
police allegations that she tried to leave Hill Department Store
with six bottles of nail polish, five pairs of earrings, shoes and
flashlight batteries in her purse and shopping bag.
   ``I was leaving the store to lock my car and come back and pay
for the merchandise,'' she told the magistrate.
   She said she would pay her fine and costs ``under protest''
through the mail, if court documents affirm her contention that
this is her first such offense. The maximum penalty, according to
the court, would be a $300 fine.
   ``If true, it's extraordinarily sad that this could have
occurred,'' New York City Mayor Edward I. Koch said of the charge.
Miss Myerson was his campaign manager in 1977 when Koch was first
elected mayor.
   The New York Daily News earlier this month quoted unidentified
sources and records as saying Miss Myerson was charged in 1970 with
shoplifting from a London department store. The newspaper said she
left London without taking care of the charge and paid a fine of no
more than $100 in 1987 to end the case.
   The Daily News said it could not determine what was stolen.
   Miss Myerson was indicted by a federal grand jury last October
on charges she tried to influence the judge handling the divorce
case of her reported lover, millionaire Carl A. Capasso.
   Capasso, serving time at nearby Allenwood Federal Prison Camp
for tax evasion, also was indicted in the case. The two are
scheduled to go on trial Sept. 14.
   Miss Myerson asked at Friday's arraignment whether her arrest
must be publicized. When told it would be published, she retorted,
``So be it.'' She was escorted from the hearing room to her car by
police.
   Should she contest Friday's retail theft charge, she faces a
June 27 preliminary hearing before District Justice Gerald C. McGee.
</TEXT>
