<DOCNO> AP880527-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1857EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-BusinessTaxes     05-27 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Business Taxes,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economists Criticize Business Tax System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pair of top Soviet economists on Friday said
progressive taxes on small businesses are an example of
bureaucratic meddling that will discourage growth of consumer goods
and services.
   Abel Aganbegyan, an economist close to Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, told reporters the progressive taxes as high as 90
percent were ``adopted behind closed doors'' by the Finance
Ministry.
   ``Some provisions are faulty. They didn't know much about
progressive taxation,'' he said.
   Gorbachev has said the cooperatives _ employee-owned small
businesses _ are a key element of his plans to improve the supply
of goods and services to consumers, who face widespread shortages
in the state-run economy.
   The Supreme Soviet, the country's nominal parliament, on
Thursday passed a law expanding the rights of the cooperatives to
compete with the inefficient state-run economy.
   And in a rare move, the body also expanded the rights of local
government to give tax breaks to preferred kinds of cooperatives
and directed that the progressive tax structure decreed April 1 by
the Finance Ministry be rewritten.
   The Supreme Soviet normally only rubber stamps legislation that
already has been approved by the Communist Party, the dominant
force in Soviet society.
   Nikolai Shmelev, an economist with the Soviet Union's
U.S.A.-Canada Institute, said the tax rates decreed by the Finance
Ministry apparently will remain in effect until they can be
rewritten.
   Tax rates for workers at cooperatives are 27 percent on a
monthly income of $1,600 and 53.5 percent on an income of $3,200.
The government has not said what income would be affected by the
maximum 90 percent tax.
   The average industrial worker earns about $320 a month. Workers
in the state sector pay a flat 13 percent tax if they earn more
than $480 a month.
   ``I think this law on progressive taxation on cooperatives is
very bad. It puts obstacles in the way of development of
cooperatives,'' Shmelev said.
   He said the debate in the Supreme Soviet was an encouraging sign
of life in that body.
   Aganbegyan said the tax rates probably would be on the books for
a year or more before they could be amended.
   Eventually, he said a uniform progressive tax rate should be
developed for those who work in cooperatives and those who for
state-run enterprises.
   The law approved Thursday by the Supreme Soviet legally puts
cooperatives on an equal footing with state-run enterprises. It
ensures that cooperative property may not be seized by the state,
allows cooperatives to own buildings and other property not
including land, and them to conduct business with overseas
companies and earn hard currency.
</TEXT>
