<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Explosion     05-27 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Explosion,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Explosion in Garbage Truck Injures One</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion in a garbage
truck Friday night injured the driver and set the vehicle afire,
police reported.
   Police spokesman Pierre Louw said the explosion occurred while a
worker was loading a garbage bin into the back of the truck in
downtown Johannesburg. He said the worker was not hurt but the
driver suffered minor injuries to his face and one arm.
   Louw said police had not determined the cause but suspected it
was a limpet mine, an explosive device that clings to other objects.
   There was no claim of responsibility. Police blame nearly all
explosions the African National Congress, the main guerrilla group
fighting white domination.
   The ANC, based in Lusaka, Zambia, seldom confirms or denies
involvement in specific attacks but acknowledges using bombs in its
campaign against the government.
   More than 70 bombings have been reported in South Africa since a
nationwide state of emergency was declared June 12, 1986, to thwart
an uprising in black townships.
   Two bombs went off Thursday in Pretoria, wounding four white
women. The explosions coincided with the 40th anniversary of rule
by the National Party, architect of the apartheid policy that
preserves power for the 5 million whites and denies a voice in
national affairs to the 26 million blacks.
   

