<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan-Journalist     05-27 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Journalist,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghanistan Pardons Imprisoned French Journalist</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Afghanistan has
pardoned imprisoned French journalist Alain Guillo, state-owned
Radio Kabul said Friday.
   In Paris, the French Communist Party newspaper L'Humanite said
Guillo would be freed Saturday.
   Guillo, a freelancer, was arrested while filming the Afghan war
in northern Afghanistan last September. He was convicted in January
of spying and sentenced to 10 years in prison.
   Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad, quoted Afghan President
Najib as saying Guillo was pardoned in view of ``the old friendship
between France and Afghanistan.''
   He said it was also in view of the Geneva accords signed April
14 to withdraw more than 100,000 Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 and helped
the Marxist government fight U.S.-backed Moslem rebels.
Afghanistan, neighboring Pakistan, the United States and the Soviet
Union signed the Geneva accords.
   Najib announced the pardon after Gilbert Perol, secretary
general of the French External Affairs Ministry, met with Najib,
the newscast said. Perol delivered a personal message from French
President Francois Mitterrand, it said.
   Eric Fornier, spokesman for the French Embassy in Islamabad,
could not confirm the reports that Guillo would be freed Saturday.
   ``Certainly it will be in the next two to three days,'' Fornier
said.
   Guillo has shared a prison cell in Kabul with Italian journalist
Fausto Biloslavo, who is serving a similar sentence, but there was
no word on whether Biloslavo would be released.
   Western diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said they expected Biloslavo's release soon because Najib is trying
to polish his government's image during the Soviet troop withdrawal.
   The Kabul correspondent for L'Humanite, Francis Cremieux, said
Guillo would fly out of Kabul Saturday afternoon and could arrive
in Paris early Sunday. Cremieux, who had met with aides to the
president, reported earlier this week that Guillo would be freed
soon.
   French journalists met with Guillo on May 14 at the
Poul-E-Charki prison near Kabul. They quoted him as saying then
that he would never ask for a pardon because he was innocent of the
spy charges and considered himself a hostage, not a prisoner.
</TEXT>
