<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 2017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-S&LRescue     05-27 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-S&L Rescue,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Board Announces Plan To Rescue S&L</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board said Friday
it was spending $304 million to rescue the Eureka Federal Savings
and Loan Association of San Carlos, Calif.
   America First Financial Corp. of San Francisco will contribute
another $100 million to the package and acquire Eureka's deposits
and 35 branch offices in northern California. The offices will
remain open under the Eureka name.
   The bank board will contribute $291 million in cash from the
Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp., which insures S&L
deposits up to $100,000, to cover Eureka's negative net worth.
   The remaining $23 million in estimated costs to the insurance
fund, which is funded through fees charged the industry, will come
from the purchase of loan participations and coverage of America
First against future loss on problems loans and against challenges
to the rescue package.
   As part of the deal, the bank board will receive $50 million
stock in America First, an affiliate of America First Companies of
Omaha, Neb., and share equally in tax benefits arising from the
transaction.
   Eureka, with $1.74 billion in assets as of March 31, was founded
in 1937. It's been in trouble since the early 1980s, when interest
rates soared, leaving many S&Ls holding low-rate mortgages.
   The bank board, in a release, also attributed the insolvency to
``unsafe and unsound loan underwriting practices.''
   Bank board Chairman, M. Danny Wall, the top federal regulator of
S&Ls, said the rescue was ``especially significant'' because of the
amount of private investment in the deal, which is a record for an
S&L rescue.
   ``This transaction is further evidence ... that the thrift
industry is a good place to invest for the future,'' Wall said in a
statement.
   The Eureka deal is the 34th bailout or shutdown of a failed S&L.
Twenty-three of the 34 were acquired by investors or merged with
existing institutions with FSLIC assistance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
