<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PLO-Arabs     05-27 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-Arabs,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO to Seek Clear-Cut Arab Stands Toward Palestinians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A PLO official said Friday the Arab
nations are not giving Palestinians the political and financial
support they need to continue the 6-month-old uprising in the
Israeli-occupied territories.
   Bassam Abu Sharif said the guerrilla movement will demand clear
stands on the Palestinian issue from all governments during the
Arab summit that begins June 7 in Algeria's capital.
   ``The Algiers summit will be the purgatory through which
everyone will have to pass,'' said Abu Sharif, media advister to
Yasser Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   He made the comments in an article in the London-based
newsletter Mideast Mirror. A copy was telexed to The Associated
Press in Bahrain.
   ``The question that will be asked both in private and in public
will be: `Who among you supports the establishment of a Palestinian
state and who opposes it?','' he said. ``There will be no room for
double talk or half-baked positions.''
   All Arab governments express public support for creation of a
Palestinian state, but hardliners often accuse pro-Western
moderates of avoiding conflict with U.S. Middle East policy.
   The American plan, promoted in trips to the region by Secretary
of State George P. Shultz, proposes limited self-rule for the 1.5
million Palestinians of the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   As of Friday, 198 Palestinians and two Israelis had died in
violence in the occupied territories since the unrest began Dec. 8.
   Abu Sharif claimed the summit had been delayed because of a
``tug of war'' behind the scenes between moderates and hardliners
over the Palestinian issue.
   He said President Chadli Bendjedid of Algeria took the
initiative to call for the summit because of ``a justified belief
that Arab officialdom was guilty of dereliction of duty toward the
Palestinian uprising in the occupied land.''
   Algeria felt Arabs ``not only withheld financial support to the
Palestinians but also kept them under political siege,'' he wrote.
   He argued that the Palestinian uprising had succeeded in putting
the latest U.S. peace initiative ``in a vicious circle'' despite
the support of Washington's ``allies'' in the region. He did not
name the allies.
   Abu Sharif claimed the purpose of the current trip to the Middle
East by Vernon Walters, U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, was
to press for ``starving the PLO of funds'' in order to hamper its
support for the uprising.
</TEXT>
