<2ND_LINE>AM-Singapore-Detainees,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Dismisses Habeas Corpus Of Detainees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The High Court refused requests Friday to
release three people held under the Internal Security Act after
they were charged with being Marxist conspirators against the
government.
   Justice Lai Kew Chai said Home Minister Shanmugam Jayakumar had
acted properly in authorizing the detentions of Kevin De Souza,
Wong Souk Kee and Chng Suan Tze, and that there was no evidence of
bad faith.
   They were arrested last year and released soon afterward, but
picked up again April 19. The Internal Security Act allows the
government to detain a person without trial for two years,
renewable indefinitely.
   In a statement issued April 18, the day before the second
arrest, all three said they were forced to confess and were
mistreated in detention. They denied being Marxist conspirators.
   Officials have not given reasons for rearresting them, but said
their statement ``was a political propaganda ploy to discredit the
government.''
