<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SmallKidnapping     05-27 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Small Kidnapping,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Edwards Sentenced To Death In Stephen Small Kidnapping, Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 31-year-old man was sentenced to death
Friday for the kidnapping and murder of a businessman who was
buried alive last September and suffocated before his family could
pay a $1 million ransom.
   Jurors deliberated less than an hour before voting death for
Daniel J. Edwards of Bourbonnais, who was convicted Monday in
Stephen Small's death. He showed no emotion when the penalty was
announced about 5:30 p.m.
   Prosecutor Frank Nowicki told jurors that Edwards' cruelty
demanded the death penalty, and asked jurors if they could imagine
``a worse way to die,'' as he stood before the homemade wooden box
in which Small's body was found.
   ``Imagine Stephen Small when that lid closed ... his life coming
to an end,'' Nowicki said. ``Imagine the panic he felt, the
helplessness ... to claw, to scrape, to scratch.''
   Edwards' live-in girlfriend, Nancy D. Rish, 26, also is charged
with murder and kidnapping and is awaiting trial. Edwards'
execution date would be set at a hearing later.
   Members of Small's family, including his wife, Nancy, were
immediately escorted from the packed courtroom.
   The jury, which had been selected in Rockford because of
pre-trial publicity in Kankakee, also was escorted from the
courtroom. Police said jurors did not want to talk with reporters.
   Small, 40, was lured from his home Sept. 2, 1987, and calls
demanding a $1 million ransom were made to his family. But the
family could not understand the tape-recorded instructions for
delivering the cash.
   Edwards and Ms. Rish were arrested two days later, the same day
police dug up Small's body from the box in which he was buried in
woods near Kankakee.
   Defense attorney Thomas Allen said there was ``some character''
in Edwards and asked the jury to spare his life. ``Danny's not
doing it to himself. You have to go back there and take a pen in
hand and sign'' the penalty, he said.
   During the death penalty hearing that began Wednesday,
prosecutors presented witnesses who described Edwards' use and sale
of drugs, and a letter he wrote to Mrs. Small and had smuggled out
of the county jail.
   It expressed ``condolences'' and said Small was not meant to
die, but demanded the Small family pay ``a blood debt.''
   The jurors convicted Edwards after listening chilling
tape-recordings of Small saying his kidnapper had put him in a
``grave'' where he would die unless the ransom was paid quickly.
   ``I ain't coming back to dig you back up,'' Small's kidnapper
was heard telling him on the tape, ``... and it's gonna get real
stuffy in here.''
   Small was the great-grandson of former Illinois Gov. Len Small.
He was former vice president of Mid America Media, a group that
owned radio and cable television stations, until the company was
sold in 1986.
</TEXT>
