<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Aruba-Colombian     05-27 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aruba-Colombian,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alleged Colombian Cocaine Trafficker Ordered Extradited to U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR WINKLAAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORANJESTAD, Aruba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-judge panel on this southern
Caribbean island on Friday ordered a Colombian man extradited to
the United States on cocaine trafficking charges.
   Alvaro Triana Murillo, arrested May 16 and held at the request
of the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration, was put aboard a
private plane following his two-hour appearance in court, officials
said in the capital.
   Chief of Police Roland Peterson refused to disclose the plane's
destination, citing security reasons. But Greg Keheo, assistant
U.S. attorney in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., said in a telephone
interview that Triana was being taken to Fort Lauderdale.
   Prosecutor Florencio Wernet told the judges Triana was indicted
by a grand jury in Florida on drug charges.
   Keheo said Triana, 37, faces charges involving the smuggling of
cocaine between 1980 and 1984.
   A spokesman for the DEA office in Miami said Triana ``is a
fugitive out of Fort Lauderdale.''
   Triana, who argued his arrest was a case of mistaken identity,
was held under tight security on this self-governing member of the
Kingdom of the Netherlands, located in the lower Caribbean Sea
about 20 miles off the coast of Venezuela.
   Triana told the three judges he exported automobile parts from
Colombia.
   ``I am innocent,'' he said. ``My misfortune was being born in
Colombia.''
   He left the courtroom in tears.
   Triana's lawyers said the man the DEA really wants is Alvaro
Triana Rodriguez, not their client.
   The judges, who had deliberated several hours, recommended to
Gov. Felipe Tromp that there was sufficient evidence to extradite.
   No U.S. officials attended the hearing.
   While Triana was taken to court, Dutch soldiers were positioned
at the prison and a nearby school was closed. The frigate Van
Kinsbergen patrolled the seas off the island.
</TEXT>
