<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 2010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama 2ndLd-Writethru a0833 05-27 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0833,0796</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Blames U.S. Ambassador, State's Abrams for Talks Breakdown</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New editing and material throughout, UPDATING with later
Noriega quotes blaming two U.S. officials for talks' breakdown,
other. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH NAVARRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega on Friday
blamed U.S. Ambassador Arthur Davis and the State Department's
Elliott Abrams for the breakdown in recent talks on the general's
political future.
   Noriega, who as head of the armed forces is the de facto leader
of Panama, also said he held the Reagan administration responsible
for his personal safety.
   He told a women's convention, ``I place responsibility for the
life of Manuel Antonio Noriega with the establishment of the United
States. I hold the establishment responsible for the life of this
son of God.''
   The United States has been trying to force Noriega to leave as
head of Panama's 15,000-member Defense Forces since he was indicted
by U.S. grand juries in Florida in February as a major drug
trafficker and money-launderer.
   On Wednesday, U.S. officials announced that their talks with
Panama to resolve the struggle over Noriega's leadership had fallen
apart. Secretary of State George P. Shultz blamed the collapse on
Noriega.
   The general did not elaborate on his charges Friday that Davis
and Abrams, the assistant secretary of state for inter-American
affairs, were responsible for the breakdown of the talks.
   But he called for ``foreign forces'' to leave Panama and for the
United States to ``leave Panama in peace. Sirs, for God's sake
leave it in peace.''
   Besides the Panama Canal, the United States also has its
Southern Command in Panama, with overall responsibility for U.S.
military operations in a wide swath of Latin America. About 10,000
U.S. troops with about 20,000 military dependents are in Panama.
   Panama's foreign minister, Jorge Eduardo Ritter, said Friday
Panama's relations with the United States are ``practically
nonexistent.''
   Ritter said relations were bad ``because the United States
maintains recognition of a government that doesn't exist.''
   Washington recognizes Eric Arturo Delvalle as Panama's legal
president, even though he was ousted in February after he tried to
fire Noriega as chief of Defense Forces. Noriega then installed
Manuel Solis Palma as president, and Delvalle has been in hiding
ever since.
   Delvalle said Friday he warned the United States in vain against
go-it-alone tactics in talks with Noriega. He also predicted
violence if Noriega doesn't leave.
   Delvalle said other Latin American democracies offered to help
and that they and the Panamanian opposition should have had a role.
   He met a small number of correspondents, including Associated
Press correspondent Joseph B. Frazier, at a location they agreed
not to disclose and told them:
   ``I have always thought that (the talks) were a ploy to delay
matters, to give (Noriega) time to strengthen his inner circle
within the ... Defense Forces and at the end, yes, to ridicule
President Reagan and the United States. ``I don't think (Noriega)
was sincere, and I told the (Reagan) administration that what
happened would happen. That wasn't very difficult. I told them
about three weeks ago,'' he added.
   Foreign Minister Ritter spoke at a news conference before
leaving for Cuba to attend a conference of non-aligned nations.
Ritter said he would use the Havana meeting to denounce what he
called aggression by the United States against Panama.
   He also said the Noriega discussions with the United States were
informal and did not involve the Foreign Ministry.
   But he added, ``I want to reiterate to you that the reason those
conversations didn't produce any result was the imposition by one
of the sides. That's what finished off the conversations.''
   He also said the government was evaluating damage to the
Panamanian economy as a result of U.S. sanctions imposed in an
effort to force Noriega from power. He said it was looking into
whether there is a basis for filing suit in the International Court
of Justice in Netherlands. A ruling in such a suit, however, would
be put into effect only if both parties agreed.
   Washington wants the general to leave the country and Delvalle
to return as president. In exchange, the United States would lift
economic sanctions and possibly drop the drug charges.
   Noriega also blamed Washington on Thursday for the talks'
collapsing.
   ``The world must know that the conversation sustained with
President Reagan's envoy broke down when he presented us with an
ultimatum in which Panama had to accept immediately his last
offer,'' he told a packed session of the National Assembly.
   Asked then whether his resignation had been discussed, Noriega
replied: ``The commander doesn't abandon his ship in stormy
weather.''
</TEXT>
