<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama-Delvalle 1stLd-Writethru a0841 05-27 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Delvalle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0841,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deposed President Calls Noriega Talks a Ploy, Predicts Violence</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADD 6 grafs at end with additional Delvalle quotes as not
going to give up claim to power, possible violence, other.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deposed President Eric Arturo
Delvalle said from hiding on Friday that he warned the United
States in vain against go-it-alone tactics in talks with Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   He also predicted violence if Noriega doesn't leave.
   Delvalle said other Latin American democracies offered to help
and that they and the Panamanian opposition should have had a role.
   He has been in hiding since his ouster in late February. He met
with a few correspondents Friday morning at a location the
journalists agreed not to disclose.
   On Wednesday, U.S. officials announced that their talks with
Panama to resolve the struggle over Noriega's leadership had fallen
apart. Secretary of State George P. Shultz blamed the collapse on
Noriega.
   Noriega, the de facto leader of Panama as head of the nation's
15,000-member military and police forces, is under indictment in
the United States as a drug trafficker.
   ``I have always thought that (the talks) were a ploy to delay
matters, to give (Noriega) time to strengthen his inner circle
within the Panamanian Defense Forces and at the end, yes, to
ridicule President Reagan and the United States,'' Delvalle said.
   ``I don't think (Noriega) was sincere, and I told the ( Reagan)
administration that what happened would happen. That wasn't very
difficult. I told them about three weeks ago,'' he said.
   ``I am disappointed at the fact that they did not use to their
advantage our knowledge of Noriega,'' Delvalle said, adding that it
is time for the United States to let Latin American nations take
the lead, a move the administration now is exploring.
   Delvalle was vice president and assumed power when President
Nicolas Ardito Barletta, elected by a 1,700-vote edge in 1984, was
ousted in September 1985.
   Delvalle was forced out by Noriega last February after he tried
to fire the general. The United States still recogizes Delvalle as
president.
   He said he has not left Panama since being deposed and that he
is not hiding ``on any military base or in any embassy.''
   What his priority is in any deal that may lead to Noriega's
removal from power is not clear.
   Arrest warrants have been out for him for two months but the
Noriega government is making no apparent serious attempt to find
him.
   Asked if there were circumstances under which he might renounce
his claim, Delvalle responded: ``Why should I? This is one of the
basic factors, respect for the constitution by the military.
   ``All over Latin American there has been a clear, loud message
that (the military) is below civilian government,'' he said.
   Delvalle said Panamanians are not used to street violence but it
could start if Noriega remains and the economy keeps going downhill.
   ``Economic pressures are building up and he knows it,'' Delvalle
said of Noriega.
   ``I think we will be facing violence in the near future,'' he
said. ``The people of Panama are getting desperate. We will see
some violent demonstrations here in the next few days or weeks.''
   Violent street protests have occurred sporadically since last
June, but have halted in what generally is attributed to the
military's successful crackdown and the opposition's difficulty in
mustering support.
</TEXT>
