<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Namibia-Boycott     05-27 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Namibia-Boycott,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20,000 Pupils Boycotting Schools</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINDHOEK, South-West Africa (AP) _ More than 20,000 children in
the north are boycotting classes to protest the presence of South
African military bases near schools, a newspaper reported Friday.
   The Namibian, a weekly paper that supports the South-West
African People's Organization guerrilla movement known as SWAPO,
said the boycott had spread to 20 secondary schools and 15 primary
schools in the territory, also called Namibia.
   It began early this month after South Africa's chief
representative, Louis Peinaar, refused to remove an army base next
to the Ponhofi school in the northern region of Ovambo. He said
bomb shelters were being built at the school to provide protection
in the event of guerrilla bombardments of the base.
   Peter Kalangula, chairman of the Ovambo administrative council,
said the South African refusal to move bases away from Ponhofi and
a few other schools ``is creating hatred against the security
forces.''
   South Africa controls Namibia in defiance of U.N. resolutions
calling for independence. South Africa says it will not grant
independence until Cuban troops withdraw from neighboring Angola,
where SWAPO guerrillas have maintained bases during their
22-year-old bush war.
</TEXT>
