<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Refugees-Vietnam     05-27 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Refugees-Vietnam,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Delegation Meets With U.N. Refugee Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese officials and the the U.N. refugee
agency began their annual meeting Friday, months earlier than usual
following a sharp increase in the number of ``boat people'' fleeing
Indochina.
   According to the agency, 10,628 boat people were registered in
the region in the first four months of this year and the May figure
is expected to top 4,000.
   Among topics to be discussed with a four-member Vietnamese
delegation led by vice foreign minister Ha Van Lau, who also is
ambassador to France, is the 9-year-old Orderly Departure Program,
said Judith Kumin, spokeswoman for the office of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees.
   The meeting normally occurs in autumn.
   Arrivals in Hong Kong increased from 798 in January through
March to 1,381 in April and 1,596 in the first two weeks of May,
Ms. Kumin told a weekly U.N. news briefing.
   She said it was the highest level since 1979. Arrivals in
Malaysia also are above average, with 2,917 in the first quarter of
1988 and 1,904 in April, she said.
   The Orderly Departure Program was negotiated to give Vietnamese
with relatives living abroad a safe, legal alternative to the risks
of fleeing their country by land or by sea as boat people. It has
enabled more than 136,000 Indochinese refugees to resettle in 24
countries since June 1979, Ms. Kumin said.
   Most refugees have gone to the United States and Canada, she
said, and gave the numbers as 65,176 and 24,615 respectively.
   In 1984, the United States called for expansion of the program
by offering to admit all Amerasian children _ most of whose fathers
were U.S. servicemen _ and their close relatives, as well as
political prisoners and their close family members.
   Ms. Kumin said the Amerasian question also was on the agenda of
the annual meeting, scheduled to end Tuesday.
</TEXT>
