<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Paris Opera,0145</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opera Exhibition To Begin World Tour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Costumes, jewelry and set designs used by the Paris
Opera will be displayed in New York next month, the first stop for
an exhibit that will tour Canada, Japan and Spain through 1990.
   ``Three Centuries of Paris Opera Treasures'' opens June 7 at the
Cooper- Hewitt Museum in New York, where it will remain until Sept.
25.
   The exhibit will present 160 pieces from the opera collection,
including costumes designed by artists Pablo Picasso, Marc Chagall,
Fernand Leger and haute couture whiz kid Christian Lacroix.
   Also to be included in the show are costumes designed by Yves
St. Laurent for the ballet ``Notre Dame de Paris'' danced by the
opera ballet company in 1965, and an encrusted Egyptian belt used
in the 1880 production of Verdi's opera ``Aida.''
</TEXT>
