<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MassGrave     05-27 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mass Grave,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Remains Found In Mass Grave Older Than World War II</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts analyzing remains found in
a mass grave believe the bones may be almost two centuries old and
not of World War II Nazi concentration camp victims, the news
agency CTK said Friday.
   The state-run agency said new evidence indicates the remains may
have been buried in northwestern Czechoslovakia under the reign of
Joseph II, who held power in the region in the late 18th century.
   CTK said the emperor had ordered that corpses be reburied
outside municipal limits to prevent disease.
   The remains were found May 19 during work in a quarry near the
town of Most, about 50 miles northwest of Prague.
   Archeologists had speculated that the remains could have either
been those of death camp inmates killed by the Nazis or victims of
Allied bombing attacks.
   ``The remains ... originally believed to come from the World War
II period have been subject to ... (testing) which showed that they
probably come from the period of the reign of Joseph II,'' CTK said.
   The news agency did not provide sources for the report and did
not elaborate.
   But an official of the Most District Museum, which is in charge
of the project, told The Associated Press the remains come from the
time of Joseph II or the Napoleonic wars.
   ``I talked to people here who remember the end of World War II
and no one recalled anything like this,'' said Libuse Pokorna.
   She said it was impossible to immediately estimate the number of
the dead buried in the grave.
   Pokorna said final results from the tests could take a month.
</TEXT>
