<HEAD>Woman Returns to Letterman House After He Refuses to Prosecute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW CANAAN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was arrested driving David
Letterman's sports car and claiming she was his wife was arrested
again after police found her inside the suburban home of the TV
talk show host, authorities said Friday.
   Margaret M. Ray, 36, of no known address, was arrested Thursday
night and arraigned Friday in Norwalk Superior Court on two counts
of second-degree burglary and first-degree larcency, authorities
said.
   She entered no plea and was ordered held on $25,000 bail pending
a June 15 court appearance.
   Her second arrest came after a cab driver tipped police that he
had just driven her from the local train station to Letterman's
house _ a day after New Jersey prosecutors dropped charges from her
first arrest, Capt. Michael Angelastro said.
   ``It's very difficult at this time to explain her behavior based
on what we know,'' Angelastro said. ``We don't know where she is
from. We are trying to determine that.''
   Ms. Ray first was arrested Sunday at the Lincoln Tunnel as she
drove the blue, 1988 Porsche Carrera into New York from New Jersey
with a 3-year-old passenger. She didn't have the $3 toll,
authorities said.
   ``I'm Mrs. David Letterman and this is David Jr.,'' Ms. Ray was
reported by authorities to have told the toll collector. ``Don't
you think David Letterman is good for the toll?''
   The child was put into the custody of New Jersey juvenile
authorities.
   Although Letterman decided not to press charges after Sunday's
incident, authorities will prosecute the woman on the latest
charges regardless of the entertainer's wishes, Angelastro said.
   ``She had no right being in the house and we took firm action
against her when we found out she had entered the house last
night,'' he said.
   After Sunday's arrest, New Canaan police alerted by Port
Authority officials found signs that someone, apparently Ms. Ray,
had broken into Letterman's modest, two-story house through a
living room window, Angelastro said.
   Furniture, plants and a rug had been moved around and there were
dirty dishes in the sink, he said.
   Ms. Ray apparently entered the house through the same living
room window again Thursday night, Angelastro said. She didn't
repeat her claim that she was Letterman's wife, he said.
   Letterman, the gap-toothed host of ``Late Night with David
Letterman,'' was reached by police in Los Angeles, where he has
been staying.
   Although Angelastro said Ms. Ray has made no threatening remarks
about Letterman, he believed Letterman was concerned about the
incidents. ``I'm sure this matter is of great concern to him,'' he
said.
   After Sunday's arrest, Letterman told authorities he didn't know
the woman and that she didn't have permission to drive her car.
   Authorities said that after identifying herself Sunday as Mrs.
Letterman, Ms. Ray then called herself Jane Doe, Margaret Ray and
finally Mary Ray. Angelastro said police found documents indicating
her correct name is Margaret M. Ray.
   A spokeswoman for the New Jersey Division of Youth and Family
Services DYFS said Friday she could not discuss the child's
whereabouts because of New Jersey confidentialy laws.
   Jack Rollins, Letterman's agent, was not in his office Friday
afternoon and was unavailable for comment, a spokeswoman said.
</TEXT>
