<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Turkey     05-27 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Turkey,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greece, Turkey Pledge To Cool Tensions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VOULIAGMENI, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greece and Turkey pledged Friday to
cool tensions in the Aegean Sea region and continue a gradual
improvement in relations between the once-hostile NATO allies.
   Foreign Ministers Carolos Papoulias of Greece and Mesut Yilmaz
of Turkey told a joint news conference that four days of talks this
week on political cooperation ended ``positively.''
   ``The first steps we have made here are modest but encouraging.
... I believe that we are duty-bound to succeed in our future
efforts as well,'' Yilmaz told reporters before leaving for Turkey.
   Both countries agreed to avoid staging military maneuvers in the
Aegean Sea during holidays and the summer tourist season.
   Greece and Turkey monitor each other's military exercises in the
region and fighter pilots often stage mock dogfights over the
Aegean.
   Greece has often protested alleged harrassment by Turkish
fighters of Olympic Airways passenger jets flying tourists to the
Aegean islands.
   The talks this week preceded a scheduled June 13-15 visit to
Athens by Premier Turgut Ozal of Turkey.
   Ozal and Premier Andreas Papandreou of Greece agreed to avoid
confrontation and boost bilateral relations during a January
meeting in Davos, Switzerland.
   Greece and Turkey have longstanding disputes over control of
Aegean airspace, the military status of some Greek islands and the
divided Mediterranean island of Cyprus.
   In March 1987, they came to the brink of war over seabed oil
drilling rights.
   But Papoulias said the ministers delayed discussion of ``large
issues'' such as the presence of Turkish troops on Cyprus for
Ozal's visit.
   The officials abolished abolished visa rules for diplomats in
each other's capitals and agreed to continue talks on cooperation
against narcotics, smuggling and terrorism.
</TEXT>
