<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Rebel     05-27 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Rebel,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contra Leader Turns Himself In, Encourages Others to Do Same</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rebel military leader turned himself
in to the leftist government and said Friday he will try to bring
the 400 Contras formerly under his command out of the mountains.
   Felix Garcia Hernandez, alias Commander Alfa Lima, 26, told
reporters Friday he had decided to quit the U.S.-supported
insurgency on Wednesday and take advantage of the Sandinista
government's amnesty program.
   Alfa Lima, a former evangelical preacher before he took up arms
against the government, spoke to reporters accompanied by
Sandinista officials.
   His acceptance of the amnesty coincided with the third round of
high-level peace talks in Managua between the government and a
Contra delegation that included his former commander-in-chief,
Enrique Bermudez.
   ``We regret it,'' Bermudez said upon learning of Alfa Lima's
decision. ``He was a field commander with a long record. We
consider him a war casualty.''
   The Nicaraguan government considered Alfa Lima one of the most
effective Contra field commanders. He had led a special military
task force in central Chontales province since 1984.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Alfa Lima said his
decision followed a series of talks with his troops and with
Sandinista Army soldiers during the provisional truce that went
into effect April 1.
   ``We sat in this farm in Chontales and we talked about how we
Nicaraguans were killing each other,'' Alfa Lima said. ``We talked
about how we wanted peace.''
   The Contras took up arms against the Sandinistas in November
1981.
   On Wednesday, he and six of his men abandoned their camp in
Chontales.
   ``We had many problems,'' he said. ``I had more than 400 men
under my command. Since February we had trouble getting supplies.
We would ask the command in Honduras for supplies and then the
planes supposedly would come from the Honduran bases. But the
commanders refused to supply us. They were hoarding everything
since the truce started.''
   Alfa Lima said he hoped to encourage more of his former Contra
troops to take advantage of the amnesty.
   ``I am going to try to convince my men to come in. There are
many out there who do not know what they are doing or why they are
fighting,'' said the soft-spoken Alfa Lima, still wearing his
camouflage uniform.
   ``Many of them are people separated from society. They say they
fight for democracy, for freedom, because they were told that, but
they don't really know,'' he said.
   ``I am going to show them that there are guarantees,'' he added.
   Under the program the government enacted in 1985, rebels may lay
down their arms and return to normal life in Nicaragua without fear
of reprisal.
   Alfa Lima said he joined the Contras in 1982 after he was
threatened and harassed by a Sandinista Army officer while he
served as an evangelical pastor in his native Jinotega province.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
