<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Shortages     05-27 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Shortages,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coffee and Meat in Short Supply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beef and pork have disappeared from
meat counters throughout communist Yugoslavia as a new wave of
shortages hit the country, a federal market inspectors' report to
the government said Friday.
   Coffee was reported in sparse supply in some parts and cleaning
powder can only be bought on and off, the Belgrade daily Politika
quoted as saying in their report.
   Other staples in short supply included butter, car tires, cement
and some construction materials.
   Most Yugoslavs have been reported on a mass shopping spree in
recent weeks in anticipation of steep price rises expected when a
government price freeze ends next month.
   The new austerity program, aimed at curbing Europe's highest
inflation and repaying a $20 billion foreign debt, provides for
further wage cuts and widespread price increases.
   The measures were originally due to start May 15 but were put
off until June because new loans from Western creditors failed to
materialize.
   The economic package is intended to reduce wages of Yugoslavs by
up to 30 percent at a time when 80 percent of manufacturers
announced new, higher prices for their products after the price
freeze expires.
   Slovenian furniture manufacturers have already announced price
increases of up to 80 percent and those of electric ware and paper
products of up to 100 percent after the 6{-month freeze is lifted.
   To cope with the meat shortage, the government announced it was
making available 20,000 tons of meat from emergency reserves.
   Bozidar Komadinic, director general of Centroproizvod company,
said there was little hope that coffee will be available in
Belgrade or Serbia any time soon, Politika reported.
</TEXT>
