<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices plunged in Tokyo Saturday over rumors
that the United States may hike its official discount rate, traders
said.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the Tokyo Stock
Exchange's key index, dropped 327.99 points or 1.2 percent during
Saturday's half-day session, closing at 26,962.50.
   Traders said rumors of a U.S. discount rate hike reduced stock
purchases, causing a decline in the market index.
   ``Speculation that the U.S. Federal Reserve may hike its
discount rate spread all over Kabuto-cho (Tokyo's financial
district),'' said a broker at a major securities firm. ``Investors
are assuming that the speculation is reliable after seeing the
higher-than-expected U.S. GNP growth rate figures for the first
quarter of the year, and as a result are selling shares,'' he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported a 3.9 percent growth rate
in the gross national product during the first three months of the
year, higher than the earlier estimate of 2.3 percent.
   ``The upcoming long weekend in the U.S. made many investors
unwilling to participate in trading today,'' added another analyst
at a major securities firm, referring to the Memorial Day weekend
in the United States starting Saturday.
   The volume on the market's first section was 850 million shares.
   Tokyo's foreign exchange market is closed on Saturdays.
</TEXT>
