<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-BritishBiz Adv31   05-27 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-British Biz, Adv 31,0764</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, May 31, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>British Business Programs Become Popular</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talking about money is something that just wasn't
done in Britain until only a few years ago.
   Now, because of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's capitalist
revolution, business, economics and personal finance are
increasingly popular subjects on British television.
   The number of television hours devoted to money matters has
grown to more than 200 a year from about 30 hours annually just
four years ago.
   ``Business is suddenly a much more interesting topic,'' said
Caroline Thomson, independent Channel 4's commissioning editor for
business, industry and science.
   The new shows have included a daily news show, a game show and
even a dramatic series.
   Britain's two publicly funded British Broadcasting Corp.
channels and two independent channels are all thinking money, but
the biggest push has been made by Channel 4.
   In September it introduced ``Business Daily,'' a half-hour news
program airing at midday Monday through Friday and targeted at
professionals in the City, London's financial district.
   In addition, Channel 4 introduced in January a Sunday night game
show, ``The Stocks and Shares Show,'' in which contestants compete
to make the most profit by investing play money in stocks.
   Channel 4 also recently ran a live weekly series called ``The
Business Exchange,'' which gave advice to some of Britain's budding
entrepreneurs on how to get financing and other topics.
   Also unusual was a six-part weekly dramatic series set in the
City, rather than more typically in London's swanky neighborhoods,
the cockney East End or the government's labyrinthian buildings.
   Called ``Killing on the Exchange,'' it ran on Independent
Television's main channel in prime time last year.
   ``There has been a big change in attitude in the past five years
toward business with privatization and the Big Bang explosion in
the City,'' Ms. Thomson said.
   Mrs. Thatcher has privatized, or sold off, billions of pounds'
worth of nationalized industries since she came into power in 1979,
partly to get more shares into the hands of the British public.
   The number of individual shareholders in Britain has trebled to
7 million in the nine years.
   Big Bang, most of which took place in October 1986, was a huge
deregulation and computerization of Britain's financial services
industry.
   ``Now, in Mrs. Thatcher's Britain, people can talk about profit
without it being a dirty word,'' Ms. Thomson said.
   Not all television viewers have been capitivated by these money
matters programs. Ms. Thomson conceded that talking about personal
finances is still taboo for many Britons.
   ``The respectable thing in Britain is not to talk about
finances, even how much they paid for a house. There are all sorts
of traditions about not revealing how much you earn.'' she said.
``That's part of the British being rather buttoned-up people.''
   The husband of a woman interviewed for ``Moneyspinner,'' a
Channel 4 personal finances program, had a fit when he found out
about it and insisted that the interview be deleted, Ms. Thomson
said.
   Still, ``Moneyspinner,'' which appears Tuesday nights in series
of eight programs, is the most popular of the money shows on
Channel 4, attracting about 2 million viewers.
   ``The Stocks and Shares Show'' has its detractors, too.
   ``It's caused more controversy than anything else I've done,''
Ms. Thomson said. Critics feel the channel shouldn't encourage
speculation, she said.
   The innovative programming comes on top of an increase in the
number of more traditional types of money matters shows, such as
the weekly current affairs programs and the odd documentary on, for
example, insider trading.
   The oldest and most popular money program on British television
is BBC 2's 22-year-old ``The Money Programme,'' a current-affairs
show viewed by almost 3 million people on Sunday evenings.
   The show features hosts conducting studio interviews with
business-world celebrities and expanded segments on newsworthy
topics.
   The trend is evident in the theater, too. Currently running are
the British plays ``Serious Money,'' which is also playing in New
York, and ``Speculators.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   FILMING STARTS _ ``Murderers Among Us: The Simon Wiesenthal
Story,'' a movie for HBO, has gone into production in Budapest,
Hungary, with Academy Award-winner Ben Kingsley (``Gandhi'')
playing the famous Nazi hunter. The movie also stars Renee
Soutendijk as Wiesenthal's wife, Cyla, and Craig T. Nelson as an
American military officer who helped Wiesenthal.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, May 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
