<1ST_LINE>a p AM-HollywoodPolitics Adv31   05-27 1011</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hollywood Politics, Adv 31,1038</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tuesday AMs, May 31, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Hollywood Activists Take Sides as Primary Approaches</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Hollywood stars are beginning to shine for
favored candidates in the June 7 California primary election, but
many Democratic celebrities remain uncommitted in a race
complicated by Jesse Jackson's anti-Jewish image.
   Not that big money isn't being raised. Nor is all the glitter
gone.
   For example, radio personality Casey Kasem and his actress wife,
Jean, are hosts for a celebrity fund-raiser for Jackson on June 5
at trendy Spago restaurant, known for its unconventional California
pizzas.
   Among those expected to attend the $1,000-a-slice, Western-theme
party are Eddie Murphy, Debbie Allen, Hugh Hefner, Herbie Hancock,
Billy Davis Jr. and Marilyn McCoo.
   Hollywood support is often vigorously sought by political
candidates, who know stars attract attention, money and _ they hope
_ voters to a campaign.
   On the Republican side, where the race was over long ago, Cheryl
Ladd, Robert Stack and producer Jerry Weintraub have endorsed Vice
President George Bush, while Frank Sinatra, Tom Selleck, Helen
Hayes, Oscar de la Renta and Yvette Mimieux have made contributions
to his campaign, said Bush's deputy finance chairman, Fred Bush.
   But things are messier among the Democrats.
   So far this season, Sally Field, Oliver Stone, Richard Gere, Ed
Begley Jr., Tony Randall, Carly Simon, Leonard Nimoy and Shelley
Winters have endorsed Michael Dukakis, the Democratic front-runner,
according to the Massachusetts governor's local spokesman, Mike
Devereaux.
   Jackson has attracted many black celebrities to his camp,
including comedians Bill Cosby and Murphy as well as Quincy Jones,
Lou Gossett Jr. and Gladys Knight. And some white performers have
pledged their support, including Valerie Harper, Margot Kidder and
Dennis Weaver.
   However, most Hollywood Democrats _ the show business
community's dominant party _ have yet to endorse either Jackson or
Dukakis.
   ``Hollywood has always been mostly Jewish and liberal,'' said
Alex Ben Block, editor of Show Biz News, a twice-monthly newsletter
covering the business side of the entertainment industry.
   ``From a Jewish point of view, it's almost unconscionable to
support Jackson,'' he said. However, neither is there any public
rush to oppose the black civil rights activist who is the most
liberal candidate in the race.
   Rabbi Marvin Hier, dean of the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los
Angeles, said Jews in Hollywood are caught between black friends
who are asking them to consider Jackson and Jewish friends who say
they must oppose him.
   ``People are caught. Anyone who endorses Jesse Jackson will not
be thought of as a hero in the Jewish community,'' Hier said.
   ``Among conservative Jewish people in this industry, Jesse
Jackson is simply unacceptable,'' said Michael Medved, film critic
for PBS' ``Sneak Previews'' and president of the Pacific Jewish
Center. ``The feeling is so intense, friendships would be so
imperiled and business would be imperiled.''
   Jackson alienated many Jews by referring to New York as
``Hymietown'' in 1984, by publicly embracing Yasser Arafat of the
Palestine Liberation Organization and by being associated with
Muslim leader Louis Farrakhan.
   The uncommitted Hollywood group includes such activists as
two-time Oscar winner Jane Fonda and her husband, Assemblyman Tom
Hayden; Norman Lear, Emmy Award-winning producer of television's
``The Archie Bunker Show,'' and Lew Wasserman, chairman of MCA Inc.
They were among those on Show Biz News' list of the 10 most
powerful political fund-raisers in Hollywood.
   Lear, whose political organization, ``People for the American
Way,'' mounted a nationwide campaign to defeat the nomination of
Robert Bork to the U.S. Supreme Court, is busy with his new
production company, Act III, said his spokeswoman, Betsy Kenny.
   ``When you jump into a presidential campaign, it takes a lot of
work and commitment, and he doesn't feel compelled to do so at this
time,'' Ms. Kenny said.
   Miss Fonda has been in Mexico since January filming ``Old
Gringo'' with co-stars Gregory Peck and Jimmy Smits.
   ``She has no plans to endorse anyone before the primary,'' said
spokesman Steve Rivers. ``Her mind is in 1913 (the time period of
the movie). But she says she will support the Democratic nominee.''
   Medved said the Haydens face a ``Catch 22'' with the Jackson
issue: If he and Miss Fonda support Jackson, they risk offending
Hayden's largely Jewish West Los Angeles constituency. If the
couple does not support Jackson, Hayden could find himself at odds
with his political leader, Assembly Speaker Willie Brown, who is
Jackson's national campaign manager, and with his longtime seatmate
in the Assembly chambers, Assemblyman Tom Bates, who is co-chairman
of Jackson's California campaign.
   Another observer, John Emerson, an official in the Los Angeles
City Attorney's Office who was deputy campaign manager of Gary
Hart's first 1988 presidential campaign, said Jackson is not really
the issue.
   ``Most of the people in Hollywood, both the executives and
celebrities, were either committed to Gary Hart or (Sen.) Joe
Biden. Both those campaigns blew up. There was a sense of not
wanting to be burned again so they wanted to wait out the primary.
But they will throw themselves into the (November) presidential
race,'' said Emerson, who now supports Dukakis.
   Ed Asner is ``on the verge'' of supporting Dukakis, and Telly
Savalas also likes him, said Mike Mamakos, spokesman for both stars.
   Conservative Republicans in Hollywood are few, but the ones who
are active are expected to work for Bush, including Charlton Heston.
   ``He will be supporting Bush, but he won't make an announcement
until after the nomination,'' said Heston's spokesman, Michael
Levine.
   Sylvester Stallone also remains uncommitted, but the tough-guy
star of the ``Rocky'' and ``Rambo'' series ``did vote for Mr.
Reagan, whom he admires greatly,'' said Stallone's spokesman, Paul
Block. ``He hasn't declared yet. But I will say that Mr. Stallone
is a Republican.''
   ``Gov. Michael Dukakis will easly beat out Jesse Jackson in the
Hollywood fund-raising race leading up to the California primary,''
Block said. ``While Hollywood is overwhelmingly Democratic and
liberal, there will also be considerable support for Vice President
George Bush.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance Tues AMs May 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
