<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0756EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-SouthAfrica-ANC Adv05   05-27 1117</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Africa-ANC, Adv 05,1148</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sun June 5 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>African National Congress Attracts Some South African Whites</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite repeated setbacks, the
African National Congress presses on with military and underground
efforts to unseat the apartheid government. Some of its new
guerrilla recruits are young whites.
   ``There is a continuing trend of young, well-educated liberal
and left-wing whites to identify themselves with the ANC,'' said
Tom Lodge, a political scientist at the University of the
Witwatersrand and an expert on the ANC.
   Increasingly, he added, the whites see the organization as ``a
legitimate and morally admirable political force.''
   Police say they have seized ANC whites with caches of arms,
arrested another in a car bombing and charged at least one with
treason.
   But ANC military activities have diminished.
   In the past year, bombings in South Africa have declined, police
have claimed major breakthroughs against ANC guerrillas, and even
the organization's leaders have conceded that its military actions
were more effective during the widespread unrest of 1984-86.
   ANC guerrillas generally operate in small groups and have little
hope of scoring conventional victories against South Africa's
powerful security forces. However, the ANC says its bombing and
sabotage campaign remains an essential element of its multi-pronged
strategy to oust the white-led government.
   ``We must step up our attacks on the police, the army and other
personnel associated with the institution (government),'' ANC
President Oliver Tambo said in March in neighboring, black-governed
Zimbabwe. ``We will strike against its economic infrastructure and
do much more intensively what we have been doing all the time.''
   However, the talk has not been matched by action.
   Two years ago, the ANC was claiming that it had enough popular
support in South Africa to direct a ``people's power'' campaign
that would make the country ungovernable.
   But since the government imposed a nationwide state of emergency
in June 1986, black unrest has dwindled from daily outbursts across
the country to sporadic, isolated incidents. ANC activity has
declined simultaneously.
   Fifty bombings were reported in the first year of the emergency
but only about 20 in the past 11 months. Police say that since the
beginning of 1987 they have killed 54 suspected ANC members and
captured 525, inflicting major setbacks to ANC operations inside
South Africa.
   ``Terrorists who are sent to the republic (South Africa) are
going on suicide missions, because confrontation with the security
forces means either certain death or a long period of
imprisonment,'' said Adriaan Vlok, the government's law and order
minister.
   However, the recent defeats do not appear to have hampered the
ANC's ability to recruit members into its military wing, known as
Umkhonto we Sizwe (Spear of the Nation).
   ``People don't join the ANC if they are worried about
setbacks,'' said Tom Sebina, a spokesman at ANC headquarters in
Lusaka, Zambia. ``People have joined _ and they continue to join _
because they are committed to our liberation struggle.''
   The ANC refuses to say what its membership is, but it is
variously estimated at 4,000 to 10,000 men with military training,
most of whom are in camps in Tanzania and Angola. No more than a
few hundred are believed to be inside South Africa.
   Whites always have had some role in ANC political activities,
some of them in its upper echelons, but spokesman Sebina said the
involvement of young whites has been growing in the 1980s, though
he declined to give any figures.
   When police arrested four whites May 8 at a farmhouse outside
Pretoria, they claimed their largest arms seizure ever. The whites
had a Soviet-made SAM-7 ground-to-air missile, limpet mines, hand
grenades, machine guns, mortars and explosives, the police said.
   The leading suspect in a car bombing that killed three people
March 17 is a 24-year-old white man whose father is a university
journalism professor.
   In Cape Town, Jenny Schreiner, a 31-year-old white whose father
is a university administrator, is on trial with 12 black
co-defendants charged with treason and terrorism.
   The government portrays the ANC as a communist-led terrorist
group that kills civilians and lacks widespread support and
political legitimacy.
   ``The conviction that the ANC is conducting a futile struggle is
already taking root in the their ranks,'' said Vlok, the law and
order minister.
   The government also claims the ANC is torn by internal strife,
that numerous of its defectors have joined the South African police
force and that the ANC keeps its dissidents in at an ``inhuman''
detention camp in northern Angola.
   Sebina denied those claims.
   He said South African agents, not internal ANC feuding, were
behind the six killings this year of ANC officials living outside
South Africa. He disclaimed any knowledge of recent defections by
ranking ANC members and said the organization did not maintain
detention camps for dissidents.
   ``The government has been making similar noises for a long
time,'' said Sebina. ``They said our back was broken when we were
outlawed (in 1960). They said the same thing when (Nelson) Mandela
was arrested (in 1962). One or two defeats will not end our
struggle.''
   Mandela, the ANC leader at the time of his arrest, is in prison
but remains a rallying point for the organization and the large
majority of blacks.
   Founded in 1912 as a black rights movement, the ANC took up arms
in 1961, the year after it was banned, saying it was left with no
alternative.
   It is the largest black group fighting the government, and it is
widely believed that the ANC would win national elections if the
country's 26 million blacks were allowed to vote.
   The ANC has offices in many African nations as well as Eastern
and Western Europe in hopes of advancing its political fortunes.
   The ANC has been drawing up a new set of guidelines for a
post-apartheid constitution that is reported to be their most
detailed political document ever.
   The Weekly Mail newspaper of Johannesburg said the proposal
calls for a mixed economy, a bill of rights and a multi-party
government. It also calls for equalizing wealth, a sensitive issue
in a country where blacks make up about 75 percent of the
population but own less than 2 percent of the country's fixed
assets.
   The most contentious issue involving the ANC remains its use of
violence. The government says it won't talk to the ANC until it
lays down its arms. The ANC says the arms are necessary to bring
the government into genuine negotiations.
   ``There has been no reassessment of the armed struggle,'' said
Sebina. ``There are still bombs exploding here and there, and I'm
sure there will be more of them.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sun June 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
