<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   05-27 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0488</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy grew at a surprisingly rapid
annual rate of 3.9 percent from January through March, much better
than previously believed, the government said.
   The Commerce Department reported Thursday that the gross
national product, the broadest measure of economic health, was
propelled during the first three months of the year by an export
surge, a rebound in car sales and a boom in business capital
investment.
   The report represented a sharp upward revision from an initial
estimate made a month ago that the GNP grew at a more modest 2.3
percent rate in the first quarter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporations' after-tax profits edged up 0.5
percent in the first three months of the year, a much smaller
increase than in the last quarter of 1987, the government said.
   The Commerce Department reported Thursday that after-tax profits
rose to an annual rate of $146.4 billion, following a gain of 2.6
percent in the previous quarter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of people losing their jobs to mass
layoffs or plant closings appears to have declined sharply last
year, but one in four of them still exhausted their unemployment
benefits before finding new work, the government reported.
   In 1987, a total of 195,950 workers were caught up in mass
layoffs or plant closings in the 11 states, compared with 272,436
workers in 1986, the Bureau of Labor Statistics said Thursday in
its first comprehensive report on the issue.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House passed a $1.1 trillion federal
budget for the 1989 fiscal year after negotiators from the House
and Senate solved a month-long dispute over domestic spending.
   The measure was approved Thursday by a 201-181 vote and sent to
the Senate, where it was expected to be accepted after that chamber
returns from its Memorial Day recess next month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharply divided Securities and Exchange
Commission broke with the Reagan administration by asking Congress
for authority to regulate the nation's stock index futures markets.
   The commission voted 3-2 Thursday to submit to Congress proposed
legislation that would strip jurisdiction for equity-related
futures from the Commodity Futures Trading Commission.
   In another proposal, the SEC said it should have emergency power
to call trading halts, delay the opening of the market or close it
early.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street has lost 8,200 jobs since October's
stock market crash and likely will shed another 18,000 workers by
year's end, an economist said.
   The report released Thursday by New York University Professor
Matthew P. Drennan was slightly more optimistic than his forecast
late last year that the securities industry in New York would lose
28,000 jobs by the end of 1988 because of the crash.
</TEXT>
