<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carl C. Icahn's flashy $60-a-share offer for
Texaco Inc. stirred little excitement on Wall Street, where
market-watchers called the bid more of a negotiating ploy than a
serious offer.
   On the New York Stock Exchange, shares in the nation's
third-largest oil company opened about $4 higher Thursday but
dropped back late in the day to close at $50, up $3.12{.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Shoreham nuclear power plant, long a
burden to Long Island Lighting Co., will be taken over by New York
state and torn down under an agreement reached by state officials
and the utility.
   If Thursday's agreement, which is subject to many conditions,
goes through, it would be the first time a completed nuclear power
plant was abandoned before it opened.
   The deal calling for LILCO to sell the $5.3 billion plant to the
state for $1 was a victory for opponents of the facility 55 miles
east of Manhattan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For years, the 757 had been the stepchild in
Boeing Co.'s fleet: a plane highly praised but seldom bought.
   But in a flurry of multibillion-dollar orders, including United
Airlines' announcement Thursday that it was ordering 30 757s and
taking options on 30 more, the twin-engine, medium-range jetliner
suddenly is Boeing Commercial Airplanes' hot item.
   Boeing valued the 30 firm orders at $1.3 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department told H.J. Heinz Co. of
Pittsburgh and Bumble Bee Seafoods Inc. of San Diego it would file
suit to block Heinz's attempt to merge the marketers of two of the
country's three leading brands of canned tuna.
   ``The proposed acquisition poses a significant threat to
competition and to the American consumer,'' Charles F. Rule, head
of the department's Antitrust Division, said Thursday. ``Canned
tuna is one of the most popular staple foods on the grocery shelf.
This merger could result in major increases in the prices consumers
must pay for one of their favorite foods.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students shouting ``Go Home Yankees!''
attacked a U.S. bank with rocks and firebombs, and farmers
protesting U.S. agricultural imports hurled cow dung at police
during a clash outside the National Assembly.
   Prime Minister Lee Hyun-jai on Thursday ordered a crackdown on
violent protests and radicals, but the mandate seemed to have
little effect on the wave of anti-American rage.
   About 30 students dashed out of sidestreets and hurled rocks and
firebombs at a branch in southern Seoul of the KorAm Bank, police
said. Four people were arrested.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices pieced together a small gain Thursday as the market
absorbed the news of stronger economic growth in the first quarter
of the year. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.38
points to 1,966.75.
   Bond prices declined.
   The dollar was marginally higher against major foreign
currencies. Gold prices fell.
   Cocoa futures prices plummeted.
</TEXT>
