<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoQuality     05-27 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Quality,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Porsche Comes in First in Car Quality Survey; Three GM Makes Reach
Top 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Porsche placed first in an annual survey naming
the 10 most trouble-free cars, while three General Motors Corp.
models made the list, two of them for the first time.
   The J.D. Power and Associates car quality survey was mailed to
75,000 owners of new 1988 model cars purchased in November and
December and asked for the number of problems experienced during
the first 90 days. The survey results were announced Thursday.
   More than 30,000 owners answered the 1988 survey, said Bruce
Johnson, senior project director for the Agoura Hills, Calif.,
consulting firm.
   The results: Porsche topped the list of most trouble-free cars
with 111 problems reported per 100 cars. Porsche cars came in sixth
in 1987.
   Bumped to the second spot by Porsche was Mercedes-Benz, a fellow
West German automaker whose owners reported 115 problems per 100
cars in 1988, up from 108 in 1987, when it placed first.
   Toyota and Nissan tied for third place with 122 problems per 100
cars, an improvement for both. In 1987, Nissan was third with 125
problems and Toyota was fourth with 129.
   Honda's upscale Acura line slipped to fifth in 1988 from second
in 1987. Owners reported 138 problems per 100 cars in 1988, up from
117 in 1987.
   Daihatsu, which ranked as the sixth most trouble-free car,
barely made it into the 1988 survey, Johnson said, because the
company began selling cars in the United States in December.
Daihatsu owners reported 141 problems per 100 cars.
   GM's Cadillac, with 143 problems per 100 cars was seventh, while
Buick, with 153, was eighth and Oldsmobile, with 157, placed ninth.
Cadillac and Oldsmobile made the list for the first time since J.D.
Powers began the survey in 1985.
   No American models made the list in 1987.
   Honda's other lines fell to No. 10, with 158 problems per 100
cars compared to the 130 problems that put the company in fifth
place in 1987.
   Mazda, Subaru, BMW and Mitsubishi, which ranked seventh through
10th in 1987, did not make the list this year. J.D. Powers reports
only the top 10 rankings, and in 1987, it announced the number of
trouble reports for only the top five cars.
   ``We discovered there is a relationship between customer
satisfaction and the problems that owners experience,'' Johnson
said.
   He said results of the short-term car quality survey have been
mirrored in the J.D. Power Customer Satisfaction Index, a rating of
dealers produced by surveying owners 12 months after their purchase.
   The CSI is important to auto dealers because auto manufacturers
use it to determine which dealers receive hot new models, new car
lines or even new brands.
   Dealers have complained that the CSI reflects problems with
vehicles more than problems with dealers, making dealers suffer for
manufacturers mistakes.
   Johnson said both dealer and vehicle quality play in the CSI
ratings.
   ``The more problems, the more pressure on the dealer to fix the
car,'' he said, adding that previous survey shows about 50 percent
of the problems customers bring back to dealerships are repaired.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0258EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BankAmerica     05-27 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BankAmerica,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clausen Says Once-Troubled Company Has Turned Corner</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BankAmerica Corp. remains ``a few more
quarters'' of operating profitability away from restoring the
dividend the beleaguered banking giant dropped in 1985, its
chairman said.
   But A.W. Clausen painted an upbeat picture of prospects for the
nation's third-largest bank holding company at BankAmerica's annual
shareholders meeting Thursday.
   ``BankAmerica is on the road to recovery,'' Clausen said at a
news conference preceding the meeting.
   ``Our turnaround was grounded on a realistic plan to focus on
core objectives, to improve the performance of the credit
portfolio, and to bring our expenses and revenues into profitable
alignment,'' he said.
   As proof of the recovery, Clausen pointed to a 62 percent
increase in first-quarter 1988 profit, decreases in net credit
losses over the past six quarters, and reduced expenses from
operations and the sale of nonstrategic businesses.
   Clausen also noted reductions in core business expenses, such as
personnel, and increases in net interest income during 1987 and
strengthening of the bank's primary capital ratio over the past six
quarters.
   ``Our challenge is to improve fundamental net income on a
quarter-by-quarter basis, to bring in each quarter's fundamental
earnings at a higher level than the previous quarter, and to extend
the recent track record of solid and continuous profitability,'' he
said.
   Clausen, a former head of the World Bank who returned as chief
executive of BankAmerica in late 1986, drew a salary of $775,000
last year.
   BankAmerica stock closed 12.5 cents higher at $10.375 a share in
composite trading Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange.
   In 1987, BankAmerica reported a net loss of $955 million, which
followed a 1986 loss of $518 million. The company recorded a profit
for the first time in six quarters in the third period of 1987,
posting net income of $54 million.
   For the first quarter of 1988, the company reported net income
of $109 million, or 56 cents a share, up from a profit of $67
million, or 34 cents a share, a year earlier. The company reported
higher earnings for the third straight quarter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0426EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Field-Funk&Wagnalls     05-27 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Field-Funk & Wagnalls,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Field to Acquire Funk & Wagnalls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Field Corp. announced that its Field Publications
affiliate will acquire all of the stock of Funk & Wagnalls Inc., a
major publisher of encyclopedias and other reference books.
   The purchase price was not disclosed, Field spokeswoman Virginia
Butts said Thursday. The New York Times, in today's editions, says
an unnamed industry expert estimated the price at $70 million to
$100 million.
   The transaction is expected to be closed next Tuesday, Butts
said.
   Funk & Wagnalls, based in Ramsey, N.J., is the second-largest
general reference encyclopedia publisher in the United States and
Canada ranked by sales, behind World Book. The company has annual
revenue of around $50 million, according to the Times.
   Funk & Wagnalls' main business is selling mass-market
encyclopedias, yearbooks, family health guides and other reference
books through supermarkets and direct marketing.
   The privately held company is owned by an investment group that
includes its management.
   The acquisition will provide Field with a new means of product
distribution, said Field President Bruce Seide.
   Field Publications, formerly Xerox Education Publications, is
based in Middletown, Conn., and markets publications to schools,
students and individual consumers. Its main products are book clubs
and the 60-year-old Weekly Reader classroom newspaper.
   Chicago-based Field Corp., owned by Marshall Field 5th, bought
its publications affiliate from Xerox Corp. in 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0344EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CableJobs     05-27 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cable Jobs,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cable Study Says Industry A Rising Star</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cable television industry will contribute
about $32 billion to the gross national product during 1988 and
provide some 490,000 jobs, a report commissioned by a cable-related
company says.
   The study was done by Browne, Bortz & Coddington Inc., a Denver
research firm, after being commissioned by Bill Daniels, chairman
of Daniels & Associates, a major cable TV financial services
company based in Denver.
   The study updated a 1986 report prepared by the same company
which also was sponsored by Daniels.
   The cable industry in the United States has continued to grow
rapidly over the past two years with annual revenue now around
$12.8 billion, a 24.3 percent increase since 1986, the report said.
   The industry provides 87,600 direct jobs, and cable-related work
provides an additional 60,000 jobs. Another 340,000 jobs are
created indirectly, according to he report.
   Cable-related employment expanded at a lower rate than either
economic output or employee income during that time, and the report
concluded that ``economic output per employee increased over the
past two years, resulting in fewer employees per dollar of economic
output.''
   The study said cable came of age during the late 1980s with half
of all U.S. households now subscribing to cable service; 75 percent
of the subscribers now have access to 30 or more program channels;
15 percent have access to 54 or more.
   Cable-originated programming makes up almost 40 percent of
viewing in the average cable home, the report said, while viewing
of network-affiliated broadcast stations dropped 12 percent in the
past five years.
   ``Our country is in the midst of a communications revolution,''
Daniels said. ``During this decade, all media and communications
industries grew rapidly, but cable television has been the star
performer.''
   The study said that in revenue terms, cable television ranks
ahead of motion picture box office, radio, home video and broadcast
network advertising.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
