<HEAD>Dollar Up Slightly; Stocks Dip</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended the week marginally higher against
the Japanese yen in Tokyo today, while stock prices dipped for the
second consecutive trading day.
   The dollar closed at 124.64 yen, up 0.14 yen from its finish on
Thursday. It opened at 124.61 yen and moved between 124.58-125.66
yen during the day.
   ``Participants stayed away from making major moves in
anticipation that the United States might raise its official
interest rates to cool the economy, following the announcement of a
higher growth rate for the U.S. gross national product,'' said an
official of a major commercial bank, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   It was reported Thursday that the U.S. gross national product
had grown by 3.9 percent in the first three months of the year, up
from 2.3 percent originally reported.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which slipped a modest 15.41 points Thursday, lost
another 137.75 points, or 0.5 percent, to finish the day's trading
at 27,290.49.
   ``Share prices went down sharply just before the end of the
afternoon session led by profit-taking in pharmaceutical issues,''
said Masahiro Umemori of Nomura Securities, Japan's largest
brokerage.
   The fear of rising inflation in the United States was strong
among investors, he added.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at 1.3 billion shares,
up from the 1.1 billion shares traded Thursday.
   Traders attributed the high volume figure to active trading in
large capital issues, such as heavy industrials and steels.
