<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0740EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-US-CanadaTrade     05-27 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Canada Trade,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Finds U.S.-Canada Trade Pact Would Hurt Some U.S. Industries</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed treaty that would remove most
tariff barriers between the United States and Canada probably would
increase trade between the two countries but leave some U.S.
industries at a competitive disadvantage, a private study says.
   The study by the Northeast-Midwest Institute, a research group
established by members of Congress, found that ``the impact of the
proposed agreement likely would be uneven, with some industries
gaining and others losing.''
   The report, released Thursday, said that the automotive and
textile industries would be the big losers under the treaty, now
being considered by committees in the House and Senate.
   In both the automobile and textile industries, Canadian tariffs
would be retained during a phase-out period stretching up to 10
years, making it harder for U.S. industries to compete, the study
said. The treaty also would allow Canada to establish new barriers
in the textile sector, the study noted.
   On the other hand, the study said, industrial machinery,
electronics and energy-intensive industries in the United States
would benefit from the agreement, in part because of already low
Canadian tariffs or more rapid removal of duties under the treaty.
   ``The stakes are high for Northeastern and Midwestern states,
where about 72 percent of total trade between the two countries
occurs,'' the study said.
   About half the 2 million U.S. jobs that are dependent upon
exports to Canada are located within 12 states, nine of them in the
Northeast-Midwest region, the study said.
   In 1986, Canadian exports to the region totaled $49 billion,
which was about 72 percent of all Canadian shipments to the United
States, the study said. The region exported $33 billion in goods
and services to Canada, representing about 73 percent of all U.S.
shipments to Canada.
   The study found that New England states would benefit from
improved access to cheap Canadian hydroelectric power and a better
chance to compete in the service sector.
   The mid-Atlantic states, New York in particular, would benefit
from lower prices for Canadian raw materials, but would be hurt by
the continuation of Canadian restrictive technical standards for
telecommunications equipment, the study said.
   The Midwest, Michigan in particular, would be hurt by continued
barriers that give Canada a competitive edge in the automotive
industry, the study said. However, lower raw material costs would
increase the manufacturers' ``ability to be price competitive in
world markets,'' the study said.
   The Northeast-Midwest Institute serves senators and
representatives of 18 states: Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois,
Indiana, Iowa, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, Minnesota,
New Hampshire, New Jersey, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Rhode
Island, Vermont and Wisconsin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
