<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UPI-Guild     05-27 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UPI-Guild,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UPI, Wire Service Guild Reach Tentative Agreement on One-Year
Contract</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Press International and the Wire
Service Guild announced that they have reached tentative agreement
on a new, one-year contract, although details of the pact were not
disclosed.
   The proposed pact was reached more than a year after the old
contract expired.
   Kevin Keane, guild administrator and president, said the terms
of the new contact will not be released until after union members
are notified by mail next week.
   The contract is subject to ratification by UPI's guild members.
   UPI Chairman Earl W. Brian said in a statement: ``We are
encouraged by the thrust of the tentative agreement which, if
ratified, would allow UPI to move toward a sound and stable
financial future.''
   The agreement was reached by a new guild negotiating team that
came on after another team quit May 9 in a dispute with the guild's
executive committee, which includes union members from UPI's rival
news service, The Associated Press.
   Job security and maintenance of an agency shop were major issues
in the talks, Keane said.
   The contract covers about 700 editorial and other employees of
UPI, Keane said.
   Negotiations toward a new contract had been carried out over the
course of a year.
   The old contract expired in April 1987. The company declared an
impasse in the talks on Nov. 1, 1987, and imposed the terms of its
own contract proposal, UPI spokesman Christopher Smith said.
   Three months later, operating control of UPI was transferred
from Mexican publisher Mario Vazquez Rana to WNW Group, a media
investment company chaired by Brian, with Paul Steinle as president.
</TEXT>
