<1ST_LINE>r f PM-WritersStrike     05-27 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guild Members Vote On Independent Contracts With 64 Companies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 64 production companies signed
independent contracts with the Writers Guild of America as union
members, claiming they had split management ranks, gathered to
decide whether to accept the agreements.
   Six more producer requests for contracts were turned in to union
officials by Thursday night, when approximately 1,500 guild writers
met at the Hollywood Paladium to cast their votes. East Coast
members of the guild cast ballots Thursday night in New York.
   The results of the voting were to be announced this afternoon,
union spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden said here.
   The 9,000-member guild claimed the contracts effectively split
management ranks among the makers of such hit productions as ``The
Cosby Show'' and ``The Tonight Show.''
   The Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers,
representing the industry's biggest producers, downplayed the
defections, which represent the first significant break in the
12-week strike that has forced delays in the start of the fall TV
season.
   ``We're anticipating ratification,'' Ms. Rhoden said before the
meeting. ``We see it strategically as a good move at this time to
break the logjam with the alliance.''
   Meanwhile, negotiators for both the alliance and the guild
agreed to meet in small groups Saturday and in aother full-dress
bargaining session Tuesday.
   Among the terms in the three-year independent contracts are a 35
percent formula for foreign residuals and greater creative input,
two of the major points of contention with the alliance since the
March 7 walkout.
   The alliance is offering 10.3 percent for foreign residuals,
said spokesman Herb Steinberg. Residuals are the fees paid to
writers when TV shows are rerun or movies reissued.
   The list of 64 production companies released at the meeting
includes the Carsey-Werner Company, which produces two of the most
popular shows on television, ``The Cosby Show'' and its spinoff,
``A Different World.''
   The makers of ``The Tonight Show'' signed a contract and the
producers of ``Late Night with David Letterman'' have agreed to a
contract but haven't signed, said union President George Kirgo.
Among the others to sign were producers of ``Alf,'' ``The Muppets''
and ``Highway to Heaven.''
   Steinberg said none of the 217 major producers that belong to
the alliance has signed independent contracts. Large producers,
whose ranks include Columbia Pictures, MTM and Lorimar, employ 80
percent of the industry's writers and supply 84 percent of
prime-time TV shows, he said.
   ``The alliance producers are holding strong,'' Steinberg said.
``Our objective is to get this town back to work and get everybody
working.''
   He estimated that the independent deals would only re-employ
about 72 writers.
   ``If they're satisfied to put 72 writers to work and leave 4,000
out of work, that's their choice,'' he said.
   ``They have no way to estimate that number,'' Ms. Rhoden
responded. ``They just pulled that out of thin air the way they do
with all of their other figures.''
</TEXT>
