<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UAL-Allegis     05-27 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UAL-Allegis,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forget Allegis; United's Parent Returns To Old Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parent of United Airlines has laid to rest
the ill-fated Allegis episode by dumping that corporate name and
reassuming its old identity, UAL Corp.
   UAL Corp. was UAL Inc. until Feb. 1987, when the company became
Allegis Corp. as part of then-chairman Richard J. Ferris' plan to
turn the airline company into a one-stop travel conglomerate.
   But stockholders didn't buy the concept and a threatened proxy
fight by the firm's largest shareholder, Coniston Partners, forced
Ferris' ouster four months later.
   The company has sold its Westin and Hilton hotel chains, its
Hertz car-rental business and a 50 percent stake in its Apollo
computerized reservations system.
   The shake-up left the Chicago company holding only United
Airlines, half of Apollo and the Allegis name, which shareholders
voted overwhelmingly to change Thursday at the annual meeting.
   ``Our objective in returning to our core business of running an
airline is to grow United Airlines into this nation's pre-eminent
airline,'' UAL Chairman Stephen M. Wolf said Thursday in announcing
plans to purchase up to 60 new Boeing jetliners.
   The name change was to be filed today with the Securities and
Exchange Commission and the company's new stock-exchange ticker
symbol, UAL, becomes effective Tuesday, said spokesman Matt Gonring.
  
