<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 0822EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TelevisedRoots Bjt   05-27 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Televised Roots, Bjt,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researchers Use Tiny Video Camera in Own `Roots' Production</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>URBANA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agricultural researchers are doing their own
production of ``Roots'' by inserting a tiny video camera into the
soil to record the underground development of soybean plants.
   The technique could help scientists understand how various
tillage systems affect crop growth, as well as when and where to
apply fertilizer and pesticide.
   ``I think it will work and it will be an important tool,'' said
Mary Ann Levan, a University of Illinois researcher who worked on
the project with U.S. Department of Agriculture engineers John
Hummel and Ken Sudduth.
   The 1- by 3-inch video camera is guided down clear plastic tubes
inserted in the bean rows and used to record root growth from a few
inches to more than 3 feet below the surface.
   ``It's not very spectacular as movies go, I'm afraid,'' said
Hummel, scanning one tape.
   Depth markers can be read on the inside of the tube, and white
soybean roots can be seen in the earth. Occasionally, an insect
moves into the frame to nibble on a root.
   ``I saw a soybean beetle,'' said Levan. ``The root was very
prominent _ new, large and white _ and there was the worm chewing
through it. It was real clear.''
   The tubes are inserted in the ground at an angle soon after
planting so the soybean crop can be checked throughout the season.
In two previous seasons, the focus has been on perfecting the
technique.
   Without the video equipment, scientists must remove cores of
soil, section them, wash off the dirt and measure roots, Levan
said. That method does not allow observation of the same roots
throughout the season, she said.
   Hummel said the tiny camera actually was designed to inspect the
inside of pipes in nuclear power plants.
   In the UI study, some soybeans being monitored are planted in
undisturbed soil while others are planted after deep, thorough
plowing.
   ``It also should be helpful for fertilizer placement because it
tells you where the active roots are during the growing season,''
said Levan. ``Also, you can observe insects that attack roots and
see when they hatch and where they feed.''
   That might help scientists determine the best time and location
for insecticides, and it should help them compare the results of
various products by watching them work in the soil, the researchers
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0299 </DOCNO>
