<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar held steady in thin European
trading early today. Gold prices fell.
   Traders said market activity was dampened by the absence of many
senior foreign exchange dealers attending a convention in Hawaii.
As well, an approaching long weekend in the major U.S. and British
markets undermined dealers' willingness to take new positions.
   ``It's going to be a day of low business volume and few people
to talk to,'' said a trader with a West German bank in Frankfurt.
   In Tokyo, where trading stops before the start of the European
business day, the U.S. currency closed at 124.64 Japanese yen, up
from 124.50 yen late Thursday. In London trading later today, the
dollar was quoted at 124.70 yen.
   Midmorning dollar rates, compared with late Thursday, included:
1.7090 West German marks, up from 1.7080; 1.4260 Swiss francs, up
from 1.4257; 5.7620 French francs, unchanged; 1.9125 Dutch
guilders, unchanged; 1,268.50 Italian lire, up from 1,268.00, and
1.2380 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2374
   The dollar rose against the British pound, which was quoted at
$1.8592, compared with $1.8625 on Thursday.
   London's major bullion dealers fixed a recommended gold price of
$452.50 a troy ounce, down from $453.30 late Thursday.
   In Zurich, gold was bid at $452.70, down from $454.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, closed at a bid of $454.12, up from
$452.42.
   Silver bullion was quoted in London at a bid of $6.58 a troy
ounce, down from $6.63.
