<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Trade     05-27 0127</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Trade,0134</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Trade Deficit Widens in April</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit widened
sharply to 1.125 billion pounds, or $2.09 billion, in April from a
revised 885 million pounds, or $1.65 billion, in the previous
month, the government said Friday.
   The current account deficit widened to 525 million pounds, or
$977 million, from a revised 285 million pounds, or $530 million,
in March, the Department of Trade and Industry said.
   The current account includes ``invisible trade'' such as
financial transactions.
   The figures were slightly worse than the markets had expected.
Expectations called for a trade deficit of about 1 billion pounds
and a current account deficit of 400 million pounds.
   However, the news had little effect on the stock and foreign
exchange markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
