<HEAD>Stern's To Close Seven Stores In Philly Area, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a two-year effort to crack the
Philadelphia market, Stern's is preparing to throw in the towel and
sell its seven department stores in the city and suburbs, a
published report said today.
   Retailing sources quoted in the Philadelphia Inquirer said
Stern's parent, Toronto-based Campeau Corp., has found a buyer for
the stores and should announce a sale within several weeks. The
buyer was not identified.
   Stern's, a 27-store chain based in Paramus, N.J., moved into the
Philadelphia market in July 1986 by taking over the Gimbels stores
in the area.
   But Stern's has not been able to improve the performance of the
seven former Gimbels, which had sales of $134.2 million in 1985,
according to unidentified trade sources quoted by the newspaper.
   The buyer is expected to be a retailer that caters to a lower-or
moderate-income clientele, possibly a discount chain, the Inquirer
reported.
   Joele Frank, a spokeswoman for Campeau, had no comment on the
report.
