<2ND_LINE>PM-Allegheny International,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court of Appeals Rules on Allegheny Hearing</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP)_ An appeals court has paved the way for an
annual meeting of the struggling Allegheny International Inc., the
subject of a heated proxy fight.
   The ruling Thursday by a panel of the U.S. 3rd Circuit Court of
Appeals upheld a federal District Court ruling and overturned a May
16 ruling by a bankruptcy court, which prohibited the meeting for
90 days.
   Last week, a federal appeals judge temporarily halted the
meeting, originally scheduled for last Friday, until the court
could hear the case.
   Circuit Court Judge Edward Becker did not set a date for the
meeting. But he said, ``It is not suggested that the court lacks
the power to fix the date.''
   The New York investment firm Speer Leeds & Kellog is leading a
proxy fight to gain control of the Pittsburgh company, which
manufactures Oster and Sunbeam appliances, among other consumer
products.
   The dissident shareholders have nominated candidates for seven
of the 13 seats on the board of directors.
   The company is reorganizing under Chapter 11 federal bankruptcy
laws, and unsecured creditors, who claim that a change in
management would delay the company's emergence from bankruptcy
proceedings, have been trying to cancel the proxy vote.
   Company management also opposes the dissidents, claiming they
have no experience in the company's business and no definite plans
for the future.
</TEXT>
