<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Hawaiian-JAL     05-27 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Hawaiian-JAL,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Air Lines Buys into Hawaiian Airlines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japan Air Lines subsidiary has agreed to pay
about $20 million to acquire a 20 percent stake in HAL Inc., the
parent of Hawaiian Airlines, the largest air carrier in Hawaii.
   Pan Pacific Hoteliers Inc. has agreed to purchase newly issued
stock, which will represent up to 20 percent of HAL's outstanding
shares, for $40 per share, HAL Chairman John H. Magoon Jr. said in
a statement issued Thursday.
   The stock purchase is subject to government review. Federal law
limits foreign ownership in U.S. airlines to a maximum of 25
percent.
   PPH does not intended to seek control or to take an active role
in Hawaiian's management, HAL said, but the Japanese group will
gain one seat on HAL's board.
   Pan Pacific Hoteliers is a Hawaii corporation that holds
investments in Hawaii real estate, including hotels and
recreational facilities.
   Hawaiian Airlines operates throughout Hawaii, as well as to the
West Coast, the South Pacific and Guam.
   ``We anticipate that this investment by PPH will strengthen our
growth potential in the Pacific,'' Magoon said. ``It will also
enhance our relationship with Hawaii's fastest growing segment of
the marketplace.''
   The airline posted operating revenues of about $300 million in
1987, making it the 14th largest in the United States.
</TEXT>
