<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EuropeanAirlines     05-27 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-European Airlines,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European Airlines Brace For Lower Profits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major European airlines expect their
profits will fall by about 16 percent this year after a dramatic 93
percent jump in earnings in 1987, the Association of European
Airlines said Friday.
   The AEA, which represents 22 major European carriers, predicted
the combined net profit of its members would fall to about $650
million in 1988 from $775 million last year.
   The airlines' 1987 net profit was up 93 percent over the $400
million reported in 1986, the AEA said in a statement.
   Gross operating profit for the group was expected to fall to
about $1.1 billion this year from a record $1.29 billion in 1987.
   The AEA's forecasts indicate airline profits would return to
1985 levels.
   The AEA said growth in passenger traffic is expected to slow to
about 7 percent this year, from 13 percent in 1987 when traffic
rebounded from a disastrous previous year.
   Traffic growth in 1987 was particularly strong on North Atlantic
routes, which recorded a 19 percent increase. However, the AEA said
traffic on the route would rise only 6 percent this year because of
the weak dollar.
   Seventeen out of the 22 AEA members fly the North Atlantic.
</TEXT>
