<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ComputerTheft     05-27 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Computer Theft,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guilty Plea in Computer Conspiracy Case
^Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computer whiz has pleaded guilty to
conspiring to sell $4 million in stolen supercomputer technology to
the Soviet Union.
   Kevin Anderson of Fremont admitted in federal court on Thursday
he took part in a scheme with three other people to sell the
Soviets plans to a system that allows computers to process as many
as 1 billion instructions per second.
   The technology had a restricted rather than classified status
but could have proved damaging to U.S. security if the Soviets had
received it, according to the government.
   The deal was broken up by government agents who infiltrated the
scheme, U.S. Attorney Joseph Russoniello said when arrests were
made last year.
   Anderson pleaded guilty to conspiring to violate export laws and
wire fraud, based on his use of the telephone to defraud Saxpy
Computer Corp. of Sunnyvale, from which the plans were stolen.
   In exchange, prosecutors dropped about a dozen other charges
against the former software engineer at Synthesized Computer
Systems Inc. in Santa Clara.
   Anderson faces up to 15 years in prison and a fine of up to
$20.3 million at sentencing July 15.
   The plea came two weeks before an extradition hearing in Canada
for Charles McVey, an alleged conspirator in the scheme. He is
being held in Vancouver, British Columbia.
   Ivan-Pierre Batinic, an engineer who once worked fr Saxpy, and
his brother Stevan also were charged in the case.
   According to court documents, Anderson had planned to use an
elaborate money-laundering scheme involving Liechtenstein banks to
set up a computer business in Dublin, Ireland, after completing the
sale to the Soviets.
</TEXT>
