<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   05-27 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened higher on the
Chicago Board of Trade today on buying encouraged by forecasts for
hot, dry weather in the Midwest through the Memorial Day weekend.
   The volatile soybean market, which fell Wednesday and Thursday,
surged at today's opening, with most contracts up more than 12
cents a bushel.
   Wheat also posted strong early gains while corn and oats were
slightly higher.
   Although dry weather poses a real threat to the maturing winter
wheat crop, the runup in soybean, corn and oat prices is largely
speculative since those newly planted crops have not yet developed
enough to sustain damage, analysts said.
   ``I don't think the crops are under stress but the traders are
sure hot,'' said Steve Freed, an analyst in Chicago with the
investment firm Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Recent trading patterns indicate soybean prices will continue to
advance if the weather stays dry, Freed said.
   In early trading, wheat was 3{ cents to 5\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.40\ a bushel; corn was 1} cents
to 2{ cents higher with July at $2.15 a bushel; oats were 2} cents
to 3{ cents higher with July at $1.74 a bushel; soybeans were 8
cents to 13} cents higher with July at $7.66{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were higher in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .02 cent lower to .35 cent higher with June at
72.25 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .05 cent
higher with August at 76.55 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent to
.33 cent higher with June at 53.20 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .20 cent to .75 cent higher with July at 54.15 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Thursday.
