<DOCNO> AP880527-0315 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1202EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-US-Wheat     05-27 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-US-Wheat,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Criticizes U.S. Cuts In Wheat Set-Aside Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community
Commission criticized the United States Friday for cuts in required
wheat set-aside acreage, which will take less land out of
production this year than last.
   ``There seems to be a fairly flagrant contradiction between what
the U.S. claims to do and what it is doing,'' said a Commission
official, who asked not to be named.
   Both the EEC and the United States are using programs to take
land out of production as a way to cut agricultural overproduction.
   The United States had adjusted its support levels for wheat
farmers by announcing earlier this week that they would have to cut
planted acreage by only 10 percent this year in order to qualify
for government subsidies.
   Last year they had been forced to cut acreage by 27.5 percent.
   Each year at this time the U.S. administration announces price
supports and acreage requirements for subsidies under various
programs.
   The EEC spokesman said it remained determined to continue with
its own set-aside programs, calling it unfortunate that Washington
was taking this action so soon before the mid-term review of the
Uruguay round of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade talks
to be held at the end of this year.
   The U.S. administration has called for an end to all
agricultural subsidies in both the United States and the 12-nation
EEC by the year 2000. The trade bloc has criticized the goal as
unrealistic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
