<1ST_LINE>r f BC-PA-Koppers     05-27 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-PA-Koppers,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Summons Beazer, Shearson to Contempt Hearing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British industrialist Brian Beazer and
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. faced a new barrier against their
$1.7-billion hostile bid for Koppers Co. when a federal judge in
Los Angeles on Friday summoned them to a contempt of court hearing
June 6.
   Koppers filed papers Thursday in U.S. District Court in Los
Angeles accusing Beazer and Shearson of violating the court's order
not to proceed with their $60-per-share tender offer.
   Echoing allegations lodged previously in federal court here,
Koppers complained that its suitors have continued to advertise for
shareholder support and extend their tender offer's expiration date.
   Koppers spokeswoman Maggie Cessar said U.S. District Chief Judge
Manuel Real filed the order Friday in Los Angeles.
   The Pittsburgh-based construction materials and chemicals
company previously won federal injunctions in Pittsburgh and Los
Angeles blocking the tender offer on considerations of securities
laws and anti-trust laws respectively.
   U.S. District Chief Judge Maurice Cohill previously scheduled a
June 6 hearing in Pittsburgh to consider alleged violations of
securities laws by BNS Inc., the group headed by Beazer and
Shearson.
   The latest extension of the offer was to expire at midnight
Friday.
   BNS said that as of Wednesday, 19.74 million common shares had
been tendered and not withdrawn and that counting shares it already
owns it could claim 77.6 percent of the shares outstanding.
   BNS also said nearly 107,600 preferred shares, or 71.7 percent
of those outstanding, have been tendered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
