<DOCNO> AP880527-0321 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1345EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Texaco-Icahn 4thLd-Writethru   05-27 0881</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco-Icahn, 4th Ld-Writethru,0909</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco Directors Reject Icahn Offer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 2-3 to CLARIFY directors called contest costly,
battle launched this morning; uppicks 4th graf pvs: In rejecting
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc.'s board today rejected a $60-a-share
buyout offer from takeover artist Carl C. Icahn and denounced the
bid as a pressure tactic.
   The directors also called on Icahn to abandon what they
described as his ``costly and disruptive'' proxy contest, in which
he is seeking five seats on the oil giant's board.
   Icahn launched the proxy battle this morning before the board
formally gathered to consider the offer, which values Texaco at
$14.6 billion. Spokesman Neil Call said Icahn did not want to waste
time and decided to mail ballots for his slate of candidates before
the long Memorial Day weekend began.
   In rejecting the offer, the Texaco board cited a number of
factors they claimed undermined the seriousness of the bid. They
echoed management's sentiments in questioning whether Icahn could
arrange financing and said the 48-hour deadline he imposed on the
offer indicated he was not serious.
   The board said it was confident Texaco's restructuring program
would enhance shareholder value.
   Analysts were skeptical that Texaco's board would approve
Icahn's offer.
   ``I would be flabbergasted if Texaco's board agreed to Icahn's
merger proposal,'' said Michael Young, who follows Texaco for Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   He joined others in suggesting that the offer was doomed from
the beginning and that Icahn, Texaco's largest shareholder, was
fully aware of that.
   Wall Street remained unenthusiastic. Shares in the nation's
third largest oil company eased 50 cents to $49.50 a share in
afternoon trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Texaco and Icahn battled it out in competing full-page ads in
selected newspapers today _ with Texaco asking shareholders if they
can trust the company's future to Icahn, and the takeover
strategist urging them to take up his offer.
   Analysts suggested Icahn's real intention in making the bid was
to push Texaco's stock price up as he continued his war of nerves
against the management of the White Plains, N.Y.-based company.
   Icahn's offer of $60 for each of Texaco's 243 million shares
would value the company at $14.6 billion.
   However, under the offer, he would have to pay out only $12.4
billion for the 207 million shares he does not already own. He paid
an average $34 a share, or about $1.22 billion, for his existing
stake of 36 million shares.
   The combined total of $13.64 billion would amount to the biggest
sum ever paid in a corporate buyout. The previous record was a
$13.4 billion acquisition of Gulf Corp. by Standard Oil Co. of
California, now Chevron Corp., in 1984.
   Texaco President James W. Kinnear, in a statement released
Thursday, reiterated his claim that Icahn's offer was bogus.
   ``There is no basis to believe that Mr. Icahn can arrange the
financing for a transaction of approximately $20 billion _
including the purchase of the shares he doesn't own ... and the
payment of debt and other obligations that would have to be
satisified in connection with his proposal,'' Kinnear said.
   When making the offer on Wednesday, Icahn said he was so sure he
could obtain financing that he would place $100 million in escrow
and forfeit it to Texaco if he failed to get commitments before the
company's annual shareholders meeting next month _ subject to
certain conditions.
   The struggle has been escalating since last fall when Icahn
began building what has become a 14.8 percent stake in Texaco.
   Today, that stake is so large that he cannot sell it quickly _
and collect his profit _ without depressing its price on the market.
   ``I think he wants somebody to bail him out,'' said Cliff
Haigler, an analyst at the securities firm Howard, Weil, Labouisse,
Friedrichs Inc. in Houston.
   Icahn revealed Thursday that Texaco recently found a buyer
willing to pay $50 a share for his stake in the oil company, but he
rejected the offer because it ``smacked of greenmail.''
   Texaco spokesman Peter Maneri said the claim ``is totally untrue
and Mr. Icahn knows it.'' Furthermore, Maneri said that if a
$50-a-share offer had surfaced, ``every indication we have is that
Icahn would have run through a brick wall to accept it.''
   In recent months, Icahn has been pressuring Texaco's management
to take steps to raise the value of the company's stock, if
necessary by breaking it up and selling off the pieces.
   He has backed up the demand by launching a proxy fight to
install himself and four allies on Texaco's 14-seat board.
   Texaco, which emerged last month from a year under bankruptcy
court protection, responded by restoring its $3 annual dividend and
expanding its planned asset sales to $5 billion from $3 billion.
   Wednesday afternoon, company officials broke off three weeks of
peace talks, claiming Icahn was making unreasonable demands for
special treatment in the financial restructuring. An Icahn
spokesman strongly denied the charge.
   A few hours later, Icahn released a letter to Texaco containing
his offer. He also said he would drop his threatened proxy contest
if management would allow the other 211,000 stockholders to
consider the offer at the company's annual meeting next month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0322 </DOCNO>
