<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   05-27 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on London's Stock Exchange settled slightly
lower Friday as the market largely ignored worse-than-expected
British trade figures and chose instead to focus on the long
holiday weekend.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index closed 1.6
points, or 0.09 percent, lower at 1,783.7.
   Volume totaled a slim 346.5 million shares, compared with
Thursday's 435.8 million. Analysts said volume was low on account
of the British bank holiday on Monday.
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit widened to 1.125 billion
pounds, or $2.09 billion, in April, and its current account deficit
widened to 525 million pounds, the government said. Average market
forecasts were for a April trade deficit of around 1 billion pounds
and a current account deficit of 400 million pounds.
   The current account includes ``invisible trade'' including
financial transactions.
   But several analysts said the trade information was not critical
to the equity market.
   ``There was a little bit of a quiver after the trade figures but
then the market took it completely in stride,'' said one analyst.
   Dealers said the only feature in an otherwise quiet, pre-holiday
market were food issues, buoyed by the competing bids for Rowntree
PLC from the two Swiss food giants Nestle SA and Jacobs Suchard AG.
</TEXT>
