<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TunaMerger     05-27 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tuna Merger,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contested Merger Plan Extended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   H.J. Heinz Co. said Friday it had agreed with
Bumble Bee Seafoods Inc. to extend their merger agreement until
June 3 while they consider the Justice Department's opposition to
the deal.
   The government announced Thursday plans to block the proposed
merger of two of the nation's top three canned tuna brands. The
deal would give Heinz half of the nation's canned tuna sales, worth
about $1 billion per year.
   The regulators rejected arguments by Heinz that canned tuna is a
commodity whose price is determined by the world market and that
imports provide adequate competition through their 27 percent share
of domestic sales.
   Heinz already owns top-selling Star-Kist. Bumble Bee of San
Diego is third.
   The Justice Department said the merger could reduce competition
and allow Heinz to hike prices on one of America's most popular
foods.
</TEXT>
