<2ND_LINE>AM-USG-Desert Partners,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USG Says Final Tally Confirms Its Victory in Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Desert Partners LP, waging a hostile $2.2 billion
takeover bid for USG Corp., lost a proxy battle for six seats on
the company's board, USG said Friday in announcing official results
of the vote.
   But the Midland, Texas-based investors group said it was
pressing ahead with its takeover attempt and had extended its
$42-a-share tender offer for 39 million shares until next Friday,
June 3, at 7 p.m. EDT.
   USG released the official results of the contest for six seats
on its board, showing the USG-backed slate. The results were
announced to stockholders Friday at a continuation of USG's annual
meeting, which was originally convened May 11.
   USG said its nominees for the board received 56 percent of the
vote, while Desert Partner's opposition slate of candidates won 41
percent.
   Three percent of the vote was withheld, according to the tally
completed by Corporation Trust Co.
   When USG announced the preliminary results Sunday, showing its
directors had won, officials for Desert Partners vowed to continue
their takeover fight.
   Fred Spar, a spokesman for the partnership, reiterated those
plans Friday.
   Besides extending its tender offer, he said Desert Partners
still was proposing to acquire USG through negotiations in a plan
that calls for giving stockholders a combination of cash,
debentures and stocks that have been valued at $50 a share.
   USG primarily manufactures building materials for the
construction industry.
   Among those elected to the USG board were three of the holding
company's executive vice presidents: Eugene B. Connolly, who also
is president and chief executive officer of the subsidiary USG
Interiors Inc.; A.J. Falvo Jr., president and chief executive of
another subsidiary, United States Gypsum Co.; and William J. White,
president and chief executive of the subsidiary, Masonite Corp.
   The three outside directors elected were James C. Cotting,
chairman, president and chief executive officer of Navistar
International Corp.; Philip C. Jackson, vice chairman of Central
Bank of the South; and John B. Schwemm, chairman and chief
executive of R.R. Donnelley & Sons Co.
</TEXT>
