<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 2023EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OffshoreDrilling     05-27 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Offshore Drilling,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Martinez Asks Government to Delay Drilling Off Keys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bob Martinez asked the federal
government Friday to delay oil and gas drilling off Florida's
southwest coast and the Florida Keys.
   Martinez wrote a letter to Interior Secretary Donald Hodel
asking for more time to study potential environmental damage from
any oil spills before any exploratory drilling is allowed.
   The governor also said he would reject requests for permits to
drill in areas leased by the Interior Department in 1984 and 1985
if such activities threaten the Keys or South Florida.
   ``It is critical that we have a detailed understanding of the
currents in the eastern Gulf (of Mexico) and Straits of Florida to
ensure the protection of the Florida Keys, home of the nation's
only living coral reef and countless other irreplaceable
resources,'' Martinez wrote.
   The only permit request the governor has received so far is from
Union Oil Co. of California, which wants to drill as many as 23
test wells north of the Dry Tortugas, which are west of Key West.
   The Republican governor also wrote a separate letter to
Florida's congressional delegation, vowing to continue discussing
the state's opposition to offshore drilling with officials in the
Reagan administration. He assured them he would take whatever
actions are necessary to protect the Keys and other sensitive
coastal areas.
   The letters dealt with an area south of Naples to just north of
the Dry Tortugas, Marquesas Islands and the Florida Keys, which was
not included in a recent agreement by Hodel to drop leasing plans
for 11 million acres off Florida's coasts.
   It is an area of 73 lease blocks for which Congress ordered a
three-year study before any drilling could be conducted.
   A panel of 30 scientists assembled by Martinez concluded that
the federal environmental research was inadequate and more would be
needed before potential detrimental impacts of such drilling on
Florida's environment and economy could be fully determined.
   Congress did not require any evaluation of the research results
before drilling could be permitted.
   Eighteen of the 19 members of Florida's congressional delegation
have signed a letter to the House Appropriations Committee urging
that a rider be attached to the Interior Department's appropriation
to prohbit the expenditure of any money for leasing or drilling off
Florida's southwest coast, Ms. Whitfield said. Rep. Sam Gibbons,
D-Tampa, declined to sign.
   The governor is concerned about what path an oil spill might
take near the Florida Keys and the impact it might have on the
coral reef, mangroves and other natural resources.
   His panel of scientists reported that existing studies lack
information on where prevailing currents might carry an oil spill
in the eastern Gulf and Straits of Florida.
   Martinez also cited the failure of the federal studies to
address all potential environmental and economic effects on
nearshore and coastal resources.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0335 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 2052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MurrayOhio     05-27 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murray Ohio,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Declines To Block Swedish Takeover Of Murray Ohio</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL RAWLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
refused Friday to block a $197 million takeover bid for Murray Ohio
Manufacturing Co. by AB Electrolux of Sweden.
   A three-judge panel said Electrolux should not be penalized, as
Murray asked, because it had been represented by a New York law
firm that once helped advise Murray on how to fight a takeover.
   The judges agreed that the law firm, Sullivan & Cromwell, had a
conflict of interest, but they noted earlier testimony that no
confidential information from Murray was passed on to Electrolux.
   Electrolux officials learned of the potential conflict of
interest April 28 and switched to another adviser, Smith, Barney &
Harris Upham Co. Inc., the following day.
   The appeals judges upheld a decision Monday by U.S. District
Thomas A. Wiseman, who said he knew of ``no law permitting the
court to enjoin the transfer of stock.''
   Immediately after Wiseman ruled, Electrolux increased its tender
offer from $48 per share, or $182 million, to $52 per share, or
$197 million.
   Murray stock rose 75 cents on the New York Stock Exchange Friday
to close at $60.75 per share, indicating Wall Street expects an
even higher offer.
   Murray officials have asked shareholders not to accept the
tender offer until they have reviewed it. Management promised a
recommendation by June 7, two weeks before the offer was scheduled
to expire.
   Two other lawsuits over the Electrolux bid are pending.
   One, in Chancery Court in Lawrenceburg, Tenn., challenges the
legality of Murray's plan to increase its outstanding stock by 50
percent _ a ``poison pill'' defense designed to make the cost of a
takeover prohibitive.
   Another lawsuit, in Ohio, was filed by Electrolux to challenge
Murray's arguments that an Ohio state law against hostile takeovers
does not apply to Murray. Murray Ohio was incorporated in Ohio in
1919 as an auto parts manufacturer but moved its headquarters to
suburban Brentwood in 1955.
   Murray Ohio manufactures lawn mowers and bicycles at
Lawrenceburg, Tenn.
   AB Electrolux, which has no connection with vacuum cleaner
manufacturer Electrolux Inc. of Marietta, Ga., operates a Tappan
range plant at Springfield, Tenn., north of Nashville.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880527-0336 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 2053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-RedkenBuyout     05-27 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Redken Buyout,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hair Product Firm to Convert to Private Ownership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Redken Laboratories, which manufactures
hypo-allergenic hair and skin products, will convert from public to
private ownership, chief executive officer Paula Kent Meehan
announced.
   Mrs. Meehan, 57, a former actress who founded the firm in as an
answer to her own allergy to hair spray, said Thursday she plans a
tender offer of $34 per share for the roughly 1.4 million shares
she does not already own.
   ``I found it very difficult being a public company,'' said Mrs.
Meehan, whose husband John is chairman and president of the company.
   ``What happens is there is a great deal of short-term thinking
that the analysts and financial community want you to do,'' she
said.``I think we did start to run our company based on quarters
rather than good planning.''
   The Meehans control about 48 percent of Redken stock. There are
2.74 million shares outstanding.
   Redken stock closed at $34 a share in over-the-counter trading
Friday.
   Mrs. Meehan said there is no possibility of a bidding war that
would increase the price of the offer, but she and her husband
refuse to sell their current stock to another party or engage in a
merger.
   Redken products are sold through beauty salons.
   She co-founded the company in 1960 with $3,000. Her partner at
that time, chemist Jheri Redding, sold his interest a short time
later.
</TEXT>
