<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 1726EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-27 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Finish Week On A High Note</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices posted strong gains Friday on the Chicago
Board of Trade in anticipation of a dry Memorial Day weekend. Grain
futures advanced slightly.
   On other markets, gold and silver retreated; livestock and meat
futures were mixed; energy futures were mixed; and stock-index
futures declined.
   Soybeans also were supported by indications the Soviet Union had
purchased soybean meal from both Brazil and Argentina, analysts
said.
   But weather concerns dominated the soybean and grain markets as
they have throughout the unusually dry spring planting period. The
nation's soybean stockpiles are declining and fears of tight
supplies have pushed soybean futures prices to their highest levels
in four years.
   Soybean prices declined on Wednesday and Thursday when rain
entered the weekend weather forecasts. But Friday, most forecasters
were calling for only scattered showers across the northern Plains
and upper Midwest and dry conditions in the rest of the Corn Belt.
   ``The markets got hammered pretty good on Wednesday and
Thursday,'' said Joel Karlin, an analyst in Chicago with Research
Department Inc. ``What we've pretty much done is moved to a level
midway between Thursday's lows and Tuesday's highs.''
   Soybean prices probably will open sharply higher Tuesday if the
long weekend is as hot and dry as expected, analysts said.
   The National Weather Service issued a six-to-10-day outlook
after the close, predicting below-normal rainfall for most of the
Midwest for the second half of next week.
   Wheat settled { cent lower to 3\ cents higher with the contract
for delivery in July at $3.39{ a bushel; corn was 2{ cents to 7
cents higher with July at $2.16{ a bushel; oats were } cent to 1}
cents higher with July at $1.72} a bushel; soybeans were 5 cents to
16{ cents higher with July at $7.68 a bushel.
   Gold and silver futures declined substantially on the Commodity
Exchange in New York in response to the dollar's gains against
other major currencies and on expectations the Federal Reserve was
set to raise its discount interest rate, analysts said.
   Activity was extremely light as many traders got an early start
on the weekend, said Bette Raptoploulos, an analyst in New York
with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The metals declined despite the inflationary effect of higher
soybean prices, but Ms. Raptopoulos said it was not yet clear
whether fears of inflation have finally left the metals markets.
   ``I would say today, perhaps, the inflationary fears diffused,''
she said.
   Gold settled $2.10 to $3.30 lower with June at $450.80 a troy
ounce; silver was 8.4 cents to 8.5 cents lower with July at $6.575
a troy ounce.
   Cattle futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange as
cash prices fell amid slackening wholesale demand. Retailers have
reduced their beef purchases in anticipation of lower demand
following the Memorial Day weekend, analysts said.
   Some traders, eyeing the recent runup in cattle prices, sold on
fears of a repeat of the 1978 market, when cattle prices peaked on
May 30, then fell 15.2 percent by June 22, said Thomas Morgan,
president of Sterling Research Corp. of Arlington Heights, Ill.
   ``There's concern we might be in for that same kind of
pressure,'' he said.
   Pork futures advanced in reaction to a slight decrease in
slaughters, which many feel is a prelude to a seasonal rise in cash
hog prices, Morgan said.
   Live cattle were .23 cent to .70 cent lower with June at 71.92
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .08 cent to .63 cent lower with
August at 76.22 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to .80 cent
higher with June at 53.62 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.30 cent to .92 cent higher with July at 54.32 cents a pound.
   Energy futures finished mixed on the New York Mercantile
Exchange in light trading ahead of the holiday weekend.
   Crude-oil futures were pressured by reports that Iraq's oil
minister, visiting the United States, said his nation had no
intention of reducing oil production, according to Nauman Barakat,
vice-president of energy futures trading for Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 7 cents to 11 cents
lower with July at $17.43 a barrel; heating oil was .26 cent to .41
cent lower with June at 47.78 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.20 cent lower to .20 cent higher with June at 52.55 cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures fell on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
where the contract for June delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
index settled 2.10 points lower at 253.50.
</TEXT>
