<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-27 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up; Gold Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against major foreign currencies
Friday as traders decided U.S. interest rates were likely to rise.
   Gold prices fell in thin trading. Republic National Bank said
gold bullion was bid at $451 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down
from $453.10 an ounce late Thursday.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar was first helped by
strong Japanese buying. It gained further when it went above 1.71
West German marks, a level which had been seen as the upper limit
of its present exchange rate.
   Although the Federal Reserve did not raise the discount rate
Friday, as some traders had expected, many continued to believe the
Fed has tightened credit enough so that U.S. banks will be prompted
to raise their prime rates another notch next week, said Jack
Adkins, a currency analyst for Refco Group in Chicago.
   Expectations of higher U.S. interest rates tend to boost the
dollar by making dollar-denominated investments more attractive.
   In London, the British pound traded late in the day at $1.8570,
down from $1.8625 late Thursday. Later in New York, sterling fell
to $1.8574 from $1.8611.
   The dollar closed at 124.64 Japanese yen in Tokyo, up from
124.50 late Thursday. In later London trading, the dollar was
quoted at 124.82 yen. At the end of the trading day in New York,
the dollar rose to 124.93 yen from 124.58 late Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.7178 West German marks, up from 1.7086; 1.4358
Swiss francs, up from 1.4233; 1.2392 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2364; 5.7770 French francs, up from 5.7565; and 1,273.13 Italian
lire, up from 1,267.75.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.7140 West German marks, up from 1.7080; 1.4305
Swiss francs, up from 1.4257; 5.7660 French francs, up from 5.7620;
1.9177 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9125; 1,270.75 Italian lire, up
from 1,268.00; and 1.2407 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2374.
   In Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid $454.12 a troy ounce, up from
$452.42.
   The late bid price for gold bullion in London was $452 a troy
ounce, down from $453.30 late Thursday. In Zurich, gold was bid at
$452.50, down from $454.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery was bid at $450.80 a troy ounce, down from $454.10 late
Thursday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $6.59 a troy
ounce, down from $6.63. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery fell to $6.530 a troy ounce from $6.610 late
Thursday.
</TEXT>
