<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ResortsInternational 1stLd-Writethru f02erearethepitchingprobables
05-27 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Resorts International, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0298,0350</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 6th graf, ``The agreement calls,'' to CORRECT to $160
million, sted $195 million.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Griffin, Trump Sign Firm Agreement for Sale of Hotel-Casino
Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The on-again, off-again deal between Donald
Trump and Merv Griffin to split up hotel-casino operator Resorts
International was officially sealed Friday, the millionaire
entrepreneurs announced.
   Griffin, the TV talk-show host turned investor, will pay
approximately $300 million for the Atlantic City, N.J., company
controlled by New York developer Trump, the men said.
   Using his profits from the deal and other funds, Trump will buy
back the company's unfinished crown jewel, the vast Taj Mahal
casino in Atlantic City, for $230 million.
   ``It looks like this is it,'' said Robert S. Trump, Donald's
brother and executive vice president of The Trump Organization, in
a telephone interview from New York. ``We are pleased, as I think
Mr. Griffin is pleased.''
   The agreement, in contrast to a handshake deal that collapsed
May 11 amid mutual recriminations, is definitive, Robert Trump said.
   The agreement calls for Trump, Resorts' chairman, to get a total
of $160 million _ $135 a share, or about $100 million, for his
Class B shares, and $60 million to terminate his management
contract. The Class B shares, which carry special voting rights,
give him 88 percent control of the company.
   In addition, Griffin, through Griffin Co., agreed to pay
approximately $200 million, or $36 a share, for all the company's
common stock, Robert Trump said.
   Trump agreed to pay $230 million for the Taj Mahal, a grandiose
project plagued by construction delays, and certain other assets.
That purchase is subject to certain closing adjustments, Robert
Trump said.
   Griffin first offered to buy Resorts on March 17 for $35 a share.
   After weeks of sparring, the men in April announced an agreement
nearly identical to the one closed Friday, only to cancel it a
month later, with Trump accusing Griffin of failing to line up
financing and Griffin accusing Trump of seeking last-minute changes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
